<HEAD><TITLE> GA-086 ANIMAL FEED ADDITIVES: TECHNOLOGIES AND
MARKETS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2> GA-086 ANIMAL FEED ADDITIVES: TECHNOLOGIES AND
MARKETS
 </H2>
<HR><P>
<I>CHARLES FORMAN </I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B>

<P>Animal feed additives are an important factor in the U.S. and world food
business and markets.  Without feed additives, the U.S feed animal grower would
be unable to grow economically the food-producing animals which supply a
large percentage of the protein consumed in this country.  Thus, this study is
basically one about nutrition, well being, and rapid, healthy, and economic
growth of farm livestock mammals. Specifically, it is concerned with feed
additives, that is, chemical materials that are added to animal feeds.</P>

<P>In this study BCC presents the technical and business background for the
manufacture, formulation, and sale of feed additives for the three most
important classes of farm animals (cattle, poultry, and swine.) Primary emphasis
is on markets in the U.S., but we also note and discuss some important
international aspects of feed additives supply, especially as it affects suppliers
and markets in the U.S.</P> 


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B>

<P>The business and markets for animal feed additives are large and diverse.  The
technology of animal feed additives is constantly changing, as both supplier
companies and those who grow food-producing animals strive to make
production more efficient.  The market is dynamic, as the search goes on for
new products to substitute for some which cause concern among people both
in government and the general public.</P>

<P>BCC performed this study to provide a comprehensive reference for those
interested and/or involved in these products. This comprises wide and varied
group of chemical and other companies which make and supply feed
additives, farmers and farm business groups, process technology and
equipment designers and marketers, politicians of all stripes, and the general
public. We have sorted through and condensed information from a large
amount of literature and other reference materials to compile this report.</P>



<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B>

<P>This report is intended to assist those involved in several different segments of the
animal feed additives industry.  These organizations and people include those
who are involved in the development, formulation, manufacture, sale, and use
of these products.  These include agricultural research personnel, product
development experts, animal husbandry experts, process and product
designers, purchasing agents, construction and operating personnel, market
staff, and top management. BCC feels that this report will be of great value to
technical and business personnel in the following areas, among others:</P>

<UL>
<LI>Farmers and farm nutrition groups.

<LI>Companies involved in the design and construction of plants to
    manufacture feed additives and components.

<LI>Organizations involved in basic and applied  animal husbandry and
    feeding.

<LI>Financial institutions that supply money for these facilities.

<LI>Personnel in  government at many levels, from the country animal
    control and feed agent/expert, to the state agricultural department,
    to the USDA and other federal agencies, the politicians who must pass
    the legislation which regulates and controls food and feed additives,
    and finally the environmental and other regulators who must
    implement and enforce the laws.
</UL>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B>

<P>This study covers the technological, economic, political, and environmental
considerations in the U.S. feed additives industry.  It is primarily a study of U.S.
markets, but because of the global nature of agriculture it touches on some
noteworthy international activities; these are primarily those which can have an
impact on the U.S. market.</P>  

<P>All market forecasts are given in constant 1994 dollars and growth rates are all
compounded. All market values are rounded to the nearest million dollars.
Because of rounding, some growth rates may not agree exactly with figures in
the market tables.</P>

<P>This report in segmented into twelve sections, of which this is the first.  Our 
definitions and organization of feed additives roughly parallel those of the
Animal Health Institute (AHI), the leading U.S. trade group in this field. We devote
separate sections to the three principal types of animal feed additives. The
other sections in this report are summarized below.</P>

<P>Section II, the Summary, encapsulates our findings and conclusions, and
includes the summary major market table.  It is the place where the busy
executive can find the major findings of the study in summary format.</P>

<P>Section III is an overview to animal husbandry in the U.S., with some trends and
statistics regarding the production of the three main types of farm livestock:
cattle, poultry, and swine. Animal nutrition and nutritional requirements are
discussed.</P>

<P>Section IV is an introduction to feed additives and a discussion of classification
systems and the three primary classes of feed additives covered in this study.</P>

<P>Section V is the first of our three sections which discuss and analyze the markets
for feed additives.  Section V is devoted to feed additives for disease prevention
and control. These are true medicinal chemicals, and include anticoccidials,
anthelmintics (worm treatments), and other additives that prevent diseases and
conditions which harm the animal or hinder its growth.</P> 

<P>Section VI is devoted to growth promoters, those feed additives which make the
animal grow faster and healthier; they are also often called "performance feed
additives."  They are primarily antibiotics, which are added to animal feeds at
subtherapeutic levels to promote growth rather than to prevent or treat disease.
We discuss both hormones and nonhormonal growth promoters.</P>

<P>Section VII covers the other, and largest, major feed additive category, that of
nutritional feed additives.  These include amino acids, macrominerals, trace
elements, vitamins, and some others.</P>

<P>Section VIII briefly discusses some important international aspects of animal feed
additives. These include noting some key foreign suppliers and the import and
export of feed additives and components into and out of the U.S.</P>

<P>Section IX is devoted to the structure of the feed additives industry, along with
some important marketing, technological, and competitive aspects of the
business.</P> 

<P>Section X covers important environmental, public policy, and government
regulatory considerations, including federal and state regulations and public
perceptions and opinions of feed additives.</P>


<P>Section XI consists of profiles of many of the companies which are leading the
way in the manufacture of animal feed additives.  These include several major
pharmaceutical and chemical companies as well as a number of smaller, often
private firms which supply smaller, often single-product, segments of the total
market.</P>

<P>Section XII is an appendix which lists and defines some of the more important
terms, abbreviations, and acronyms used in the animal husbandry and feed
additives industry.</P> 

<P>Beyond the scope of this study are many products which are sometimes added
to animal feeds, but which are not considered feed additives in the sense
ordinarily understood and used in the industry. These include:</P>

<UL>
    <LI>Animal feeds and feedstuffs themselves, basically feed
        grains.  These are products of a large U.S. market (over $30
        billion) which supplies bulk feeds for farm animals.

    <LI>Agents which are used therapeutically to cure disease
        which has already infected the animal.  The only exceptions
        are the disease-preventing additives in Section V, which
        prevent infection by parasites such as Coddicia.  Thus we
        exclude an antibiotic injected to cure bovine mastitis as well
        as all injectable vaccines.

    <LI>Animal insecticides, some of which are administered in feeds
        to kill larvae in animal feces.

    <LI>Growth-promoting hormones which are not added directly
        to feeds but are instead injected, implanted, or otherwise
        administered.

    <LI>So-called "energy" feed additives.  These are usually
        non\protein nitrogen sources such as urea and ammonium
        nitrate, and are more feedstuffs themselves than are feed
        additives.

    <LI>Auxiliary compounds which are added to feedstuffs to make
        them last longer, handle better, or taste better. These
        include antioxidants and other preservatives, flavors,
        formulation aids such as free-flow agents and emulsifiers,
        and pelletizing agents. Many of them are the same
        additives used in human foods, and are regulated similarly. 
</UL>
<P>Our scope is further narrowed to farm food-producing animals raised in large
numbers in the U.S. There are only three such large classes grown in this country:
beef (both dairy cattle and beef cattle raised for slaughter), poultry (chickens
and turkeys), and swine.  Other farm animals which are major food sources in
other countries, such as goats and sheep, are not as important in the United
States.</P>

<P>BCC's focus on farm animals raised for food production thus also excludes
aquaculture, all pets, horses, and other exotics such as zoo animals. These are
large and separate markets of their own, such as the $5 billion-plus U.S. market
for pet foods.</P> 

<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B>

<P>Searches were made of the literature, including many of the leading trade
publications, and well as technical compendia and government publications. 
Product and market information was obtained whenever possible from the
companies involved.  The information for our corporate profiles was obtained
primarily from the companies themselves, especially the larger publicly owned
firms.  Other sources included directories and articles.</P>


<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B> 

<P>Other BCC reports and newsletters which may be of interest include:</P>

<UL>
<LI>GA-054: Applied Biology & Biotechnology for Livestock
<LI>GA-080B: Vitamins, Minerals, Proteins and Amino Acids for Animal Health
Applied Genetics News
Food Ingredient News
</UL>

<B>DISCLAIMER</B>

<P>The author assumes no responsibility for the information in this report or for its use. 
All material in the report is intended to be as reliable as possible, and was
gathered, analyzed, and written in a professional manner. The author assumes
no liability for any loss or damage which may result from any reliance on any
materials or information developed and presented in the report.  This report is
not a legal or accounting document and much of the information developed
and presented is of a speculative nature.</P>




