<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GA-087: FLAVOR TRENDS & DEVELOPMENTS: 
BEVERAGES, ETHNIC & FAT-REDUCED FOODS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GA-087: FLAVOR TRENDS & DEVELOPMENTS: 
BEVERAGES, ETHNIC & FAT-REDUCED FOODS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Dorothy Kroll
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The flavor industry is seeing increasing demand from processors of
three types of products: beverages, ethnic prepared foods and fat-
reduced prepared foods. These products satisfy growing consumer
demand for new and different taste experiences, and for healthful
products that minimize health risks associated with major disorders
or even provide health benefits.<P>  

In addition to these products growing in sales, the importance of
flavors is mounting as processors use them as key marketing tools
to out-pace the competition.  In some cases, flavors have been
responsible for breathing new life into beverage categories that
were lagging in consumer interest and sales, such as milk which has
evolved into a new type of beverage - the flavored milk.<P>  

Flavors give taste and can be functional. Some flavors impart only
their special flavors when used individually or in some type of
blend, combination or system.  However, suppliers have been
actively developing other types of flavors that satisfy various
processor needs as well. Flavors may now provide mouthfeel and
texture; give the flavor of fats, oils, sauteed and fried fats;
reduce the amount and type of ingredient used so that cost and fat
content can be lowered; and provide choices by making the flavors
in both natural and synthetic forms.<P> 

With these technological advances in flavors as well as in flavor
delivery systems, flavor houses have been able to help processors
use new flavors in new types of products as consumer interests and
preferences change.  Moreover, new types of products are being
marketed more readily because major food companies are acquiring
niche beverage, ethnic and fat-reduced food makers, thereby making
possible national distribution to large supermarkets for greater
consumer exposure.<P> 

Flavors for beverages, for example, are changing because consumers
are moving away from sweet flavors to more cool, refreshing flavors
in all types of beverages.  The flavors once found only in a soft
drink may now be found in a hot or iced drink. Flavor suppliers
have a range and diversity of flavors for beverages that rival
other types of products such as frozen desserts.<P>   

In addition to new flavors being continually developed, there are
new beverages being developed that need flavors as well as flavors
being used for the first time in long-standing. existing beverages.
At one time the special domain of niche beverage makers, the giant
processors have begun to use flavor as a main attraction. Beverages
using flavors include various new age, fruit juice, hot, iced,
dairy-based, soft and sports drinks.<P>

Flavors for ethnic prepared foods are seeing a growing market
because different types of products are no longer considered
specialty items, but mass market items. Flavors can be  the same
flavor used in any type of product or especially adapted for a
specific ethnic product, and/or Western tastes.<P> 

Like beverages, there are new types of ethnic groups offering their
products to nonethnic consumers through niche marketers.  As
consumer demand grows for the newer food types, processors
interested in entering the market rely more heavily on flavor
suppliers to help them develop unfamiliar ethnic tastes. Examples
of ethnic products include Italian, Mexican, and various Asian
ethnic groups.<P>

Flavors for fat-reduced foods are often required to do more than
give flavor to products, and supply some of the properties of fat
that provide both flavor and mouthfeel. With many processors
anxious to make fat-reduced versions of full-fat products, and in
the same range of flavors, flavor suppliers try to develop flavors
that work in any type of fat-reduced product.  Moreover, the
flavors have to work with other types of ingredients, such as fat
replacers.<P> 

The aim of flavor and product development is to provide consumers
with equal choices for full-fat and fat-reduced foods. Without the
choices, health-minded consumers may leave the food category, or
those who have left may never return.  Some examples of fat-reduced
products are dairy and baked goods, snacks, condiments,
meat/poultry products, candy/confections, granola cereals, and
nutrition bars.<P>


<b>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

This report is designed to achieve the following objectives:
To discuss the trends and developments among flavor types that are
enabling food and beverage makers to flavor key marketing tools to
attract consumers.<P>

To describe the trends and developments within each product type
that are spurring demand for flavors.<P>

To suggest the market size for each flavor type as influenced by
the types of applications in which each is used.<P>

To analyze the structure of the flavor industry, the market
influences and driving forces affecting flavor development, and how
flavor houses are responding to manufacturers' needs for flavors.<P>


<b>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

BCC seeks to provide insight into one key question:  With which
types of flavors can suppliers best satisfy the needs of food and
beverage makers so that they can satisfy myriad consumer demands?<P>

The report examines each product type in terms of existing and
newer versions in order to demonstrate the changing flavor needs of
food and beverage makers.<P>

The report presents each type of flavor in order to show how it is
being used, or not being used,  in each type of product.<P>

The report discusses the interests and needs of consumers and how
they shape choices in flavors demanded in their foods and
beverages.<P>

The report analyzes why certain types of flavors may be having fast
sales growth as they respond to varying processor needs, and why
other types of flavors may be having slower growth.<P>    


<b>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

Each product type is described, and then how each type of flavor is
used in those products. Trends in niche marketing, the use of
natural and synthetic flavors, and various other consumer and
manufacturing trends are discussed in terms of their impact on the
choice of flavors made by food and beverage processors.<P>


<b>METHODOLOGIES</B><P>

Sales estimates and projections for each type of flavor as they are
used in each of the three product groups are presented. Estimates
and projections were developed from such factors as width of the
range of applicability, sales growth of each product type,
perceived health and safety concerns by consumers for each product
type,  and various technological and manufacturing trends that
facilitate flavor development and usage for the different products.<P>



<b>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC first conducted an extensive review of the secondary
literature, consisting of materials gathered from trade journals
and magazines, company materials, trade and professional
associations and government and industry sources. Following that,
some one hundred telephone interviews were conducted with personnel
in technical, marketing and sales departments of large and small
flavor houses.<P>

