<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE> GA-088: SHELF LIFE TECHNOLOGY FOR
                       PROCESSED FOODS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2> GA-088: SHELF LIFE TECHNOLOGY FOR
                       PROCESSED </H2>
<HR><P>
<I>DOROTHY KROLL </I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B>

<P>Consumers want fresh, quality processed foods and beverages.
Processors want their products to maintain the same quality
during transport and storage as when they left the plant. With
this extended shelf life, processors can have longer production
runs, more shipping time, and less wastage. </P> 

<P>These twin desires were traditionally met with chemical
preservatives that fought against oxidation, degradation and
contamination.  However, in recent years consumers have been
demanding a reduction in the use of chemicals in their foods and
beverages because they fear that they can pose health risks.</P>  

<P>In response, processors have been looking at alternative
technologies that will preserve the freshness, flavor, texture
and nutrient value of their products from the time they leave the
plant until cooking and consumption in the home by the consumer.</P> 

<P>Adding to the importance of extending shelf life is the range of
new types of products that are being developed in response to
consumer interests and preferences. There are reduced fat,
calorie, sugar and salt products that can have shorter shelf
lives through reduction of certain ingredients. There are
fortified foods and drinks that meet the needs of health-minded
consumers and use nutrients which can be lost during processing
and/or pose flavor problems.  Then there are the plethora of
microwaveable products that fit the hectic work-play lifestyles
of many consumers but have short cooking cycles that can affect
product quality.</P>

<P>The alternative technologies being considered by processors are
different types of preservatives, modified atmosphere packaging
(MAP) that could provide barrier properties and therefore
eliminate the use of preservatives, and encapsulation which
protects ingredients through their shelf life so that there is no
loss in functionality.</P>

<P>Preservatives include antioxidants which prevent foods from
becoming rancid, and antimicrobials which protect foods against
microrganisms. Antioxidants work in foods containing fats and
oils and prevent the oxidation that produces rancidity that
causes loss of flavor, color, nutrient value and texture. 
Antioxidants include BHA, BHT, TBHQ, PG, sulfites, tocopherols,
ascorbic acid/salts, erythorbic acid/salts, and substances with
preservative properties such as spices/herbs, essential oils,
citric acid and phosphoric acid.</P>
 
<P>Antimicrobials ensure food safety by inhibiting the growth of
mold, yeast or bacteria which not only cause deterioration of
products but also can cause health problems for consumers.
Antimicrobials include sulfites, sorbates, propionates,
benzoates, parabens, nitrites, natamycin, nisin, and those with
antimicrobial properties such as BHA, BHT, spices/herbs,
essential oils, citric acid, lactic acid, acetic acid, phosphates
and medium chain fatty acids.</P>

<P>MAP is a type of packaging, created with special equipment and
materials, that can protect foods by controlling oxygen and
keeping them safe without the use of preservatives. 
Encapsulation is a method that creates a coating or shell around
an ingredient that, if left unprotected, would jeopardize the
product's quality. The encapsulated ingredient maintains its
integrity throughout its shelf life, and until consumption by the
consumer. The types of problems that encapsulation prevents are
degradation of ingredients, interaction of ingredients, premature
flavor release, and unpleasant flavors spoiling product flavor.</P>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B>

<P>This report is designed to achieve the following objectives:</P>

<P>To discuss the trends and developments among the various shelf
life technologies that are helping food and beverage makers
deliver non-rancid, safe foods to consumers.</P>

<P>To describe the trends and developments within each type of shelf
life technology that seeks to respond to the needs of processors as they, in
turn, seek to satisfy the interests and needs of consumers.</P>


<P>To suggest the market size for each shelf life technology as
influenced by its level of functionality, price, and range of
applicability. </P>

<P>To analyze the structure of the shelf life technology industry,
the market influences and driving forces that affect usage of
specific methods, and how suppliers are responding to processors'
needs to find new ways to extend shelf life.</P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B>

<P>BCC seeks to provide insight into one key question:  With which
technologies can suppliers best help processors extend shelf life
as they seek to meet consumer demands for healthful and varied
processed products?</P>

<P>The report examines each shelf life technology and the various
types that make up each category in terms of current and future
trends and developments.</P>

<P>The report presents each type of shelf life technology in order
to show how it is or isn't being used, and in what types of
applications, possible motivators or limiting factors on usage.</P>

<P>The report discusses the market influences that shape consumer
attitudes toward certain shelf life technologies, and how these
attitudes then create certain demands from processors as to what
should or shouldn't be done to extend shelf life or their
products.</P>

<P>The report analyzes why certain shelf life technologies are
enjoying good growth  while others are experiencing slower
growth, taking into account such factors as functionality and
price differentials.</P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B>

<P>Each shelf life technology is described, and then the various
types of additives, materials, equipment or ingredients that are
included in each technology. The various types of preservatives
are discussed, as are the materials and equipment needed to
create MAPs, and the various types of ingredients that can be
encapsulated.</P>


<B>METHODOLOGIES</B>

<P>Sales estimates and projections for each type of shelf life
technology are presented. Estimates and projections were
developed from such factors as the range of applicability,
functionality, price, health and safety concerns on the part of
consumers and processors, and market, technological and
regulatory factors affecting each technology.</P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B>

<P>BCC first conducted an extensive review of the secondary
literature, consisting of materials gathered from trade journals
and magazines, company and product literature, trade and
professional associations and government and industry sources.
Subsequently, some 100 telephone interviews were conducted with
personnel in technical, marketing and sales departments of the
various types of suppliers involved in shelf life technologies.</P>



