<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GA-094 PROTEIN INGREDIENTS IN FOODS: A WESTERN EUROPEAN PERSPECTIVE
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GA-094 PROTEIN INGREDIENTS IN FOODS: A WESTERN EUROPEAN
PERSPECTIVE
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>ANTHONY REDVERSE-MUTTON</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>


<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>


This report sets out to assess the present market for protein ingredients in the 17 Western
European 
countries and to analyze potential progress over the course of the next five years.  The countries
for which 
statistical data is provided are:<P>

<UL>
  <LI>The United Kingdom
 
  <LI>Germany
 
  <LI>France
 
  <LI>Italy
 
  <LI>The Benelux countries (Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg)
 
  <LI>The Iberian Peninsula (Spain and Portugal)
 
  <LI>Other Western European countries (Sweden, Denmark, Norway, Finland, 
Switzerland, Austria, Greece and the Republic of Ireland.
</UL>



The base year for statistics shown in this report is 1995 and estimates are provided for 1996 and
forecasts 
for 1998 and 2000.<P>

In the context of this report, protein ingredients are defined as products obtained from plant or
vegetable, 
animal and microbial sources, used to impart nutritional value to a wide range of foods.  They are
the 
sources of all the amino acids, required as a basis for healthy diets.  They also have functional 
characteristics that influence the texture and taste of many different types of foodstuffs.  The main
protein 
ingredients used in food applications in Western Europe comprise the following:<P>

<UL>
  <LI>Soy flour
  <LI>Soy concentrates
  <LI>Soy isolates
  <LI>Textured soy protein
  <LI>Wheat gluten
  <LI>Pea
  <LI>Faba bean
  <LI>Casein
  <LI>Caseinates
  <LI>Whey
  <LI>Egg whites
  <LI>Egg yolks
  <LI>Fish proteins
  <LI>Yeasts
</UL>


<B>SCOPE</B><P>

In this report, the economics, technological advances, legislative controls and end-use
requirements 
relating to the various types of protein ingredients will be analyzed in the light of positive and
negative 
influences.<P>

This report examines the usage of protein ingredients in five major sectors of the retail food
industry in 
Western Europe, namely:<P>




<UL>
  <LI>Bakery products
  <LI>Meat and meat products
  <LI>Dairy products and desserts
  <LI>Specialty foods
  <LI>Pet foods
  <LI>Other foods (sauces, dressings, soups, etc.)
</UL>

Developments in these sectors will be analyzed and potential growth or otherwise assessed over
the next 
half decade.  The effects of any movement in these sectors on protein ingredient consumption will
be 
calculated as will changing demands brought about by European legislation or variations in
national 
requirements.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

The views, opinions and expertise of a representative selection of producers and end-users have
been 
analyzed in the compilation of this report in order to help project the future development of
protein 
ingredients in Western Europe.  Technical books, trade magazines and journals have been studied,
as have 
projections by economic, political and financial organizations, relating to the industrial growth and 
stability of the individual European countries during the course of the next five years.<P>  

Financial data contained in this report is, where relevant, shown in the local currency of the
individual 
countries as well as in U.S. dollars.  Exchange rates used for currency conversion are shown in
Appendix 
1 at the end of this report.<P>

The findings and projections expressed herein represent our best assessment of future trends in the
light of 
current developments.<P>

During the course of this report, certain words, phrases or abbreviations may occur that, in some
respects, 
are peculiar to the food and protein ingredients industries.  Appendix 2 at the end of this report
provides 
an explanation for some of the words or terms utilized.<P>

Note:     This report measures the weights in tonnes, not tons.  A tonne is a metric ton
          or 1,000 kg (2,240 lbs.).<P>


<B>BCC ON-LINE SERVICES</B><P>

<B>INTERNET</B><P>

Now you can locate the hard-to-find information you need on the Internet's World Wide Web.  By 
directing your browser to Business Communications Co.'s new "home page" you will be able
to:<P>

  Examine our complete catalog of Business Opportunity Reports and order 
directly from BCC.<P>

  Subscribe to any of our more than 20 monthly technology/marketing 
newsletters.<P>

  Read announcements of recently published reports and newly launched 
newsletters.<P>

  Register for BCC's well-known conferences.<P>

  Request additional information about any BCC product.<P>

  Take advantage of special offers.<P>

To reach this important new information resource, go to http/www.buscom.com<P>


<B>Direct Access</B><P>

Direct access to BCC on-line is achieved by calling (203) 866-9534.<P>













