<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
B-101  THE U.S. HEALTHCARE DELIVERY SYSTEM IN THE YEAR 2000 OPPORTUNITIES FOR SUPPLIERS, GOODS AND SERVICES</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>B-101  THE U.S. HEALTHCARE DELIVERY SYSTEM IN THE YEAR 2000 OPPORTUNITIES FOR SUPPLIERS, GOODS AND SERVICES</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>BARBARA BRIENDEL</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This study, Viewpoints Of The U.S. Health Care System In The Year
2000uOpportunities For Supplies, Goods and Services, was undertaken
to provide the reader with a definitive review of the chances that
are under way in the U.S. health care delivery system, and an
assessment of the system and the changing needs that will emerge by
the year 2000. Since the majority of American health care
consumers, health care professionals, industry suppliers, insurers
and reimbursement organizations consider the current system 'out of
control', it is an indisputable fact that modifications will occur.
As a result, many new opportunities will be created. It is the goal
of this study to describe the current health care delivery system,
to keynote potential changes while emphasizing composition,
structure, and dynamics. Since most participants and market
observers agree on the overwhelming nature of this goal, we at BCC
have focused on specific market aspects. These particular
objectives include providing information on the significant
segments that deliver goods, products and services that are
susceptible to change, and the resultant opportunities that will
emerge. It is these opportunities that are the major objective of
this report.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

The United States health care delivery system is nearly an $800
billion industry, representing 14% of the Gross Domestic Product
(GDP). It grew at an estimated rate of twice that of inflation
during the 1980s with no sign of slowing through the next decade
The system is under attack for being too costly and is accused of
not being capable of providing equal care to all citizens,
particularly denying care to the growing number of people without
health insurance and those not eligible for Medicaid.<P>

There is little disagreement that the health care delivery system
will be forced to change, but what type of change will occur is
open to debate. The political arena, particularly in this election
year, has entered the fray Observers of Congress report that
approximately sixty various proposals for some form of universal
health insurance or cost containment methods for providing more
equal care at lower costs are coming before Congress. The consensus
of many industry observers is that some form of a universal health
care plan will be enacted, but who will pay and how many changes
will be implemented are unknown. BCC's goal is to identify all
potential changes and to analyze the most probable evolution of the
industry and to identify  specific opportunities resulting from
these changes.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This study provides information in the following areas:<P>

<UL><LI> U.S. health care delivery system infrastructure<BR>
<LI> Number and distribution of professional service providers,
     medical facilities and dispensing sites, and products<BR>
<LI> Funding and financing vehicles within the system<BR>
<LI> Role of technology and its impact on the health care delivery
     system<BR>
<LI> Foreign health care delivery programs<BR>
<LI> Innovative programs and significant trends<BR>
<LI> Viewpoints of health care industry participants and observers<BR>
<LI> Emerging opportunities</UL><P>

Since the study is oriented to provide information on
opportunities, as well as market data, it will prove to be of
particular value to current industry participants and companies
anticipating entry into the health care delivery market. Readers
who should find benefits within the study are corporate executive
officers, corporate managers, industry planners, new product
developers, government liaison executives, industry analysts,
investors and venture capitalists.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This study encompasses a description of the current health care
delivery system and the system that will probably evolve by the
year 2000, including professional service providers, facilities and
dispensing sites, and the products/services market. Also included
is a discussion of funding and financing of the system and current
health care delivery practices. Selected programs existing in
various states and foreign countries are also described. The report
includes proposed programs as well as viewpoints expressed by
industry participants and observers of the probable components of
the future American health care delivery system. Significant within
the report is a section detailing future opportunities for health
care goods, services and products.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

The changing nature of the current health care delivery market
caused BCC to develop an innovative methodology for this study that
would be capable of detecting the latest, up-to-the minute changes,
as well as the detection of emerging opportunities. Consequently,
the primary methodology of this report was the collection and
analysis of opinions held by various market participants and
observers as to what they envision the U. S. health care delivery
system will be in the year 2000. The major portion of this
information was derived from telephone and personal interviews with
individuals in the forefront of the health care delivery system.
This data, combined with data from secondary sources and from BCC's
extensive data bank on this subject, was analyzed by BCC staff
members with numerous experiences in the medical marketplace.
Findings and forecasts were confirmed with industry experts.<P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Interviews were conducted with physicians, hospital administrators,
government personnel, insurers, professional organization
representatives and lobbyists, pharmaceutical company executives,
medical products company executives, health care planners and
university academicians. Further information was obtained through
an extensive literature search.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

The BCC project director on this report is an analyst with advanced
marketing degrees and with extensive experience in the health care
delivery industry. Among the other BCC studies published by this
analyst are reports on medical diagnostic kits, the blood industry,
microorganism testing systems, gene probe markets, medical
diagnostic equipment, biocompatible materials, bioengineered
protein drugs, new drug delivery systems, skin, wound and hair care
products and the laser industry.<P>



