<H1 ALIGN=center>CO47N CANCER TREATMENT AND DIAGNOSTIC

PRODUCTS</H1>

<I> <H3 ALIGN=center>ANNA CRULL/GERIANN PARK</H3> </I>



<H2 ALIGN=center>INTRODUCTION</H2>



<H3>GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</H3>



<P>This BCC, Inc. technical/marketing report analyzes the segment of the cancer

industry that provides products for therapy and diagnosis.  Market forecasts are

provided for chemotherapeutic agents, hormone therapies, biological therapies, radio-

pharmaceuticals, electromedical diagnostic devices, and cancer detection products. 

The report provides a general overview of common types of cancer products; discusses

both commercial agents and those in development; summarizes the federal

regulations affecting these products; describes the major players in industry; and

suggests where research and development is headed.</P>





<H3>PURPOSE OF THIS REPORT</H3>



<P>This report provides the reader with insight into the direction of the cancer

industry.  From this report, the reader should be equipped to identify business

opportunities, be familiar with the major players, and be knowledgeable about the

advances in therapy and diagnosis.</P>



<P>This BCC, Inc. study is intended for those who require a business-oriented

overview of this area of medical research.  The report is designed for those who desire

to learn the new and developing areas of cancer research and those who are

interested in exploring opportunities for commercialization.  The report will be of

value to manufacturers of drugs, diagnostics, and medical devices; marketing

directors and strategic planners; investors; and companies interested in entering or

expanding their involvement in the cancer industry.</P>





<H3>SCOPE AND FORMAT</H3>



<P>As the population ages, the market for products that diagnose and treat cancer

increases.  At the same time, new technologies, especially those from the

biotechnology industry, are being developed that will revolutionize the cancer

industry.  This updated BCC, Inc. study analyzes the sales of products for cancer and

suggests new trends and directions for research and development.  This report

provides information about drugs, diagnostics, medical devices, and their markets, as

well as companies, government agencies, and universities involved in cancer product

development.  Certain company profiles feature specific product information.</P>



<P>Although in practice diagnosis precedes therapy, BCC approaches the market

sectors in order of importance to the industry.  Diagnostic products experience slower

growth and keener competition, while therapeutic agents enjoy the glory.  This

observation may explain why diagnostic agents have been dubbed the "stepchild" of

the large therapeutics sector.  Nevertheless, diagnostic products are an important

constituent of the market.</P>  



<P>The report begins with an overview of the four modalities of cancer therapy: 

surgery, radiation therapy, chemotherapy, and biological therapy.  After reviewing

federal regulations, the report analyzes the markets for chemical anticancer drugs,

biological products, and radiation therapy.  Then, diagnostic products are described. 

The leading companies are profiled in a separate chapter.</P>  



<P>Values of the market in this report are for the year given, represent sales by

companies in the marketplace, and are for the United States only.  Projections are in

terms of real dollars and represent real growth.  Competition from other drugs or

diagnostics plays a role in the success or failure of these agents.  The values are

generally based on the best estimates of those involved in the commercialization of

the techniques.</P>



<P>Products that are not of therapeutic benefit to the patient, such as pain relievers

and artificial limbs, are not included in the market analysis.  Accordingly, costs due

to surgery, including the technique of bone marrow transplantation, are not

considered in this report.</P>



<P>Many believe that the manipulation of genetic information holds the key to

products that will diagnose, treat, and prevent cancer.  Highlighted in this report are

new and developing technologies, many of which are the brainchildren of the

expanding biotechnology industry.  This emphasis suggests the advances in store for

the cancer industry.</P>





<H3>METHODOLOGY</H3>



<P>Research for this report began with an in-depth analysis of technical and

business literature, as well as a review of the history of the diagnosis and treatment

of cancer.  Interviews with industry experts, federal government representatives,

company representatives, and university scientists provided the basis for an

assessment of the outlook for the anticancer industry.</P>









<H3>DISCLAIMER</H3>



<P>This report is of a professional nature and has every intent at accuracy.  It is not

to be considered an endorsement of any product described.  Nor is it intended to

constitute a legal or accounting document.  Neither the analyst, project manager,

typist, nor the publisher assumes any liability for loss or damage as a result of

reliance on this material.</P>





<H3>RELATED BCC PUBLICATIONS</H3>



<P>This report focuses on cancer products.  BCC also has published C139 "Brain

Diseases & Disorders:  Diagnostics & Treatment Products," C170 "Emerging Markets

for AIDS & AIDS-Related Infections," C141 "Immune Diseases:  Advances in

Diagnosis & Treatment Products," and C177 "New Therapeutics & Diagnostics for

Women's Disorders."</P>



<P>Other BCC reports of potential interest to the reader include C143

"Biotechnology in the 1990's:  Taking Stock," C160 "Human Gene Therapy: 

Technology Analysis & Market Forecast," C072 "New Horizons in the Pharmaceutical

Industry," C088RR "Dynamic Antibody Industry Including Polyclonals &

Monoclonals," C164 "Immunoassays:  Markets, Technology & Patent Survey," C102

"Plant-Derived Chemicals," C117 "Protein Manufacture," C056R "Amino Acids

Products & Technology," C147RB "The Enzymes Outlook for Specialty & Medical

Applications," C186 "Polysaccharides," C020BR "Antioxidants:  Markets, Materials,

Trends," and C144 "Reagents for Biotechnology."  A complete list of related BCC

reports can be found inside the back cover.</P>  



<P>In addition, certain monthly BCC newsletters cover cancer-related products. 

Examples of such newsletters are "Medical Material News" and "Applied Genetics

News."</P> 





