<CENTER><H2>C-050N: DRUG DELIVERY SYSTEMS:
NEW DEVELOPMENTS,
NEW TECHNOLOGIES    
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Howard Kibbel
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

This technical/marketing study has been prepared as an in-depth analysis to 
forecast and track the significant advances in the advanced alternative drug 
delivery systems market.  Many of these advances include the development of 
systems based on novel delivery technologies that offer near-term impact on 
the pharmaceutical industry, while other systems based on emerging delivery 
technologies are just beginning to be understood and will not make their way 
to the marketplace until 1998 or later.<P>

As a result of the benefits derived from using the newer drug delivery 
systems, the advanced alternative drug delivery segment of the U.S. 
pharmaceutical industry continues to grow significantly and to encroach on 
conventional means of drug delivery.  This segment is attracting the attention 
of researchers involved in the development of new chemical entities for the 
delivery of precise, controlled dosages to specific locations.  Interest in 
this segment has broadened as physicians and patients become increasingly 
aware of the economic, therapeutic and social benefits of controlling the rate 
and duration of an active ingredient.<P>  

<b>HISTORY OF THE MARKET</B><P>

The concept of advanced alternative drug delivery systems, especially those 
that offer a sustained, controlled release action targeted to a desired area 
of effect has had great appeal for nearly half a century.  However, prior to 
the advent of improved alternative delivery methods, drug delivery systems 
were considered only as a means of "getting the drug into the patient."  
Actual practice of controlled release began with the applying of timed release 
coatings to pills or solid drug particles in order to mask their taste and 
make them more palatable.<P> 

Between the late 1940s and early 1960s, the concept of chemical 
microencapsulation technology began to generate considerable interest as an 
alternate means of delivering drugs.  New uses of this technology are being 
derived from continued research into the chemistry of polymer entrapment.<P>  

In the continued quest for more refined systems, in the 1980s, 
polymer/membrane technology came to the forefront as alternative drug delivery 
systems entered a new phase of development with the introduction of 
transdermal drug delivery systems. This passive technique continues to 
experience high growth and carve out a specialty niche within the 
pharmaceutical industry.  Advances on this technology include more active 
techniques, such as electroporation, iontophoresis and sonophoresis, that use 
either low electrical currents or ultrasound to deliver drugs through the 
skin.  Similar, upcoming active techniques are pulsed or self-regulated 
delivery systems that can be adjusted to a patient's biological rhythms.<P> 

Expect researchers to refine further the process of targeting site-specific 
delivery with pinpoint accuracy, by attaching drugs to liposomes, bioerodible 
polymer implants and monoclonal antibodies.  Emerging technologies have 
brought many developmental advanced alternative systems from the realm of 
theory to either commercialization or near-commercialization.  These systems 
include hydrogels, microsponges, mucoadhesives, cyclodextrins, erythrocyte 
ghosts, encapsulated cells, self-regulated devices and enzyme-mediated 
devices.<P> 

<b>SCOPE OF THIS REPORT</B><P>

The scope of this report includes a comprehensive analysis of trends and 
economic indicators that affect the U.S. advanced alternative drug delivery 
systems industry. This report focuses on the present status of this industry 
and both quantifies and qualifies market information on it.  Its scope 
includes discussion of the following items:<P> 
                                                                                                    
<LI> What are the major systems now in use?<P>

<LI>  What technologies will be developed and marketed in the
     near-term?...the next five years?...the next decade?<P>

<LI>  What are these technologies and what companies (drug 
     or non-drug) are working with them?<P>

<LI>  What drug companies will market products incorporating
     these new drug delivery techniques?<P>

<LI>  How will these systems impact on present drugs and the 
     structure of the pharmaceutical marketplace?<P>

  <LI>   What are the benefits and limitations of each technology?<P>

<LI>  What components go into these drug delivery systems?<P>

<LI>   Who are the major suppliers of components and raw materials?<P>



<b>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

This research results from extensive primary and secondary research, with much 
of the information being gathered through telephone interviews with leading 
pharmaceutical and drug delivery systems market participants, drug 
reformulators, academic researchers and pharmaceutical industry observers, as 
well as government and professional agencies and academic researchers.  The 
balance of the information comes from an on-line data search of available 
government, trade and technical publications relating to this topic, including 
literature on licensing agreements, company activities, patents and state-of-
the-art technologies.<P> 

Projections are given for the mid-term potential of various alternative drug 
delivery systems.  These projections are in terms of 1993 constant dollars, 
including the predictions for the 1993-98 time period.  The average annual 
growth rates conform to the convention for significant figures.  Where precise 
information was not forthcoming, a consensus was made, using a formulation of 
reasonable assumptions and estimates based on a baseline obtained from 
historical data.  The specific demographic area covered by the projections is 
the U.S.<P> 

<b>VALUE OF THIS REPORT</B><P>

This comprehensive technical/marketing study will be of particular interest to 
senior technical and marketing personnel and corporate and product planners 
within the pharmaceutical industry.  The report will be also be of value to 
investment analysts, investors and venture capitalists.<P> 


<b>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

Current information on some portions of drug delivery systems are covered on a 
monthly basis by BCC, Inc. in its newsletters:  "Applied Genetic News" and 
"High Tech Separation News."  Other related BCC reports that may be of 
interest include the following:<P> 

<UL>    C-010X    -    Advanced Controlled Delivery Technology<BR>
     C-181     -    New Strategies for Drug Marketing<BR>
     C-177     -    New Therapeutics & Diagnostics for Women's Disorders<BR>
     C-68R     -    Inert Ingredients for Drugs - Update<BR>
     C-170     -    Emerging Markets for Drugs & Vaccines for AIDS and Related Infections<BR>
     C-088R    -    The Dynamic Monoclonal & Polyclonal Antibody Business<BR>
     C-088S    -    Review of Manufacturing Technologies for 
                         Antibodies<BR>
     C-160     -    Human Gene Therapy<BR>
     GB-159    -    Intravenous Therapy Products<P></UL>

