<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-020BR ANTIOXIDANTS: MARKETS, MATERIALS, TRENDS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-020BR ANTIOXIDANTS: MARKETS, MATERIALS, TRENDS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>PHILIP ROTHEIM
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>OBJECTIVES AND GOALS OF STUDY</B><P>

The objectives of this study are threefold:<P>

<UL> <LI> To qualitatively identify the inert ingredients of drugs,
      not just conceivable ones but the ones actually being used,
      and not just in tablets but in all dosage forms.<P>

<LI> To quantify the consumption of inert ingredients, not
      merely in terms of preferences but in terms of pounds and
      dollars.<P>

 <LI> To communicate the issues driving the consumption of inert
      ingredients in drugs and shaping new directions in the
      types of inert ingredients.</UL><P>

<B>REASONS FOR STUDY AND ITS CONTRIBUTION</B><P>

  Most technical-business studies on drugs focus on the active
  therapeutic agents of medications, but very little attention
  is ever paid to the inert ingredients that actually make those
  medications possible.  Yet, inert ingredients are critically
  important, since they create the dosage forms and provide
  other specific benefits.  This study therefore seeks to shed
  light on a "hidden" topic of importance to drugs.<P>

  The present study updates a previously published report done
  several years ago.  In the intervening years, we also
  published a study addressing a more specialized aspect of
  inert ingredients.  At the time of their publication, these
  previous studies appeared to be the only ones of their kind
  estimating the quantities of inert ingredients consumption.
  We believe we continue to be unique with the present study.<P>

  Being the only published study attempting to quantify inert
  ingredients has a risk because comparisons cannot be made.
  However, we have received feedback from our earlier studies
  allowing us to make refinements for the present one, and for
  this study we obtained new data and information, as well as
  "helpful hints," allowing us to improve on our earlier
  efforts.  The result is this updated, expanded and more
  refined study.<P>

 <B> REPORT AUDIENCE</B><P>

  This study is intended for business managers, strategic
  planners, marketers, product managers, and sales executives.
  It is not a text on drug formulation and this study is not
  intended to serve formulation scientists.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND CONTENT</B><P>

  This study covers inert ingredients for drugs.  Drugs are
  defined as products requiring clinical trials and FDA approval
  for marketing. This study quantifies inert ingredients for
  drugs formulated in the U.S.  Products formulated outside the
  U.S. and marketed here (or elsewhere) are excluded; the U.S.
  includes all 50 states and, for the purpose of this study, we
  include Puerto Rico.  Drugs formulated in the U.S. and sold
  outside the country are included.<P>

  This study encompasses inert ingredients principally for
  conventional drugs and it covers all conventional dosage
  forms: oral solids (including tablets, capsules and other),
  oral liquids, topicals (including dermal, ophthalmic and
  otic), injectables, respiratories, suppositories and other
  conventional forms.  The following advanced forms of drug
  delivery are excluded: transdermal patches, implantables, oral
  delivery of peptide drugs, and other delivery forms generally
  regarded as advanced.  Inert ingredients for advanced dosage
  forms will be covered in a separate study.<P>

  This study includes only inert ingredients intended to be in
  and part of the final, formulated drug compositions, e.g.
  fillers, vehicles, and performance-related substances.  It
  excludes process aid chemicals that help the drug formulation
  process but which do not appear in the final compositions
  (e.g. wet granulation solvents).<P>

  This study includes prescription and nonprescription (OTC)
  drugs, but  considers only orthodox drugs and excludes
  cosmaceuticals, nutraceuticals, and herbal medicines. Also
  excluded from consideration are personal care products,
  cosmetics and toiletries.  The study excludes veterinary
  drugs.<P>

  This study analyzes inert ingredients in drugs only in the
  aggregate aspects, with regard to chemical types and by types
  of dosage forms served.  We do not analyze inert ingredients
  by specific therapeutic drug class and we do not consider
  individual products and brands.<P>

  In the instances when a substance serves as an inert
  ingredient in some products and as an active ingredient in
  other products, we consider only the inert ingredient use.  In
  the instances when a substance simultaneously serves as active
  and inert ingredient, we do not consider it (but do consider
  the other inert ingredients in the formulation).<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

  This study is the product of only three man-months of effort.
  Much of the information, data and insights come from telephone
  interviews with ingredient suppliers, generally involving
  product and sales managers as well as technical staff.  We
  also had telephone interviews with drug manufacturers,
  contract formulators and ingredient semiformulators.  In all,
  we directly interviewed about fifty people.<P>

  This study also made use of secondary information, including
  product literature from ingredient suppliers, technical papers
  written by pharmacy and formulation experts, and various
  professional magazine articles written by people knowledgeable
  about the subject.   We also made use of the major
  professional and scientific texts in this field.<P>

  In instances where data were lacking, we made estimates of our
  own and checked them for "reasonableness" by seeking
  concordances between quantities of dosage forms in their
  entirety and quantities of ingredient categories.<P>

  All analyses of inert ingredients consumption refer to the
  domestic U.S. only.  Quantities of solid materials are
  expressed in lbs., quantities of liquids in gallons (with
  conversions to lbs., based on density), and quantities of
  solutions in lbs. of dry substances.  Dollar values are stated
  for products  and grades ready and suitable for pharmaceutical
  use, and generally refer to the supplier level directly in
  contact with formulators.  Values are expressed in millions,
  where l MM lbs. = one million pounds and $l MM = $l million.
  Forecasts of sales to 1998 are expressed in constant 1993
  dollars to reflect real changes without inflation, and the
  AAGR is the average annual (compounded) growth rate, derived
  using standard tables of present value.<P>

  Product brand names are indicated in capital letters.
  Mentions of products are not endorsements and omissions, if
  any, are not intentional.  All analyses are made
  independently, without the bias of vested interests.<P>


<B>PERSONNEL FOR STUDY</B><P>

  The writer of this report is a chemist-biochemist who also has
  an M.B.A. degree in marketing.  He has experience in both the
  food and pharmaceutical industries as a research scientist and
  as a technical-business advisor to executive management.<P>

  At BCC, the writer has done many studies on chemical and
  medical subjects. He is the Director of Biotechnology and
  Healthcare, and Editor of Applied Genetics News.  He has had
  many occasions to provide custom consultation on behalf of
  both large and small companies, which has included repeat
  business.  The writer is a member of the American Chemical
  Society and has presented talks at many professional
  conferences.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>

  Other reports by the writer, or those done by others, that
  relate to the present topic include:<P>

<UL>           C-050R: New Drug Delivery Systems<BR>
           C-068: Inert Ingredients for Drugs (first
  publication)<BR>
           C-069: Chemicals for Cosmetics and Toiletries<BR>
           C-135: New Directions in Pharma Tablet Manufacture<P></UL>

