<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE> C-072 NEW HORIZONS IN THE PHARMACEUTICAL    
INDUSTRY</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">

<CENTER><H2>C-072 NEW HORIZONS IN THE PHARMACEUTICAL    
INDUSTRY</H2>

<HR><P>

<I> Valeria Scioscioli</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST<P>


 <H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>


 <B> STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This report was written to piece together, in a comprehensive
fashion, the emerging directions of all the major forces
shaping the evolution of the industry, namely, new discoveries,
domestic and international competition and competitiveness,
economics, science, demographic changes and the public sector,
along with their reciprocal feedbacks. These will shape also
the strategies of the major actors in the 1990s and beyond.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B>

<P>The report was written to fill a void: most studies of the
industry focus on new chemical entities in the market or in the
pipeline, and on their potential sales in the U.S., given an
existing demand. While NCEs and their potential demand are
important, they do not exhaust all the forces acting on the
industry's environment; therefore, they provide no guide for
strategic planning, nor do they reveal new opportunities.</P>


<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B>

<P>The business executive will find in this report a detailed
summary of the global environment of the pharmaceutical
industry and its future implications.  We put in first place
the forthcoming unification of europe with its unified science
policy, regulationS and markets.  In this context, we stress
the importance of both domestic and cross-border competition
(i.e., joint ventures in r&d and marketing).  At the same time,
we give great emphasis to research, insofar as discoveries
create markets.  The information presented together will lead
directly to the strategies of the dominant companies, whose
foundations can be summarized as follows: a) being the first to
exploit new discoveries and technologies and to build around
them national and international research, marketing and
distribution networks able to exploit economies of scale and
scope;  b) diversifying across all segments of the industry
while shedding unrelated operations in other industries;  c)
keep "reinventing" existing business, for instance, by looking
for new uses of existing drugs.  In this respect, it is
remarkable that some old drugs are being found useful for
diseases they were not originally meant to cure.</P>

<P>Although we stress the links among the major components of the
industry's environment, every effort was made that the reader
with specific interests in individual sectors or fields of
research can meet these in individual chapters without any loss
of information.</P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B>

<P>This very comprehensive report begins with an examination of
the economic structure of the american drug industry and
continues with a presentation of the biotechnology segment.
This innovative segment of the drug industry is presented at
greater length in all relevant aspects:  R&D, the role of
biotechnology within the traditional sector of the industry,
and the specific research on the major diseases present and
future drugs are meant to treat (heart disease, cancer, nervous
disorders, AIDS, diabetes, and others).  In each case, market
forecasts are provided, based on both trends of the disease
incidence of the diseases in the general population, and on
expected drug price inflation.</P>

<P>The public sector, a major presence in the industry, is
presented in all the roles it plays through the FDA, the patent
system and as a purchaser of drugs. the generics and OTC
markets are presented separately for the different roles they
play in the industry.  This is followed by a profile of
consumers and the different products different age groups
require.</P>

<P>Finally, the dominant foreign markets -- primarily, the EC and
japan -- are presented at length, along with the major moving
forces within them: patent systems, rules and regulations,
mergers and cooperative research. as mentioned, the EC receives
greater attention for the historic events taking place there.
the report ends with a brief description of the dominant
american companies.</P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B>

<P>Forecasts of individual markets, and of the pharmaceutical
market as a whole, are based on trends, which in turn are
premised on the assumption that the age-specific incidence of
the individual diseases will remain unchanged through the
present decade.  Changes in demand will then be affected most
by age shifts in the general population. expected price growth
of the drugs is applied to the affected population in order to
calculate sales' growth through the year 2000.  It is our
contention that growth in prices rather than in demand will
continue to drive the growth in drugs' sales.</P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B>

<P>The report is based largely on two different sources:
information on emerging drugs and on their therapeutic
potential from medical and pharmacology literature; industry
economics figures from trade literature and other sources.</P>

<B>RELATED BUSINESS COMMUNICATIONS WORK CREDENTIALS</B>

<P>Previous business communications reports from the same author
include studies on engineered foods, the dairy industry and on
"grey markets" for an aging america.</P>


 







                          













