<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-135 NEW DIRECTION IN PHARMACEUTICAL TABLET MANUFACTURE
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-135 NEW DIRECTION IN PHARMACEUTICAL TABLET MANUFACTURE</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>PHILIP ROTHEIM</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>REASONS FOR STUDY</B><P>

Pharmaceutical manufacture is an important enterprise in the U.S.
and other industrialized countries, and oral tablet manufacture is
the most significant of all because more drugs are made as tablets
than any other dosage form.  Tablet manufacture has significance to
pharmaceutical firms, ingredient suppliers, the medical community
and patients, as well as health authorities and others concerned
with healthcare.<P>

The way tablets are manufactured has been undergoing change in
recent years and is likely to head in new directions.  As a
consequence, the requirements for inert ingredients used in tablet
manufacture, in particular the requirements for tablet binders and
processing-aid solvents used in wet granulation, are undergoing
change as well.  For business reasons, it is essential to grasp the
nature of the forces for change and their significance to the
future, especially for ingredient suppliers who wish to stay in the
game.<P>

<B>OBJECTIVES AND GOALS</B><P>

The objectives of this study are to:  (a) Shed light on the forces
for change in oral tablet manufacture, especially wet granulation;
(b) Forecast directions of change over the next five years; and (c)
Quantify materials requirements for tablet binders and
processing-aid solvents used in tablet manufacture, especially in
wet granulation tableting.  The goals are to provide useful
insights for the management of change and to identify emerging
business opportunities.<P>

<B>AUDIENCE FOR REPORT</B><P>

Readers of this report  are expected to be senior business managers
with decision-making responsibilities, having position titles such
as strategic planning, new business development, marketing and
product managing; the writing is geared to this type of audience.
Although the study contains some technical discussions, scientists
will find this report of only limited value and for them we suggest
various scientific texts on drug formulation.  Our technical
discussions are not intended to go into depth but to bring out
insights constructive for business purposes.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF STUDY TO BUSINESS INTERESTS</B><P>

Few publications address the manufacture of tablets and ingredients
requirements for tablet manufacture from a business perspective.
As far as we are aware, this is the only published market study to
deal with the subject of tablet manufacture and, in particular,
tablet binders and process-aid tableting solvents.  Moreover, as
far as we are aware, this is the first and, so far, only published
study to deal with the subject quantitatively.  Other market
studies address only the sales of formulated, finished drugs and
often include tablet sales, but they do not shed light on sales of
inert ingredients for drug formulation or on tablet binders and
process-aid solvents in particular.  Scientific publications
typically address only the art and science of drug formulation and
the physical-chemical and performance characteristics of tableting
materials but not the business aspects.  This study's contribution
is to fill the information gap with respect to business interests.<P>

The writing of a first or only publication on any subject always
raises the issue of not having other publications to compare it
with.  In some respects the publication is a breakthrough, while at
the same time it engenders uncertainty as to the validity of data
and their meaning.  Compounding the issue is that, as outside
analysts, we are not privy to all the data that may exist within
pharmaceutical and ingredient supply firms.  In the particular
instance of this study, readers may be able to supplement our data,
analyses and insights with information known only to them and thus
use this publication simply as a guide.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT OF REPORT</B><P>

After the introduction and summary, this report opens with an
overview of pharmaceuticalS and tablets.  It discusses the major
types of dosage forms, details tablets and describes BCC's
forecasting scenario as it relates to the future of tablet binders
and solvents.<P>

Next is a description and analysis of tablet manufacturing
technologies and major trends in manufacture.  Issues affecting
tablet manufacture directly relate to business prospects for tablet
binders and tableting solvents.<P>

Third, we discuss the industry structure for tablet binders AND
solventS.  This section includes industry participants, business
dynamics, major driving forces for future directions and
international aspects.<P>

Fourth is a brief description of government regulations and their
influences on tablet manufacture and materials requirements.<P>

Fifth is a section on markets for tablet binders.  This section
includes technical and accounting definitions of tablet binders,
and a comprehensive examination of tablet binders from various
perspectives.  This section includes a first-time-ever quantified
analysis of the market size for tablet binders, with market
segmentations.<P>

Sixth is a section on markets for tableting solvents.  The issue of
process-aid solvents in tablet manufacture is a major one, and our
discussion illuminates this timely subject, with full quantifying
of market sizes.<P>

Seventh is a section providing selected company profiles.  They
were selected as representative of various aspects of materials
supply industry structure.<P>

Finally, this report has three appendices:  the survey
questionnaire used in this study, a directory of tablet binder and
solvent suppliers, and a list of technical and trade information
sources.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

The basis of this study is a previously published BCC study, done
by the analyst, on "Inert Ingredients For Drugs."  That study
covered the whole, broad subject of inert ingredients including
bulkers and fillers, vehicles and bases, manufacturing aids and
specialty additives used for U.S. manufacture of all common dosage
forms, including oral, topical, injectable, nasal, otic, ophthalmic
and insertable.  That study was the first ever published to address
drug inert ingredients from the business viewpoint and the first to
comprehensively attempt to quantify amounts of consumption and
dollar sales of those materials.<P>

That study examined the totality of materials usage in drugs, but
it did not break down the functional performance roles of materials
serving multiple purposes, nor did it break down material uses by
dosage form, for materials serving multiple types of dosage forms.
Therefore, to do this study on tablet binders and wet granulation
solvents took a special effort.  This entire study is the result of
four man-months of effort, fully half of which addressed just the
quantification of binders and solvents.<P>

A unique feature of this study is a survey of drug formulators.  A
total of forty subjects representing a cross-section of U.S. drug
firms were asked a set of questions designed to bring out
information on current practices, future directions and feelings
toward material suppliers and their products.<P>

<B>CREDENTIALS AND RELATED BCC STUDIES</B><P>

The analyst for this study is a chemist-biochemist also holding an
MBA in marketing, who has many years of experience in industry,
first as a bench researcher, then as an advisor to executive
management on business opportunities and, finally, as a
market-industry analyst with BCC.  Among the analyst's many
published BCC studies are:  Inert Ingredients For Drugs,
Stereoselective Chemical Technology Emphasizing Chiral Technology,
Monoclonal & Polyclonal Antibodies, Medical Anti-Infective Agents,
Specialty Enzymes & Advanced Enzyme Technologies, Cancer Diagnostic
& Treatment Products, Bioengineered Medical Proteins, Plant-Derived
Chemicals, Biohazard (Toxicology) Testing, Medical Diagnostic Kits,
New Drug Delivery Systems, Vaccines & Antiviral Drugs, Sexually
Transmitted Diseases, and Strategic Analysis of the Diagnostic
Reagents Industry.  The analyst has extensive experience providing
professional consultations to technical-business management of
major corporations.<P>

BCC is an established market research and market analysis firm with
expertise in the fields of health, biotechnology, plastics, metals,
ceramics, organic chemicals, electronics, membranes,
communications, food, agriculture, and waste treatment, among
others.  The firm has a reput`ti 	
