<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-139  BRAIN DISEASES AND DISORDERS: DIAGNOSTIC
AND TREATMENT PRODUCTS</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-139  BRAIN DISEASES AND DISORDERS: DIAGNOSTIC
AND TREATMENT PRODUCTS</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>PHILIP ROTHEIM</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The goal of this study is to assess the impact of new technologies
on sales of neuroproducts over the next five years and beyond.  The
objective is to help executive managers plan for the future.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR STUDY AND ITS CONTRIBUTION</B><P>

Medical product data services ably provide information on where
companies have arrived in the market as a result of decisions made
in the past.  Rarely do they delve into the information and
insights needed to navigate and implement the future.  Neuromedical
products now receive prominence as a consequence of the 1990s being
hailed as "The Decade of the Brain."  What products should be
developed?  What products can be developed?  What do new
technologies have to offer?  What will product sales likely be five
years from now and beyond, and who will receive the revenues?  What
can be done now to get in on a rising tide?  What areas are more
problematic and are to be viewed more as long-term?<P>

This report's contribution is to take a forward look at
developments now in progress and being implemented in the
neuromedical arena.  Not only data but also analyses, insights and
explorations of critical issues are provided.  In a time when
resources have to be rationed, there can be little substitute for
this kind of forward "thinking."  Excitement over new developments
is tempered here by a rational examination of all dimensions.<P>

<B>AUDIENCE FOR REPORT</B><P>

Readers of this study are expected to be business managers and
scientists interested in business.  This report is specifically
geared to address the job functions of strategic planning, new
business development, marketing, product management and research
management.  Investment analysts should also find this report of
value.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND CONTENT</B><P>

This report is a business study and not a science or medical text.
Emphasis is on new and future developments, and not on the past.
The focus of this study is the central nervous system, and
peripheral system agents are barely discussed.  Historical sales
analyses include current dollars, constant dollars and constant
dollars per unit population.  Present and projected sales refer to
the United States, but this study has some important demographic
analyses for other countries.  The study goes to great length to
shed light on issues and forces shaping the neuroproducts market
and neuroproduct supply.  Forecasts are reasoned and explained, not
just stated, and possibilities for commercial failure are
considered as much as the opportunities for commercial success.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

This study results from three man-months of research and
concentrated effort to gather all relevant and timely information
on the subject.  Primary sources of information were scientists,
physicians, psychiatrists and business managers of many sorts, who
were interviewed by telephone.  Secondary sources were copious
technical and business literature gathered from scientific
publications, government publications and companies, as well as our
in-house computerized literature search capabilities and current
awareness newsletters such as Applied Genetics News.  Original
contributions by the author, and critical assumptions, are
explained in the text.<P>

Sales figures are expressed in U.S. millions of dollars ($1 million
= $1 MM = $1,000,000).  In general, they refer to U.S. sales and
consider only the manufacturer-level.  Projections to 1995 are
expressed in constant 1990 dollars to reflect real changes without
inflation, and assume constant prices.  The five-year average
annual growth rate (AAGR) is derived by the compounding method
using standard tables of net present value.<P>

BCC and the analyst have no vested interest in any company or
product mentioned in this report.  All analyses and forecasts are
made independently and without bias.  Omissions of company names or
products, if any, are unintentional.  Medical opinions are the
expressions of others.<P>

<B>CREDENTIALS AND RELATED WORK</B><P>

The writer of this study is a biochemist and M.B.A., with previous
experience in the pharmaceutical industry.  Among his published
studies in the biomedical field are:  Cancer Diagnostic and
Treatment Products, Medical Anti-Infectives, Toxicology,
Bioengineered Medical Proteins, New Forms of Drug Delivery, STDs,
Inert Ingredients For Drugs, Materials for Tablet Manufacture, and
Protein Manufacturing Technologies.  Other related BCC studies, by
others, include Blood Industry, Medical Diagnostic Kits, Drug Abuse
and Monitoring Reagents, New Horizons In Pharmaceuticals,
Diagnostics and Treatments For Immune Diseases, and Non- and Semi-
Invasive Surgery.<P>


