<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-170  EMERGING MARKETS FOR DRUGS & VACCINES FOR AIDS AND
AIDS-RELATED INFECTIONS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-170  EMERGING MARKETS FOR DRUGS & VACCINES FOR AIDS AND
AIDS-RELATED INFECTIONS</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>BARBARA BREINDEL</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The market for vaccines and drugs for AIDS and AIDS-associated diseases is an
explosive one which will have a significant impact on the pharmaceutical
industry.  Although the disease incidence and the related market is not of the
magnitude of those for illnesses such as heart disease, the market is
nevertheless still significant. Various vaccines and innovative drugs are
under development with great potential for treating and, perhaps, preventing
AIDS.  The goal and objectives of this study are to fully describe the current
and future status of this market segment and its dynamics, and to forecast
market size through the year 2000.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

AIDS infection within the U.S. population is reaching devastating levels.
Approximately 242,000 Americans have been diagnosed as HIV positive.   A
cumulative 160,000 have already died from AIDS. Projections by the World
Health Organization forecast that approximately 40 million people worldwide
could be HIV-infected by the year 2000, with the U.S. experiencing 1.5 million
cases. Efforts aimed at "curing" AIDS have not been successful and drugs
currently marketed to treat HIV/AIDS are only pallitives.  Only the drugs to
treat AIDS-associated infections and related conditions have met with
therapeutic success.<P>

A quest has begun within the medical community to combat this disease and to
develop vaccines to prevent HIV infection and/or the development of full-blown
AIDS. Also, the search includes development of better drugs to treat the AIDS-
associated infections.   Recent theories postulating on the multiple phases of
HIV disease and the complex events promoting the deterioration of an HIV-
infected patient's immune system have added a new parameter to the development
of treatment strategies.<P>

The Pharmaceutical Manufacturers Association (PMA) recently reported that
there are currently in progress 95 projects involving 91 different medicines
and vaccines relating to AIDS.  To date, 17 therapies for AIDS and AIDS-
associated diseases have received FDA approval for marketing.  These drugs
have provided a 1993 U.S. market of $787.5 million at the manufacturer's
(wholesale) sales level.  By 1998 this combined market is projected to grow to
over $1.4 billion in constant dollars.<P>

It is the purpose of this study to define this market in detail, with
particular emphasis on emerging products and opportunities.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This study details the United States market for vaccines and drugs for AIDS and
AIDS-associated infections, including:<P>

<UL><LI>products that are currently marketed<BR>
<LI>emerging and current technologies<BR>
<LI>analysis of these technologies, including their limitations and
           potential impact on future products and market growth<BR>
<LI>current market structure and size with forecasts through 2000
           in constant 1993 dollars<BR>
<LI>analysis of market dynamics and trends<BR>
<LI>corporate strategies<BR>
<LI>projections of disease incidence<BR>
<LI>drug delivery requirements<BR>
<LI>regulatory and economic issues affecting the marketplace
           including health care financing issues<BR>
<LI>niche areas offering opportunities for development<BR>
<LI>identification of potential market barriers<BR>
<LI>international aspects of the market</UL><P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This study encompasses the nearly 100 products currently under development, as
well as all existing products for AIDS and AIDS-associated medical conditions.
Also included are any emerging technologies that offer potential opportunities
for new drugs or vaccines.<P>

The AIDS therapy market is defined against current disease incidence and
forecasted incidence.  Wherever possible component suppliers, end markets,
government and regulatory agencies, major companies competing in this
marketplace, relative market shares and impact on worldwide status are
discussed.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

The methodologies employed in this study include use of both primary
interviews with industry personnel and analysis of secondary data.  Among the
primary data sources are drug company personnel, government and regulatory
representatives, industry observers, scientists and industry professional
organizations.  Growth calculations are made in constant 1993 dollars at the
manufacturers' price level.<P>

All data collected was reviewed by BCC's specialists in the health care
industry and all findings and projections were confirmed with numerous
industry sources.<P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Data sources for this report include information obtained from interviews with
various market participants and observers.  Substantial secondary data was
available from the federal government through the National Center for
Infectious Disease division of the Centers for Disease Control (CDC) and the
Agency for Health Care Policy and Research (U.S. Department of Health and
Human Services.  BCC's extensive library also served as a data source as did
corporate and industry trade association publications.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

The BCC project director of this report holds both medical technology and
advanced marketing degrees.  Further supporting the analyst's knowledge in
this area is extensive experience in the pharmaceutical industry, the medical
device industry, and in other high technology markets.  The most recent
studies published by this analyst are a study of emerging opportunities in the
U.S. health care delivery system in the year 2000, an examination of the
medical diagnostic kits and products market and a report on the U.S. blood
industry.  Other reports issued by this analyst are reports on trends in non-
invasive and minimally-invasive medical devices, microorganism testing
systems, gene probe markets, bioengineered protein drugs, new drug delivery
systems, medical diagnostic equipment, biocompatible materials, and the laser
industry.<P>

Published BCC reports related to the present topic include:<P>

<UL>C045N     -   MEDICAL DIAGNOSTIC KITS AND PRODUCTS<BR>
      C-057     -   VACCINES AND THEIR ALTERNATIVES<BR>
      C-065R    -   THE EXPANDING MARKET FOR BIO-ENGINEERED
                    PROTEIN DRUGS<BR>
      C-071R    -   THE BLOOD INDUSTRY<BR>
      C-072     -   NEW HORIZONS IN THE PHARMACEUTICAL INDUSTRY<BR>
