<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>C-171: THE NEW AND RE-EMERGING MARKET FOR HUMAN 
                      VACCINES</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=Left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO"><CENTER><H2>C-171: THE NEW AND RE-EMERGING MARKET FOR HUMAN 
                      VACCINES</H2>

<HR><P>
<I>SANDRA GRAHAM</I><BR>
Project Analyst<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B>

<P>A goal of this study is to identify the forces shaping the re-emerging vaccine 
market. Another goal is to quantify the sales of both vaccines and forecast 
future sales.</P> 

<P>The objectives of the study are to:</P>

   <P>Identify key business and political issues as they relate to the vaccine
      industry </P>
   <P>Describe potential vaccines in clinical trials and in preclinical and
      research programs</P>
   <P>Describe development efforts to improve vaccine delivery using adjuvants 
      and other new delivery technologies</P>
   <P>Define the patient populations, forecast markets to 1999 and identify high
      growth areas.</P>


<B>REASONS FOR STUDY</B>

<P>The vaccine industry is changing rapidly.  New methods of preparing vaccines, 
new targets for vaccines and new delivery technologies are emerging.  Diseases 
such as Lyme disease and hantavirus are becoming international problems.  New 
outbreaks of old diseases such as tuberculosis and cholera point out the need 
for improved vaccines. The Center for Disease Control and Prevention has 
announced that common bacterial infections are becoming immune to current 
antibiotics.  The threat is increasing as germs genetically change.  There is 
an increase in fatalities due to tuberculosis in AIDS patients.</P> 

<P>Vaccines offer both preventive and therapeutic opportunities for controlling 
and/or eradicating numerous diseases.  The key issues shaping the market need 
to be defined, analyzed and put into a composite image of the industry.  A new 
industry is emerging as new types of vaccines target old diseases and new 
types of diseases are being targeted by the biotechnology industry.</P> 


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B>

<P>This report is written for business executives interested in serving the 
market for vaccines.  The study will be a valuable resource of information, 
data and analysis for suppliers of these products, including the 
pharmaceutical manufacturers, as well as purchasers of the vaccines.  
Investors looking for new growth areas in healthcare, and those looking for 
strategic alliances and business opportunities will find this study highly 
worthwhile.</P> 

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B>

<P>The vaccines covered in this report provide both a clear image of the industry 
today and a look at the future of the vaccine industry.  For over 30 diseases, 
this study provides information on market size (patient population), sales 
estimates and projections of growth for the market.  Included in the study are 
the traditional childhood diseases (measles, mumps, rubella, chicken pox, 
whooping cough), the diseases endemic and epidemic in developing countries 
(malaria, diphtheria, cholera, HIV), diseases showing resurgence in unexpected 
areas (tuberculosis, polio) and diseases not previously treated with vaccines 
(rheumatoid arthritis, multiple sclerosis, cystic fibrosis, diabetes, 
chlamydia, genital warts).</P> 

<P>Excluded from this study are vaccines for allergies.  Also vaccines which have 
not been actively discussed in the trade literature over the past year are 
excluded.  Examples include adenovirus vaccines and yellow fever vaccines.</P> 

<P>The study format includes for each disease a detailed description including 
companies, composition of vaccines, status of development of vaccines and 
related comments in a tabular format.  For selected diseases with high levels 
of activity, a "phase diagram" providing a snapshot of who (company), what 
(vaccine description) and when (status) is included.</P> 


<B>METHODOLOGY</B>

<P>Primary sources include meetings with pharmaceutical industry professionals 
and telephone conversations.  Secondary information was obtained from various 
trade literature, the Pharmaceutical Research & Manufacturers Association, 
company press releases and other company literature, the Physicians' Desk 
Reference, U.S. government documents, disease-specific associations such as 
the American Cancer Society and Lyme Disease Foundation and numerous technical 
books and journals.</P> 

<P>All sales figures are for worldwide sales unless stated for a specific 
country.  Sales are expressed in millions of dollars (106) and shown in tables 
as "MM".  All dollar figures are in constant dollars.  No corrections for 
inflation are included.</P> 

<P>Sales figures were determined using U.S. government documents, 1994 Red Book 
prices for vaccines, and sales data and vaccine descriptions found in company 
and trade literature.  Projections are based on projected approvals for new 
vaccines, known efforts by government agencies worldwide to provide vaccines 
for specific diseases, current vaccination rates and populations.</P> 

