<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
C-177  NEW THERAPEUTICS & DIAGNOSTICS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-177  NEW THERAPEUTICS & DIAGNOSTICS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>SANDRA GRAHAM
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

A goal of this study is to identify diseases and medical conditions affecting
only women or disproportionately affecting women, or which require special
diagnostic or therapeutic products because of the unique requirements of
females. Another goal of this study is to quantify the sales of diagnostic and
therapeutic products for women's medicine and to forecast sales.<P>

The objectives of the study are to:<P>

<UL><LI>  Describe the current treatments and roles of drugs in the market
       applications where women are the only or the majority of patients.

<LI>   Examine potential therapeutics now in clinical trials and in
       preclinical and research programs that target women's diseases
       and medical conditions.

<LI>   Define the patient populations, forecast therapeutic and diagnostic
       markets to 1997, and identify high growth markets.</UL><P>


<B>REASONS FOR STUDY</B><P>

Women's diseases and medical conditions have never been a separate issue of
attention for the pharmaceutical industry until now.  Yet, today we know that
the special needs of women are not always being met and we recognize that the
female and male responses to medications can differ in many instances.<P>


<B>AUDIENCE FOR REPORT</B><P>

This report is written for business executives interested in serving the
women's market for diagnostics and therapeutics.  The study will be a valuable
resource of information, data and analysis for suppliers of these products,
including pharmaceutical and diagnostics manufacturers, as well as for
purchasers of the products.  Investors seeking new growth areas in healthcare,
and those looking for strategic alliances and business opportunities will find
this study highly worthwhile.<P>



<B>SCOPE OF STUDY</B><P>

The diseases and medical conditions covered in this study exclusively or
primarily relate to women. For the 20 diseases or conditions covered, this
study provides market size (patient population) data, sales estimates, and
projections of growth for each of the 20 diseases and conditions. Included are
female-specific cancers (ovarian, cervical, endometrial, breast);
gynecological infections; female-specific kidney and urological diseases;
menopause and osteoporosis; and female reproduction (contraception,
infertility, pregnancy).<P>

Excluded from this study are diseases and medical conditions which affect men
and women about equally or in a non-gender related way, such as heart disease,
hypertension, lung cancer and many others.  Important as they are,
understudied as they are from the perspective of women's needs, this study simply cannot address them all.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Primary information came from telephone interviews with physicians, scientists and business executives in the medical field.  Secondary information was obtained from various trade literature, the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers Assn., pharmaceutical company annual reports and other company literature, the Physicians' Desk Reference and USP Drug Index, U.S. government documents, disease-specific associations such as the American Cancer Society and Endometriosis Society, and numerous technical books and journals.<P>

Except where noted, all sales estimates and analysis relate to the U.S. market only. Except where noted, all sales figures refer to the retail level. Estimates are provided for 1992, 1993 and 1997 and are given in millions of dollars.  Forecasts for 1997 are expressed in constant 1992 dollars to reflect real changes without inflation.   The average annual growth rate, AAGR, is derived by the compounding method from standard tables of present value.

All analyses are made independently, without the bias of vested interests. Mentions of products are not endorsements, and omissions, if any, are not intentional.<P>


<B>ANALYST CREDENTIALS</B><P>

The analyst for this study has a B.S. degree in chemistry (Drexel University)
and an M.B.A. degree in management (Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute), as well
as additional credits in marketing (Hartford University Graduate Center).  She
has extensive work experience in a major pharmaceutical company, as a research
analyst.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>

Published BCC reports that relate to the present topic include:<P>

<UL>C-047R:  Cancer Diagnostic and Therapeutic Products<BR>
C-072 -  New Horizons in Drugs<BR>
C-084 -   Microorganisms Testing<BR>
C-092 -   Medical Anti-Infective Agents<BR>
C-181 -   New Strategies for Drug Marketing<BR>
GB-097 -  OTC Home Healthcare Products</UL><P>


