C-181: THE CHANGING DRUG INDUSTRY:
HIGHLIGHTING MARKETS, MARKETING TECHNIQUES, 
STRATEGIES, STRUCTURES & TECHNOLOGIES    
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>C-181: THE CHANGING DRUG INDUSTRY:
HIGHLIGHTING MARKETS, MARKETING TECHNIQUES, 
STRATEGIES, STRUCTURES & TECHNOLOGIES    
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Barbara Briendel
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This report, New Strategies In Drug Markets, addresses the tactical marketing maneuvers pharmaceutical companies are implementing, or perhaps should 
implement, in response to the efforts of health care reformers to cut costs.   <P>

The U.S. pharmaceutical industry generated domestic sales of over $57 
billion for drugs in 1993, up nearly 7% from the previous year, but the 
industry has shown past annual growth rates at the double digit level.  The industry is one of world's most profitable, but recent attacks on drug pricing, as well as patent expirations allowing for inroads by generic drugs, 
changes in the tax laws (Section 936), and poor foreign exchange rates do not bode well for the near future. Furthermore, large multinational companies and 
foreign-owned companies experiencing contracting markets, due to many of the 
same problems in their own countries, are focusing on the U.S. market for 
expansion.  Drug companies have been actively developing various strategies, 
both current and future, in their quest for maintaining current position and 
sustaining growth.<P>

Within the goals of this study BCC will provide detailed 
information on these various strategies and an analysis of each, with 
particular emphasis on how they will impact on the current and future status 
of the pharmaceutical market through the year 2000.<P> 


<b>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

The current climate for developing, manufacturing and marketing pharmaceuticals
is at an all-time low and the short-term outlook is one of further uncertainty. 
Among the reasons BCC undertook this study is to provide information and
analysis on: Barbara Briendel


<UL><LI> Strategies required for drug companies to survive and thrive in this 
    uncertain climate<P>

<LI>  Numerous new marketing concepts drug companies are instituting, including
    joint ventures, licensing, marketing alliances, mergers, acquisitions, 
    and new pricing strategies<P>

<LI>  Innovative product concepts, drug delivery systems, and new dosaging formats
    companies are incorporating into their product lines<P>

<LI>  Distribution methods and group purchasing programs being undertaken by
    pharmaceutical companies<P>

<LI>  Creative approaches in advertising and promotion. <P></UL>


<b>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This study should prove of particular value to managers and observers of the
pharmaceutical industry, since it provides details on the United States
pharmaceutical market with emphasis on drug marketing, including:<P>

<UL><LI> new marketing concepts and trends<P>

<LI> changes in traditional strategies<P>

   <LI> changes in marketplace and market segments<P>

<LI> impact of outside influences such as national health care programs and 
       the  regulatory environment; with identification of potential market 
       barriers<P>

<LI> current market structure and size with forecasts through 2000 in constant
       1993 dollars<P>

<LI> new advertising and promotion programs with an analysis of their 
       potential benefits and limitations<P>

<LI> identification and analysis of new distribution systems with particular
       emphasis on their cost saving benefits to drug consumers<P>

<LI> identification of niche areas offering opportunities<P>

<LI> corporate strategies<P>

<LI> international aspects of the market.<P></UL>


<b>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The entire pharmaceutical industry is examined in this report, with particular 
emphasis on those companies that are taking innovative marketing actions to 
position themselves as market leaders through the year 2000.<P>  

The market is segmented into ethical and over-the-counter drugs in both the 
branded and generic forms.  Throughout the report an effort is made to discuss 
vertical integration of market segments and to identify component suppliers, 
end markets, government and regulatory agencies.  Companies participating in 
the marketplace will be described as to relative market share, marketing 
strengths, participation in new segments, and innovative marketing practices.<P> 

<b>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

The methodologies employed in this study include use of both primary interviews
with industry personnel and analysis of secondary data.  Among the primary data
sources are drug company personnel, government and regulatory representatives,
industry observers, scientists, and industry professional organizations.<P>  

Growth forecasts are made in constant 1993 dollars based on the manufacturer's
(wholesale) price level unless otherwise noted.<P>

All data collected was reviewed by BCC's specialists in the health care 
industry, and all findings and projections were confirmed with numerous 
industry sources.<P> 

<b>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Data sources for this report include information obtained from interviews with 
various market participants and observers.  BCC's extensive library also 
served as a data source, as did corporate and industry trade association 
publications and industry data banks.<P> 

<b>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

The BCC project director of this report holds both medical technology and 
advanced marketing degrees.  Further supporting the analyst's knowledge in 
this area is extensive experience in the pharmaceutical industry, the medical 
device industry, and in other high technology markets.  The most recent 
studies published by this analyst are a study of emerging opportunities in the 
U.S. health care delivery system in the year 2000, an examination of the 
medical diagnostic kits and products market, and a report on the U.S. blood 
industry.  Other reports issued by this analyst are reports on trends in non-
invasive and minimally-invasive medical devices, microorganism testing 
systems, gene probe markets, bioengineered protein drugs, new drug delivery 
systems, medical diagnostic equipment, biocompatible materials and the laser 
industry.<P> 

Published BCC reports related to the present topic include:<P>

<UL>  C-170    -     MARKETS FOR VACCINES AND DRUGS FOR AIDS AND
                    AIDS-ASSOCIATED MEDICAL CONDITIONS<P>

     C-045N  - MEDICAL DIAGNOSTIC KITS AND PRODUCTS<P>
     C-057    -     VACCINES AND THEIR ALTERNATIVES<P>
     C-065R -  THE EXPANDING MARKET FOR BIO-ENGINEERED
               PROTEIN DRUGS<P>

     C-071R -  THE BLOOD INDUSTRY<P>

     C-072  -  NEW HORIZONS IN THE PHARMACEUTICAL INDUSTRY<P>

     C-088R -  DYNAMIC ANTIBODY INDUSTRY<P>

     C-092  -  MEDICAL ANTI-INFECTIVE AGENTS AND THE IMPACT OF
               BIOTECHNOLOGY<P>

     C-109  -  NEW TRENDS IN ANTIVIRALS<P></UL>

