<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GB159  INTRAVENOUS THERAPY PRODUCTS, TECHNOLOGY AND MARKETS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GB159  INTRAVENOUS THERAPY PRODUCTS, TECHNOLOGY AND MARKETS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>YATIN B. THAKORE, Ph.D.<BR>
MS. KANAN THAKORE, MS, RD, CNSD
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYSTS
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

Intravenous therapy is a critical element in the treatment of patients. One out of
eight persons will undergo intravenous therapy of some form this year.<P>

Intravenous infusion has been tried periodically for blood transfusion since the mid-
1600s, with mixed results. Only in the last 50 years, has it become more
commonplace.<P>

Today, infusion therapy is almost routine. In hospitals, 90 percent of surgical patients
and a third of non-surgical inpatients receive some form of intravenous therapy.
Intravenous infusions are used for introducing fluids, nutrition, blood or its products,
and medications to patients.<P>

Infusion product markets consist of two components: therapeutics, and hardware. The
former consists of intravenous solutions and nutritionals, blood products, and
intravenous drugs. The latter consist of vascular access and delivery devices.<P>

There has been major progress on both fronts. On the therapeutic front, new drugs
and therapies have expanded the applications, offering more effective treatment of
certain diseases. Biopharmaceuticals have been a recent entry in this field, and will
continue to have a major impact in the coming years. Newer experimental therapies,
such as those for removing and modifying certain cells very selectively, could
significantly expand the role of infusion therapy.<P>

On the hardware front, electronic infusion pumps, and disposable infusion pumps
have become smarter, offering features such as patient control, and remote
programming. Catheter manufacturers are looking at improving the catheter materials
and catheter design to make them more biocompatible, and to offer better infection
control. In spite of all the progress, infection at present has remained a major
problem.<P>

The question of safety has become the issue of the nineties. This will provide for a
major growth opportunity for equipment makers, and breathe some life into some of
the mature segments of the IV business.  The AIDS epidemic has given added urgency
to design safer hardware. To this end, intravenous sets and catheters, which protect
workers from needlestick injuries, have been amongst the newest innovations. The
cost-containment climate actually helps these more expensive products. Apart from
protecting the workers, they prove cost-effective; diagnostic tests and treatment for
needlestick injuries cost about $200 per injury according to one estimate. Newer
guidelines for worker safety are also pushing the use of the value-added, safer
products.<P>

Alternative site care is another factor that will continue to reshape the infusion
products industry. The cost-containment movement by hospitals was fueled by the
implementation of the prospective payment system (PPS), as mandated by Congress
in the mid-eighties. As a result, home and alternative site infusion businesses have
been booming. Innovative hardware design, and newer and safer drugs have facilitated
this trend. Growth of infusion products for the alternative site market will remain
strong.<P>


<B>PURPOSE OF THIS STUDY</B><P>

This study examines a very important segment of the healthcare market. It analyzes
technology, current status and future trends of infusion products.<P>

In spite of the infusion products business being around for nearly 50 years, it has
continued to evolve. It has seen new therapies, such as nutritional and drug therapies,
added to its menu. Progress in materials, electronics and manufacturing technology
have made today's hardware quite sophisticated.<P>

Today, far from being a settled business, this industry is changing and still evolving.
On the one hand, new drugs and therapies, concerns about worker safety, the trend
towards alternative site therapy, and more value-added hardware are offering growth
opportunities for some of the market sectors. On the other hand, advances in newer,
less invasive drug delivery and targeting methods, threaten to bite into some of the
IV products market.<P>

This study looks at the markets and technologies, and attempts to identify the future
course of this business. Infusion products include IV solutions, hardware, drug and
blood products. Often the latter two are not included as part of the infusion products
business. We have tried to provide a more complete picture of the infusion products
business by including drugs and blood products in our study. We feel that this would
be helpful for those who may want to see the 'big picture.'<P>


<B>TARGETED AUDIENCE</B><P>

This study will be useful to those who are in the infusion industry, or are interested
in the infusion industry. It is intended to provide them with an understanding of the
markets, trends, technologies and overall structure of the industry. Executives of
companies involved with the manufacture or distribution of infusion products or
supplies, including hardware, solutions, drugs, or blood products, will find this a
useful resource. It would be helpful also to prospective entrants in this business,
organizations promoting or serving the infusion business, analysts, venture capitalists,
investors and industry watchers.<P>

<B>SCOPE OF THIS STUDY</B><P>

This study examines the intravenous infusion products used for therapeutic
applications. It includes intravenous solutions, drugs, nutritionals, blood products, and
necessary hardware to administer these products. The focus is clearly on intravenous
and therapeutic products.<P>

We therefore have generally excluded infusion products used for other routes, e.g.
enteral products, peritoneal catheters, non-IV drugs, etc. We have also excluded non-
therapeutic applications, such as some of the diagnostic catheters.<P>

An exception to this general definition of 'infusion' is when we have discussed the
home infusion industry. This industry combines service and products, and the
definition of infusion used in the context of the home infusion industry, by
convention, is broader, and includes enteral nutrition, intramuscular injections, and
certain aerosol inhalation therapies. We have also excluded diagnostic catheters from
our study.<P>

In the hardware sector, we have included needles and catheters, IV sets, pumps and
controllers, and other miscellaneous devices such as filters, valves and fittings.
Additionally we have also included certain critical raw materials and components,
such as tubing, filters and plastic films.<P>

We have provided detailed description and analyses of markets by product types and
by segments where they are used. We have also discussed markets for key raw
materials and components, and the home infusion business. The emphasis throughout
this report is on domestic markets, but we have provided a short chapter that
estimates the international markets.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

Research for this study consisted of extensive study of published literature, BCC
resources, and interviews with industrial, university and governmental experts.<P>

Published information was searched via databases covering medical, biological,
chemical and business fields. Additionally dozens of books, government reports,
conference proceedings, company annual reports and related marketing reports were
consulted.<P>

Primary data collection was via interviews with industrial manufacturers, end users,
market watchers, and officials of governmental and business associations.<P>

 The information was assimilated and discussed among the BCC staff. The basis and
assumptions behind projected and forecasted markets are clearly defined in this
report.<P>


<B>BIOGRAPHY/QUALIFICATIONS</B><P>


Project analysts for this report, Dr. Yatin Thakore, and Ms. Kanan Thakore, together
bring years of industrial experience in the areas of healthcare, foods and nutrition and
biomaterials.<P>

Dr. Yatin Thakore has 12 years of industrial experience in the areas of biomaterials,
biotechnology, and healthcare. Dr. Thakore obtained his doctorate degree from the
University of Utah in Materials Science and Engineering, with specialization in
polymers and biomaterials. Dr. Thakore holds several U.S. and international patents
in the fields of separation processes and diagnostics.<P>

Ms. Kanan Thakore, is a registered dietitian, and a certified nutrition support
dietitian, working at the JFK Hospital in Edison, NJ. She coordinates the nutrition
support team to care for critically ill patients. Ms. Thakore has over seven years of
work experience as a clinical dietitian. She obtained her Masters degree in Foods and
Nutrition from Rutgers University.<P>


