<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GB-103R  ADVANCED OPTICAL MATERIALS
Applications, Markets and Technology
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GB-103R  ADVANCED OPTICAL MATERIALS
Applications, Markets and Technology</H2>

<HR><P>

<H3><I>
INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This new Business Communications Company (BCC) report provides a
detailed analysis of the markets and technology for advanced optical
materials which fulfill a host of different needs in both military and
commercial applications. The study updates and revises BCC report GB-
103A Advanced Optical Materials that was published in 1987. The materials
investigated in this report include:<P>

 Glasses and other Crown glasses, flints, borosilicates,
common optical materials etc.
 Glass ceramics/ceramics (Zerodur, ULE, 9600, spinel,
 ALON, silicon carbide, alumina, etc.)
 Crystalline/polycrystalline (Fused silica, fused quartz, cultured
 materialsquartz, calcite, natural quartz,
sapphire, germanium, silicon
 Alkaline FluoridesMagnesium fluoride, calcium
 fluoride barium fluoride, lithium
fluoride
 Metal Halides, Potassium chloride, sodium chloride,
potassium bromide<P>

The principal objectives of this study are to:<P>

 Characterize the current and potential markets for these materials
through 1995 in light of existing and new materials, technology, and
applications<P>

 Evaluate the effects of proposed and actual military budget cuts on
the advanced optics industry<P>
 
 Discuss new defense- and nondefense-related applications for
advanced optical materials<P>

 Characterize the major end-use markets for these materials<P>

 Define and quantify the current and potential applications for these
materials<P>

 Identify and characterize the major players<P>

 Discuss the major economic and geopolitical factors impacting the
industry.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

A great deal has happened over the last three years since the first advanced
optical materials study was published by BCC. There have been major
changes in global politics with the opening up of Eastern Europe, the
marked changes in the Soviet Union, and the potential for increased threats
from the Middle East. The industry has reeled under the threat of major
cutbacks in defense spending, and defense-related programs already have
been stretched out, delayed, or cut. At the same time, the U.S. economy
appears to be sliding ever so slowly into a recession. It would appear that
difficult times await the advanced optics industry. BCC, which actively
follows the advanced optics industry, as well as related industries
including electro-optics, sensors, fiber optics, and microelectronics, found
that the oft-quoted dismal predictions for the industry are not likely to be as
terrible as feared. BCC recently completed a major study investigating
nonlinear optical materials (BCC report GB-117), and found significant
margin for growth in a number of different defense-related and
nondefense-related areas. In addition, two recently completed major
studies on the aerospace industry (BCC reports GB-122 and GB-124)
projected growth in related industries that utilize substantial amounts of
advanced optics. These studies, along with many inquiries from executives
in the advanced optics industry, suggested to us that a new advanced
optical materials study should be initiated to go back and look at the crucial
issues affecting the industry and re-evaluate the markets for advanced
optical materials during this transitional and unsettled period.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

This BCC report provides a thorough analysis of the advanced optical
materials industry as it pertains to both defense and commercial
applications. Specifically, this study:<P>

 Analyzes and quantifies specific applications in military/aerospace
for reconnaissance, guidance and control, identification, designation, fire control, etc.<P>

 Analyzes and quantifies specific applications for nonmilitary
applications in industry for vision, various sensors, materials
processing, thermal measurement and control, etc.<P>

Analyzes and quantifies specific medical and other commercial
applications<P>

 Provides U.S. and worldwide market projections for advanced
optical materials through 1995<P>

 Evaluates the materials and markets<P>

 Discusses companies and organizations involved in materials
production, research, and manufacturing<P>

 Discusses foreign materials competitors, end users, and markets.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

The information presented in this study was derived from over 150
interviews with knowledgeable industry, government, and academic
sources, including materials producers, fabricators, end users, and
research scientists and engineers in all of the areas covered. Due to the
increasing worldwide nature and importance of these special advanced
materials, foreign sources were contacted, in addition to domestic sources,
and worldwide information and specific market data, where available,
were included in this study. In addition, a thorough search of the technical,
trade, scientific, and governmental literature was conducted.<P>

BCC's extensive in-house resources were consulted and utilized where
appropriate, and portions of several recently published major BCC market
research studies  were included in the evaluations. This study was
conducted over a four-month period ending in August 1990. Information
and data are current to the end of August 1990. Dollar market projections
are given in constant 1990 dollars unless otherwise indicated. A list of
acronyms appears in Appendix A.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC STUDIES</B><P>

BCC has conducted a number of major studies analyzing advanced
materials and their respective markets over the last few years. They
include:<P>

 GB-117---Nonlinear Optical Materials: New Technologies, Applications,
and Markets<P>

 GB-141---Optical Thin Films: New Technologies, Applications, and
Markets<P>

 GB-114---Chemically Derived Ceramics and Glasses--Sol Gel Processing<P>

 GB-121---Electronic Ceramics<P>

 GB-128---Thick Film/Thin Film Impact on Microelectronics<P>

 GB-122---Airframe Materials<P>

 GB-122---Materials for Aerospace/Aircraft Propulsion Systems <P>



<CENTER><HR WIDTH=50% SIZE=4>
