<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GB-141  OPTICAL THIN-FILM MARKETS AND TECHNOLOGY:
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GB-141  OPTICAL THIN-FILM MARKETS AND TECHNOLOGY:</H2>

<HR><P>


<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This new Business Communications Company (BCC) report provides a
detailed analysis of the markets and technology for optical thin-film
deposition materials, equipment, and services (merchant and captive). The
report covers both defense- and nondefense-related applications. This study
updates and completely revises an earlier BCC report GB-100--Thin Films
for Microelectronics and Advanced Optical Applications. However, because
of the extraordinary interest in optical thin films, the current report is
devoted exclusively to optical thin films. Microelectronic thin films are not
treated in the current study.<P>

The major topics covered in this BCC report include:<P>

<MENU> Materials used for optical thin-film deposition, including:
common compounds, precious metals, diamond, and others<P>

       Equipment used for optical thin-film deposition<P>

       Thin-film deposition technology<P>

       Special processes, such as various types of energy-assisted
deposition, diamond production processes, and sol-gel processes<P>

In-depth analysis of the markets, applications, and technologies<P>

       Worldwide market projections through the year 2000 (merchant
 and captive)<P>

       Discussion and listing of companies, government agencies and
laboratories, universities, and their foreign counterparts<P>

       Geopolitical analysis of events relevant to the industry<P>

       Recent patents and analysis</MENU><P>

The principal objectives of this study are to:<P>

<LI>       Characterize the current and potential markets for optical thin-
film deposition materials, equipment, and services through 2000<P>

<LI>       Evaluate the effects of proposed and actual military budget cuts on
the industry<P>

<LI>      Characterize and discuss new defense- and nondefense-related
applications for optical thin-films<P>

<LI>       Characterize the major end-use markets for optical thin films<P>

<LI>       Define and quantify current and potential applications for optical
thin films<P>

<LI>      Identify and characterize the principal industry participants<P>

<LI>       Analyze and discuss the major economic and geopolitical factors
impacting the industry.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

A great deal has happened since the first optical thin-films study was
published by BCC, Inc. in May 1987. The stock market crashed later that
year. The Soviet Union began releasing its Warsaw Pact Satellites--
culminating in the fall of the Berlin Wall. The U.S. economy steadily slid
into a recession. The Savings & Loan industry failed, the banking industry
is heading in the same direction, real estate values have tumbled from their
inflated values of the mid-1980s, and unemployment is up and rising, all of
which have shaken the consumer's confidence. <P>

The astoundingly huge
bailout of the S&Ls will place a long-term economic burden on the United
States for decades, not to mention the rising national debt. Iraq invaded
Kuwait, and now the U.S. and a good deal of the West have participated in
the Gulf War. And to top it all off, now the Soviet Union and its tanks are
rolling backwards toward its old dictatorial ways--freedom for Latvia and
Lithuania is being crushed, and it is yet to be determined who is next.<P>

The optics industry has reeled under the threat of major cutbacks in
defense spending, and defense-related programs already have been
stretched out, delayed, or cut. It would appear that difficult times await the advanced optics industry, and thereby, the optical thin-film deposition industry. BCC, which actively and carefully follows the advanced optics industry, as well as related industries including electro-optics, sensors, fiber optics, microelectronics, and other high-performance materials found that the oft quoted dismal predictions for the industry are not likely to be as terrible as suggested.<P>

BCC recently completed several major studies covering different aspects of the optics industry. Two major studies, one investigating the advanced optical materials industry (BCC report No. GB-103R) and another investigating nonlinear optical materials (BCC report No. GB-117), found significant margin for growth in a number of different defense-related and nondefense-related areas. In addition, during the course of producing BCC's monthly newsletter, Optical Materials & Engineering News (OMEN), it has become apparent that there is tremendous interest and ongoing work in the field of optical thin films.<P>

These studies and OMEN, along with many inquiries from executives in
the advanced optics industry, suggested to us that a new optical thin-film deposition study should be initiated to go back and look at the crucial issues affecting the industry and re-evaluate the markets for optical thin films during this transitional and unsettling period.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

This BCC study fills an essential gap in the industry. It is the only "on the
shelf," openly available report that provides an in-depth technical/economic
analysis of the optical thin-film deposition industry.<P>

This BCC report provides a thorough analysis of the optical thin-film
deposition industry as it pertains to both defense, nondefense government,
and commercial applications. Specifically, this study:<P>

<LI>       Analyzes and quantifies specific applications in military/
aerospace for reconnaissance, guidance and control,
identification, target designation, navigation, etc.<P>

<LI>       Analyzes and quantifies specific applications for nonmilitary
government applications, such as those for The Mission To Planet
Earth and its component Earth Observation System (EOS)<P>

 <LI>      Analyzes and quantifies specific applications for nonmilitary
applications in industry for vision, various sensors, materials
processing, thermal measurement and control, etc.<P>

<LI>       Analyzes and quantifies specific medical and other commercial
applications<P>

<LI>       Provides U.S. and worldwide market projections through the year
2000 for both merchant and captive market segments<P>

<LI>       Evaluates the technology, applications, and markets<P>

<LI>       Discusses companies and organizations involved in materials
production, research, manufacturing, equipment production, and
service providers (merchant and captive)<P>

<LI>       Discusses foreign competitors, end users, and markets<P>

<LI>       Analyzes and discusses relevant geopolitical issues<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

The information presented in this study was derived from over 150
interviews with knowledgeable industry, government, and academic
sources, including materials producers, equipment manufacturers,
service providers, end users, research scientists, and engineers in all of the
areas covered. Due to the increasing worldwide nature and importance of
this special field, in addition to domestic sources, foreign sources were
contacted and worldwide information and specific market data, where
available, were included in this study. In addition, a thorough search of the
technical, trade, scientific, patent, and governmental literature was
conducted.<P>

BCC's extensive in-house resources were consulted and utilized where
appropriate, and portions of several recently published major BCC market
research studies  were included in the evaluations. This study was
conducted over a three-month period ending in March 1991. Information
and data are current to the first of March 1991. Dollar market projections
are given in constant 1990 dollars unless otherwise indicated.<P>


