<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GB-144  ADVANCED OPTICS/ELECTRO-OPTICS MARKETS, AND THE POTENTIAL FOR
TECHNOLOGY TRANSFER FROM DEFENSE/GOVERNMENT APPLICATIONS TO COMMERCIAL
APPLICATIONS</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GB-144  ADVANCED OPTICS/ELECTRO-OPTICS MARKETS, AND THE POTENTIAL FOR TECHNOLOGY TRANSFER FROM DEFENSE/GOVERNMENT APPLICATIONS TO COMMERCIAL APPLICATIONS</H2>

<HR><P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This new Business Communications Company (BCC) report provides a
detailed analysis of the potential for technology transfer from
defense and government applications to the commercial sector. It
provides estimates of market potential for specific commercial
application areas, including:<P>

<MENU>-    automotive<BR>
-    commercial aircraft<BR>
-    commercial space<BR>
-    telecommunications<BR>
-    environmental monitoring<BR>
-    industrial<BR>
-    medical<BR>
-    computers<BR>
-    astronomy</MENU><P>

In addition, this report provides technology transfer estimated
potential broken down by optics/electro-optics technologies,
including:<P>

<MENU>-    lasers (all types)<BR>
-    detectors/sensors (IR, UV, visible, excluding electron tubes)<BR>
-    components (e.g., lenses, windows, prisms, mirrors, etc.)<BR>
-    materials (IR, UV, visible range)</MENU><P>

Further, this report provides an overview of the markets, and
provides projections through 1996 or 2001 for the following areas:<P>

<MENU>-    lasers (all types)<BR>
-    detectors/sensors (IR, UV, visible, excluding electron tubes)<BR>
-    detector materials (MCT, InSb, InAs, InGaAs, PtSi, Ge, PbS &
     PbSe)<BR>
-    components (e.g., lenses, windows, prisms, mirrors, etc.)<BR>
-    materials (IR, UV, visible range)</MENU><P>

The principal objectives of this study are to:<P>

<MENU>-    characterize and quantify the current and potential markets for
defense and government technology which is available for transfer in
terms of percent of market penetration and dollar value<P>

-    characterize and quantify the current and potential end-use
markets for the major optics/electro-optics applications indicated
above<P>
-    characterize and quantify the current and potential markets for
the component technologies indicated above<P>

-    evaluate the effects of proposed and actual defense budget cuts
on the industry<P>

-    elaborate and discuss new defense- and nondefense-related
applications for optics/electro-optics technology<P>

-    identify and characterize the principal government participants<P>

-    identify and characterize the principal industry participants<P>

-    identify and characterize the principal university participants<P>

-    identify and characterize major research consortia<P>

-    characterize the nature of the technology-transfer process, and
elaborate problems, barriers, and approaches.</MENU><P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

The optics/electro-optics industry has reeled under the threat of
major cutbacks in defense spending, and defense-related programs
which already have been stretched out, delayed, or cut. It would
appear that difficult times await the advanced optics/electro-optics
industry. BCC, which actively and carefully follows the advanced
optics/electro-optics industry, as well as related industries, has
found that the oft-quoted dismal predictions for the industry are not
likely to be as terrible as suggested.<P>

BCC recently completed several
major studies covering different aspects of the optics industry.
Three major studies, one investigating the advanced optical materials
industry (BCC report no. GB-103R), another investigating nonlinear
optical materials (BCC report no. GB-117), and the third, covering
the optical thin-film industry (BCC report no. GB-141), found
significant margin for growth in a number of different
defense-related and nondefense-related areas. In addition, in editing
BCC's monthly industry newsletter, Optical Materials & Engineering
News (OMEN), it has become apparent to this writer that there is
tremendous interest and ongoing work in optics/electro-optics and
technology transfer. These studies and OMEN, along with many
inquiries from executives in the advanced optics/electro-optics
industry, suggested to us that a new study should be initiated during
this transitional and unsettling period to investigate the crucial
issues affecting the industry; re-evaluate the markets for lasers,
detectors/sensors, components, and materials; and develop estimates
of the market potential for technology transfer in these fields.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

This BCC study fills an essential gap in the industry. It is the only
"on the shelf," openly available report that provides an in-depth
technical/economic analysis of the optics/electro-optics industry in
terms of individual component technologies, application markets, and
the potential for technology transfer.<P>

This BCC report provides a thorough analysis of the
optics/electro-optics industry as it pertains to technology transfer
in defense, nondefense government, and commercial applications.
Specifically, this study:<P>

<MENU>-    provides estimated market potential for technology transfer in the areas indicated above through 2001.<P>

-    provides U.S. and worldwide market projections through the year
2001 for optics/electro-optics technologies and commercial end-use
applications.<P>

-    analyzes and quantifies specific applications in
military/aerospace for reconnaissance, guidance and control,
identification, target designation, navigation, etc.<P>

-    analyzes and quantifies specific applications for nonmilitary
government applications, such as those for The Mission To Planet
Earth and its component Earth Observation System (EOS)<P>

-    analyzes and quantifies specific commercial applications, such
as remote sensing, medical, instrumentation, vision, various sensors,
materials processing, thermal measurement, process control, etc.<P>

-    evaluates the technology, applications, and markets.<P>

-    discusses and lists government agencies, companies,
organizations, universities, and research consortia involved in
technology transfer activities.<P>

-    analyzes and discusses U.S. defense-related budgets and
activities pertaining to optics/electro-optics and technology
transfer.<P>

-    provides a detailed summary of legislation governing technology
transfer, including problems and benefits.<P>

-    analyzes and discusses relevant geopolitical issues.<P>

-    provides summaries of representative technologies available for
transfer from government laboratories and industry.</MENU><P>

In addition to the material on available technologies included in
this report, BCC is making available a more complete list of
available technologies as an adjunct to this report. Details on this
supplement can be obtained from BCC.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

The information presented in this study was derived from over 175
interviews with knowledgeable industry, government, and academic
sources, including technology-transfer officers in government,
industry, and academia; researchers and executives in the laser
industry, detector/sensors industry, components industry, and
materials industry. Interviews of representatives of all of the major
optics/electro-optics-related consortia also were conducted. Due to
the increasingly worldwide nature and importance of the industry, in
addition to domestic sources, foreign sources were contacted and
worldwide information and specific market data, where available, were
included in this study. In all, approximately 220 companies and
organizations were surveyed. In addition, a thorough search of the
technical, trade, scientific, patent, and governmental literature was
conducted.<P>

BCC's extensive in-house resources were consulted and utilized where
appropriate, and portions of several recently published major BCC
market research studies were included in the evaluations. This study
was conducted over a 3.5-month period ending in August 1991.
Information and data are current to the first of August 1991. Dollar
market projections are given in constant 1991 dollars unless
otherwise indicated.<P>


