<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GB-150  OPTICALLY ACTIVE POLYMERS, ORGANOMETALLICS
AND BIOMOLECULAR MATERIALS/DEVICES:
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GB-150  OPTICALLY ACTIVE POLYMERS, ORGANOMETALLICS
AND BIOMOLECULAR MATERIALS/DEVICES:
</H2>

<HR><P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This new Business Communications Company (BCC) report provides a
detailed analysis of the potential for optically active organic
materials. As defined in this report, they include:<P>

<MENU>Organic Polymers<BR>
 Metallorganic Optical Materials<BR>
 Biomolecular Optical Materials</MENU><P>

These materials may be used for various nonlinear optical and
electro-optical applications, principally in:

<MENU>communications<BR>
 information processing<BR>
 memory/storage<BR>
 imaging<BR>
 optical limiting, and<BR>
 new applications, many of which, are yet to be created.</MENU><P>

The principal objectives of this study are to:<P>

<MENU><LI>     Investigate and discuss the relevant technologies and
applications<P>

<LI> Characterize and quantify the current and potential markets
for optically active organic materials and devices<P>

<LI> Characterize and quantify the current and potential end-use
markets for the major optics/electro-optics applications for
nonlinear optical materials<P>

<LI>  Identify and characterize the principal industry participants,
worldwide<P>

<LI>  Identify and characterize the principal government
participants, worldwide<P>

<LI> Identify and characterize the principal university
participants, worldwide.</MENU><P>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

BCC recently completed several major studies covering different
aspects of the optics industry. Three major studies, one
investigating the advanced optical materials industry (BCC report
no. GB-103R), another nonlinear optical materials (BCC report no.
GB-117), and the third, covering the optical thin-film industry
(BCC report no. GB-141), found significant margin for growth in a
number of different commercial areas and defense-related areas. In
addition, during the course of editing BCC's monthly industry
newsletter, Optical Materials & Engineering News (OMEN), it has
become apparent that there is tremendous interest and ongoing work
in optics/electro-optics, particularly with respect to nonlinear
optical processes. These studies and OMEN, along with many
inquiries from executives in the advanced optics/electro-optics
industry, suggested to us that a new study should be initiated to
ascertain the current state of the art, and the market potential
for optically active organic materials.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

This BCC study fills an essential gap in the industry. It is the
only "on the shelf," openly available report that provides an
in-depth technical/economic analysis of optically active organic
materials in terms of individual component technologies,
applications, markets, and potential.<P>

This BCC report provides a thorough analysis of the potential for
optically active organics, including polymers, organometallics, and
biomolecular materials. Specifically, this study:<P>

<MENU><LI> provides an assessment of the relevant technologies<P>

<LI> provides worldwide projections through the year 2001 for the
major end-use markets which could utilize these materials and
devices<P>

<LI>  provides worldwide projections through the year 2001 for the
major systems markets which could utilize these materials and
devices<P>

<LI>  provides worldwide projections through the year 2001 for
device applications which could utilize these materials<P>

<LI>  characterizes potential applications for optically active
organics<P>

<LI>  provides lists of companies, government laboratories, and
universities involved in optically active organic materials/devices
research and development<P>

<LI> provides summaries of interviews with companies, government
agencies, universities, and research consortia<P>

<LI>  provides summaries of company, government laboratory, and
university research and development activities<P>

<LI>  provides a patent search and analysis, current through August
1991.</MENU><P>

<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

The information presented in this study was derived, in part, from
over 75 interviews with knowledgeable industry, government, and
academic sources. Due to the increasing worldwide nature and
importance of the industry, in addition to domestic sources,
foreign sources were contacted and worldwide information and
specific market data, where available, were included in this study.
In all, over 100 companies and organizations were surveyed. In
addition, a thorough search of the technical, trade, scientific,
patent, and governmental literature was conducted.<P>

Extensive BCC in-house resources were consulted and utilized where
appropriate, and portions of several recently published major BCC
market research studies were included in the evaluations. This
study was conducted over a 1.5-month period ending in October 1991.
Dollar market projections are given in constant 1991 dollars unless
otherwise indicated.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC STUDIES AND PUBLICATIONS</B><P>

BCC has conducted a number of major studies analyzing advanced
optics/electro-optics and related markets over the last few years.
They include:<P>
<MENU>GB-103A---Advanced Optical Materials: Applications, Markets, and
Technology--1986<P>

GB-103B---Advanced Optical Detectors and Detector Materials:
Applications, Markets, and Technology--1988<P>

GB-103R---Advanced Optical Materials: Applications, Markets, and
Technology--1990<P>

GB-114---Chemically Derived Ceramics and Glasses--Sol Gel
Processing--1988<P>

GB-117---Nonlinear Optical Materials: New Technologies,
Applications, and Markets--1989<P>

GB-121---Electronic Ceramics--1990<P>

GB-128---Thick Film/Thin Film Impact on Microelectronics--1990<P>

GB-130---Chemical Vapor Deposition--1990<P>

GB-133---Physical Vapor Deposition--1990<P>

GB-134---Ionic & Molecular Surface Modifications--1990.

GB-141---Optical Thin-Film Markets and Technology: Materials,
Equipment, and Services--1991<P>

GB-144---Advanced Optics/Electro-Optics Markets, and the Potential
for Technology Transfer from Defense/Government Applications to
Commercial Applications</MENU><P>

<B>OTHER RELEVANT BCC OPTICS PUBLICATIONS</B><P>

<MENU>Optical Materials & Engineering News--A monthly industry newsletter<P>

The Optics 500 Directory</MENU><P>


