<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GB-162  ADVANCED TRANSPORTATION CONTROL SYSTEMS -
A Technical/Economic Analysis
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GB-162  ADVANCED TRANSPORTATION CONTROL SYSTEMS -
A Technical/Economic Analysis
</H2>

<HR><P>


<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This new Business Communications Co. (BCC) report provides one
of first views into the new Intelligent Vehicle Highway System
(IVHS) from a marketing, economic, and technical approach.<P>

The principal objectives of this study are to:<P>

<UL>   <LI>  Investigate and discuss the relevant technologies and
          applications<P>

    <LI>  Characterize and quantify the current, near-term, and
          mid-term technologies, applications, and markets for IVHS
          components<P>

   <LI>  Identify and discuss the pertinent institutional and
          legal issues<P>

  <LI> Identify and characterize the principal industry
          participants<P>

   <LI> Identify and characterize the principal government
          participants<P>

   <LI> Identify and characterize the principal university
          participants.</UL><P>

In addition, this study sought to distinguish between the
technologies and systems which are likely to be incorporated into
IVHS, and those which are more fantasy than reality.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR CONDUCTING STUDY</B><P>

Although there are several government-sponsored studies available
covering IVHS, there have been no multi-client technical/economic
market analyses of this important and potentially enormous new
industry. IVHS promises to be one of the largest and broadly based
new industries of the 21st century--and it appears to be getting
off to a roaring start in the '90s. It is important to have an
unbiased and thorough analysis of this new industry in order to
make investment decisions, the consequences of which will carry
through well into the first two decades of the next century. IVHS
has the potential for developing into a multi-billion dollar
industry over the next five years, and certainly over the next ten
years. The U.S. government is providing enormous sums of money for
the development of IVHS technologies, and it seems very likely that
it will continue  to do so. IVHS may very well be the "bail-out" of
the defense industry, now that the Cold War has ended.<P>

Thus, IVHS is a budding and burgeoning industry that cannot be
ignored. Business Communications Co. is the first market
research firm to provide an independent analysis of the
technologies, applications, markets, and potential.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THIS STUDY</B><P>

This study comes at a critical time in the development of IVHS.
Companies and governments are seeking realistic evaluations of the
potential for IVHS technologies and applications. Is IVHS real or
a boondoggle? Or, how much and what parts of IVHS are feasible and
viable in the near term and mid term; are the long-term features of
IVHS doable? This timely BCC study seeks to answer these questions,
and provide a cogent discussion covering the reasons for its
conclusions. The study also provides convincing rationale for
continuing government support of these programs regardless of which
administration is in power.<P>

Foreign companies and programs are discussed and compared to U.S.
programs. Competition between foreign and U.S. IVHS industries is
also discussed in detail.<P>

The report provides a thorough analysis of the current and
potential markets for IVHS technologies and component systems.
Specifically, it:<P>

<UL>     <LI>  provides an assessment of relevant technologies<P>
     <LI>  provides market projections from 1992 through 2002<P>
     <LI>  characterizes potential applications<P>
     <LI>  discusses the major driving forces behind the development
          of the industry<P>
     <LI>  identifies niches of specific promise<P>
     <LI>  discusses the thorny institutional and legal issues<P>
     <LI>  provides a thorough and representative list of companies
          and organizations involved in IVHS<P>
     <LI>  provides brief company profiles.</UL><P>

<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

The information presented in this study was derived, in part, from
over 75 interviews with knowledgeable industry and government
sources. Due to the increasing worldwide nature and importance of
the industry, in addition to domestic sources, foreign sources were
contacted and worldwide information and specific market data, where
available, are included in this report. In all, over 150 companies
and organizations were surveyed. In addition, a thorough search of
the technical, trade, and government literature was conducted.<P>

Extensive BCC in-house resources were consulted and utilized where
appropriate. This study was conducted over a three-month period
ending in October 1992. Dollar market projections are given in
constant 1992 dollars unless otherwise noted.<P>


