<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GA-067 CONTROLLED/MODIFIED ATMOSPHERE PACKAGING
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GA-067 CONTROLLED/MODIFIED ATMOSPHERE PACKAGING</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>LARRY WANG</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This comprehensive study deals with all aspects of
modified/controlled atmosphere and vacuum packaging, and
includes elaborate treatment of processes, atmospheres used,
materials and types of containers used, as well as a description
of the types of products which can benefit from this form of
packaging.  1990-1995 consumption figures are used throughout
this report.<P>

This study is important because modified/controlled atmosphere
packaging is finally becoming an important factor in the overall
food packaging market and by 1995 should be the fastest growing
facet of this market.  This prognosis is based on the rapid
growth of material and process technologies, past Western
European experience and the great economic benefits of
MA/CA/vacuum packaging for foods such as meats, poultry,
produce, fruit and pasta.<P>


SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This is an in-depth study and a quantified description of
different aspects of MA/CA/vacuum packaging.  The study deals
with the advantages and disadvantages of different types of
packaging atmospheres and materials, applications, suppliers and
consumption figures for materials, containers and equipment.
End-use markets which benefit from MA/CA/vacuum packaging are
described and quantified.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

This report consists of four principal sections:

<MENU>     1. Overview<BR>
           2. Basic Systems - Technology<BR>
           3. Materials<BR>
           4. Markets</MENU><P>

In the Overview, the scope and major components of MA/CA/vacuum
packaging systems are described.  Terms related to gas packaging
are defined and the market structure for major system components
is delineated.  Products packaged in specific atmospheres as
well as gas selection criteria are listed. Overall consumption
of materials, gas blends and types of containers is quantified.
Packaging by the type of system (CAP, MAP, vacuum) is also
tabulated.  This section concludes with a discussion of
international dimensions of the gas packaging market.<P>

Basic Systems - Technology section deals in detail with
different atmospheres and the function of individual gases and
gas blends.  It also elaborates on the supplier market.  Gas
generation methods and gas consumption figures for bulk and
retail forms of packaging are provided.  The role and
performance of oxygen and carbon dioxide absorbers as well as
gas emitters and their suppliers are elaborated.<P>

Microbiological problems and safety concerns as pertaining to
MA/CA/vacuum packaging and refrigerated distribution are
described and related to specific products.<P>

Equipment used in MA/CA/vacuum packaging is described. Equipment
suppliers are listed and their products analyzed.  A brief
description of the sealing methods is provided because of the
crucial importance of sealing to the proper functioning of
MA/CA/vacuum packaging systems.<P>

Finally, the three basic modes of gas packaging are defined and
described, including the sous vide process which is a special
case of vacuum packaging.<P>

The section on Materials deals with basic forms of packaging
used for MA/CA/vacuum packaging -- films and trays -- as well as
with the different types of plastics and non-plastic materials
used.  Different types of mono-, multilayer and barrier films,
resins used and the types of containers made from films are
elaborated.  Trays, tray materials and complex systems using
trays and films are also described. In each case, the principal
suppliers and consumption figures for materials and types of
containers are tabulated.  The new smart films for breathable
products are discussed.<P>

The last section of the study deals with the end-use Markets
such as meats and poultry, fish, produce and fruits, pasta and
baked products, and miscellaneous products including non-foods.
Specific examples of packaging for individual products are
provided as well as consumption figures by units, volume of
packaging materials used, types of containers, types of systems
and materials used.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION AND TARGET AUDIENCE</B><P>

This study is designed for manufacturers of packaging materials,
especially films and trays, gas atmospheres and packaging
equipment, as well as companies which sell basic packaging
systems or specialize in gas packaging.  It will also be of
great help to industry analysts and investment firms that
specialize in packaging and distribution of food products and
oxygen and moisture-sensitive non-food products.<P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Information sources for this study include numerous interviews
with the representatives of resin, film and tray manufacturers,
and suppliers of food gas packaging systems and packaging
equipment.  Other important sources of information were:
suppliers' literature, technical and commercial magazines,
government statistical publications and selected BCC Opportunity
Reports such as:<P>

<MENU>      P-063U   -    The Changing Plastic Film Business<BR>

      P-111    -    Multicomponent Films<BR>

      P-085N   -    What is New in Barrier Packaging<BR>

      P-106    -    Food and Medical Packaging Trays</MENU><P>



