<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
GA-077 NEW PACKAGE TYPES/CONFIGURATIONS FOR PROCESSED
CONVENIENCE FOODS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>GA-077 NEW PACKAGE TYPES/CONFIGURATIONS FOR PROCESSED
CONVENIENCE FOODS</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>DOROTHY KROLL</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

In a dynamic industry, this report analyzes and quantifies how
suppliers of  packaging materials  and preformed packages used
by processors  of prepared convenience foods are responding to
processors' changing  needs, interests,  and  preferences,  as
processors, in  turn, respond to shifting consumer demands for
packaging. The  prepared  foods  of  interest  include  quick-
cooking frozen,  chilled/refrigerated, shelf-stable foods in a
variety of packages that require different cooking methods, as
well as  these three  food types  marketed  in  microwave-only
packages. The  packaging materials  of  concern  are  plastic,
paperboard, glass, steel, and aluminum cans.<P>

Today's consumers  demand that  packages satisfy both personal
needs, shaped  by demographics and social trends, and those of
the product, as well as be consistent with prevailing societal
attitudes and  goals. Packages should have convenient features
that make food preparation and serving easier, yet respect the
environment by  having fewer  materials  added  to  the  waste
stream.   They should  be recyclable  or reusable.  Along with
these  demands   are  the  usual  expectations  that  packages
preserve food  quality and  resist  any  elements  that  could
affect food safety.<P>

Changes in packages have been made possible by improvements in
food processing,  package materials,  and configurations.  New
food processing methods have produced the need for packages to
become more heat-resistant, extend shelflife with little or no
chemical preservatives, and improve the quality of foods.<P>

Improvements in  package materials  have enabled  suppliers to
develop  packages   that  are  microwaveable,  cook-in/eat-in,
stronger,  lighter,   simpler  and  safer  to  use,  and  more
environmentally friendly.    Moreover,  material  improvements
have alleviated  some problems  created by  the use of certain
materials, such  as off-flavors,  off-aromas, and migration of
chemicals, as well as deficits of microwave oven cooking.<P>

Improvements in  package configurations  allow the development
of   convenience features, such as lids that are easy to open,
close, reclose,  and reseal, single-serve packages for portion
control, and  light-weight packages  for easy  portability for
consumption outside the home.<P>

The prepared  food packaging  industry is composed of material
suppliers and  package converters  of preformed  packages. For
some packages,  food  processors  can  choose  between  buying
preformed packages  or buying  the materials  and forming  the
package on-site at the food plant.<P>

This industry  is a highly fragmented segment of the packaging
industry, and  is very  competitive with  many companies vying
for their material or configuration to be the favored, generic
choice of  the majority  of food  processors.  Most  companies
confine themselves to supplying just one type of material that
can be used for one or more food types.<P>

As package materials wax and wane in popularity, some industry
leaders who  find their  material losing  favor have  begun to
move into  other, more  promising materials.    A metals maker
may  acquire   a  plastic   container  manufacturing  company.
Sometimes, material  suppliers will  try to  improve  a  given
material so  that it  matches the desired characteristics of a
competing material or at least addresses some of its deficits.
An example  of this  would be  an aluminum can maker trying to
make cans stronger and more durable like steel cans.<P>

In this  report, BCC has defined prepared convenience foods as
those foods  which are referred to as second-generation foods,
either because  of preparation, packaging, or a combination of
both. The  foods are fully prepared by a food processor before
packaging, distribution,  and sales,  and are ready-to-heat or
ready-to-eat either  cold or  at room  temperature.  The foods
may be  a whole  new food idea like a frozen stuffed sandwich,
or a  familiar canned  item like  sliced fruit  but in a small
plastic cup or aluminum can with easy open lid.<P>

Further  definitions  for  consumer  cooking  methods  include
packages that  require foods to be removed before microwave or
conventional cooking, dual ovenable packages for microwave and
conventional  ovens,   cookable  packages  for  microwave  and
stovetop cooking,  packages  for  microwave-only  cooking,  or
packages that require no heating/cooking for foods.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

This report was designed to accomplish the following
objectives:<P>

<LI>To  identify   specific  areas  of  interest  and  concern  to
consumers  regarding  packages,  and  analyze  how  they  have
contributed to  the development  of attitudes  that, in  turn,
have  shaped   consumer  demands  for  package  materials  and
configurations.<P>

<LI>To  gain   an  understanding  of  consumer  demands  that  can
influence  purchasing  decisions,  in  order  to  suggest  the
linkage between  packages and foods and consumer acceptance or
rejection thereof.<P>

<LI>To learn  how certain  consumer attitudes,  as well as social,
economic, regulatory, and technological trends, help or hinder
package suppliers  who seek  to satisfy  the demands  of  food
processors.<P>

<LI>To analyze  the role  of suppliers  and the  structure of  the
supplier  industry,   and  suggest  the  directions  in  which
suppliers must  move in  order to  help food processors market
products in  packages that  consumers  will  accept  as  safe,
convenient, and "green."<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

BCC sought to provide insight into one key question:  How, and
with what  types of  package materials and configurations, can
suppliers serve food processors interested in meeting consumer
demands for  packages that  protect both  food quality and the
environment, while delivering optimum convenience?<P>

The study  will discuss  the  social,  demographic,  economic,
environmental, and  educational influences that shape consumer
preferences for  package materials  and  configurations.    It
analyzes the  confluence of  these market  forces and how they
either advance  or hamper  development and growth of packages.
It suggests  how these  preferences influence  buying patterns
that ultimately  affect the increase or decrease in demand for
the foods themselves.<P>

It will  describe food  processing methods,  how each  package
material and  configuration succeeds or fails to withstand the
rigors of  each, what  package choices  are open  to the  food
processor on  the basis of each method, how the choices affect
the degree  of consumer  convenience in  cooking the food, and
how food  processors offer  consumers cooking  flexibility  by
packaging the same foods differently.<P>

It will  discuss the  packaging needs  of each  food type, the
advantages  and   disadvantages  of   each  material  and  its
appropriateness for  each food  type.   It looks  at how  each
package configuration  can serve  each food  type and specific
application.       Materials    covered    include    plastic,
paper/paperboard, metal and glass.<P>

It will  delineate how  a food processor views each package in
terms of  image and  status for the product and as a marketing
tool to  attract consumers, how new types of packages can help
food processors  save  costs,  and  how  new  packages  expand
applications and  markets that  heretofore  might  have  posed
economic or technological constraints on food processors.<P>

It will  discuss material  preferences,  e.g.,  metal,  glass,
plastic.   Types of  metals, glass  or plastics  aren't broken
down by type.<P>

The insights  and conclusions  reached in this study can be of
special value to suppliers of materials and package converters
for the  food processing  industry. The  information  provided
here can  be useful  for developing  packages that enable food
processors to  stay competitive  and maintain  or gain  market
share.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

BCC has confined this report to examining prepared convenience
foods defined  as those quick-cooking foods that serve as part
or full  meals rather  than snacks  such as popcorn. The first
section deals  with frozen  food packages.  The second section
discusses packages  for chilled/refrigerated  foods. The third
section reports  on  shelf-stable  foods.  The  final  section
encompasses  frozen,   chilled,  and   shelf-stable  foods  in
packages that are designed only for use in the microwave oven.<P>

The first  three sections  include discussion of microwaveable
foods and packages as one cooking method among many.  However,
the final section is devoted exclusively to foods reformulated
for the  quick cooking  time of  the microwave  oven and/or in
packages designed  to interact  with the  foods.  These  foods
should not  be cooked  with any  other method because the food
processor  ensures  optimum  quality  only  with  the  special
formula or package design.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGIES</B><P>

BCC describes each package material and configuration for each
food type,  then evaluates  each in  terms of  its  value  and
utility to  food processors.  A discussion  follows about  how
food processors  are trying  to satisfy consumer demands, what
that implies  in terms of requirements from suppliers, and how
suppliers are  trying to  comply  with  the  demands  of  food
processors. Estimates  and projections  of package  volume and
sales for  each material  and  configuration  were  calculated
according to  several factors:  expected growth  or decline in
the consumption  of certain  foods and  shipments  of  various
types of containers; patterns and trends in package usage; and
the  influence   of  market   forces  on   each  material  and
configuration.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

BCC first  conducted an  extensive  review  of  the  secondary
literature with materials gathered from the library, trade and
professional associations,  government and  industry  sources.
This review  was  then  followed  up  with  some  one  hundred
telephone  interviews  with  personnel  in  marketing,  sales,
technical,  and   research  and   development  departments  at
material suppliers, package converters, and food processors.<P>


