<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-085N  WHAT IS NEW IN BARRIER PACKAGING FOR FOOD
AND NON-FOOD PRODUCTS?
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2> P-085N  WHAT IS NEW IN BARRIER PACKAGING FOR FOOD
AND NON-FOOD PRODUCTS?</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>LARRY WANG</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B> GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This detailed report deals with the all-plastic barrier packaging in all its
forms: monolayer, multilayer -- coextruded, coated and laminated systems.
Both rigid and flexible forms of packaging are elaborated. In addition, some
background information on metallized plastic and other forms of packaging
is provided. The overall packaging container market is schematically
represented in the Introductory Figure.<P>


<B>INTRODUCTORY FIGURE
THE PACKAGING CONTAlNER MARKET</B><P>

This study was undertaken because of the explosive growth in the
consumption of different barrier resin packaging systems and the
proliferation of new processing technologies, types of barriers and a new
appraisal of how much barrier must be provided for different types of
products.<P>

<B>SCOPE & FORMAT</B><P>

This study is an in-depth elaboration and quantified description of various
types of all-plastic barrier food and non-food packaging systems and their
use in different markets. The study deals with processing, properties,
applications, markets, manufacturers and consumption figures of resins
and processes and describes the end-markets. Forecasts are made through
1995.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

This study is divided into five major sections:<P>

1. Overview
2. Barrier and Structural Resins
3. Adhesive Tie layers
4. Multilayer Film and Sheet Technology
5. Markets for Barrier Packaging<P>

In the Overview, the scope and major issues are described. Food and non-
food packaging as well as types of barrier resins are delineated. Monolayer
and multilayer -- coextruded, coated and laminated systems are described
and quantified. Flexible and rigid packaging is described and discussed.<P>

New trends in the development of barrier and structural polymers are
discussed and the consumption statistics for major types of resins are
provided. Inter-layer adhesives are defined and briefly discussed.<P>

Technical aspects of barrier packaging systems are related to the type of
processing: hot-filling, retorting, aseptic and CAP-MAP. The use of
containers and plastic resins is related to the type of processing and is
quantified. Finally, the food preservation techniques, material technologies,
markets and distribution systems as well as shelf-life considerations are
briefly elaborated.<P>

The section on barrier and structural resins deals with different types of
barrier resins and their use in monolayer and multilayer packaging
systems. Multilayer packaging is further subdivided into coextruded,
coated and laminated systems. The principal barrier resins discussed are
PVdC, EVOH, acrylonitrile-MA, nylons and such polymers as modified
polyesters, acrylic derivatives and liquid crystal polymers. Silica coatings of
plastic containers, as well as oxygen scavenging systems are also
elaborated.<P>

Principal barrier resins are described in detail, including properties, types
available as related to usage, applications, market structure and
consumption statistics.<P>

One new type of chemical barrier packaging, known as Oxbar, is also
briefly treated in this section of the study. The chapter concludes with a
brief description of structural resins used in barrier packaging systems.
These include: polypropylene, polyethylenes, nylon, polyester, polystyrene
and polycarbonate.<P>

The section on "Tie Layer Adhesive" resins deals with the adhesive
properties of such resins, their consumption, and with different domestic
and foreign manufacturers.
The section on Multilayer Technology deals briefly with the coated and
laminated barrier systems and extensively with the coextruded systems.<P>

Different types of coextrusion feedblock systems and their respective merits
are elaborated, as well as the chief parameters involved in the control of
viscosity variations, gauges amd film uniformity.<P>

Principal purveyors of feedblock coextrusion systems, as well as the
developments in thermoforming technology for barriar containers, are also
discussed.<P>

This section of the study concludes with the description of integrated
barrier packaging systems and elaboration of the economic factors involved.<P>

The last section of the study deals with the markets. The following areas
related to markets for barrier packaging are elaborated and quantified:<P>

1. Overall packaging markets and Plastics share of the market.
2. Barrier packaging and its share of plastics packaging.
3. Food and non-food packaging.
4. Flexible and rigid barrier packaging.
5. Types of resins used in barrier packaging.
6. Markets by the level of barrier required.
7. Type of packaging by food processing.
8. Submarkets served by barrier packaging.<P>

Finally, after a brief discussion of food preservation techniques, individual
food markets are elaborated.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION AND TARGET AUDIENCE</B><P>

This study is designed for the manufacturers of barrier resins, barrier
packaging systems, and manufacturers of related equipment as well as for
companies which specialize in packaging. It will also be of great assistance
to industry analysts and investment firms that specialize in plastic
packaging of food and non-food products.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Information sources for this study include interviews with numerous
representatives of manufacturer barrier resins, barrier packaging systems
and equipment, as well as with several food and non-food packagers who
use all-plastic barrier packaging. Other important sources were suppliers'
literature, technical and commercial magazines, government statistical
publications and selected BCC Opportunity Reports such as:<P>

P-085 -- Coextruded Barrier Packaging
P-089 -- Hot-Fill & Retort Packaging
P-111 -- Multicomponent Film and Sheet
P-107 -- Medical Packaging
P-106 -- Plastic Packaging Trays<P>



