<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-130  THE FLEXIBLE POUCH BUSINESS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-130  THE FLEXIBLE POUCH BUSINESS</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>HOWARD KIBBEL</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>OBJECTIVES OF THE STUDY</B><P>

It is  apparent to  everyone in  the broadly-defined packaging
business that  concern for  the environment  will not abate in
the 1990s.  It will grow as we examine our living patterns and
our commercial  practices from the standpoint of the impact on
resources.  The EPA, charged with the responsibility of caring
for the  environment, is pursuing a policy of source reduction
and development of recycling infrastructures for all packaging
materials.   Certain forms  of packaging  will meet  this dual
criteria and  thrive in the marketplace.  Others will fail one
or both  aspects of this test and gradually yield market share
to  other,   more   economic   and   environmentally-favorable
packaging media.<P>

One  form   of  plastic  packaging  that  has  been  available
virtually since  the dawn of the commercial plastic era is the
flexible pouch.   While  some products are ideally packaged in
rigid containers  (e.g., cans,  cases, tubs, trays, etc.) made
of either  plastic materials  or non-plastics,  virtually  all
food and many non-food products are suitably packaged in small
or large  pouches produced  from single-  or multi-layer film.
The  contents  can  be  liquid,  semi-liquid,  or  solid,  and
dispensed all at once or over time.  As the durability and the
barrier properties  of these  pouches  were  improved  and  as
processing and  filling equipment  evolved to  the point where
they could accommodate high-speed production lines, they began
to compete,  not only  against other  flexible packaging media
(e.g., paper  and plastic  bags), but  against rigid packaging
media (e.g., metal and plastic cans) as well.<P>

What are  the direct  and indirect  economic and environmental
advantages of  the plastic  pouch today?   What  has been  its
recent growth performance (in the 1980s) and what is it likely
to be  in the  near future  (through 1996)?   How much of this
past and  anticipated future  growth is  derived from existing
markets and  how much  from new markets, replacing alternative
plastic and  non-plastic packaging  media?   And,  critically,
what advantages  (e.g., weight,  thin-walls, low-cost  resins,
processing and  filling speeds,  recyclability) does the pouch
realistically offer  the packaging company today facing slower
economic growth in the short term and heightened environmental
awareness in the long term?<P>

These are  the issues  which we  address in  this report.   We
believe our judgments of a quantitative and qualitative nature
to be  both accurate  and candid, based on the wide network of
information gathered  and industry  participants consulted  in
the course  of our  research.   For example,  we would contend
that from the perspective of the first part of the EPA's waste
management  program  -  source  reduction  -  the  thin-walled
flexible pouch  is in  an excellent  position to  gain  market
share.  However, from the standpoint of the second objective -
recyclability -  the pouch  offers no distinct advantages over
rigid plastic  or most  other packaging  media, and its growth
potential may be restricted for that reason.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT OF THE STUDY</B><P>

This study  views pouch  production and  consumption  patterns
from all  aspects, including  the types  of pouches  currently
available, the  equipment used  to fabricate  and  fill  these
pouches, the  various resins  used as  substrate  and  barrier
materials, the  key applications  in the  primary markets, the
economics of  pouch production, and the past/future pattern of
consumption--in absolute  terms and as a share of the entire
spectrum of packaging materials.<P>

Interestingly,  many   of  the   resin  suppliers,   equipment
manufacturers, film  suppliers, and  film  converters  in  the
field make  little distinction  between a pouch and a bag.  In
the absence  of an  industry consensus  for what constitutes a
pouch, we  have decided  to define  a pouch  as a bag which is
formed on-line  during the  filling stage,  usually with  more
hermetic seals than typically found in a bag.  It is made from
heat-sealing film  or a  combination of  such film with coated
paper or  foil, then  sealed at  the sides  and at the bottom.
The main  distinction, therefore, between a pouch and a bag is
that the  latter unit is fabricated completely before filling.
In addition,  there are  several other packaging media that do
not fall neatly into the pouch or bag categories which we have
elected to  include as well - namely, the bag-in-box container
and the boil-in-bag concept.<P>

The quantitative  data that  we offer  for the  various  pouch
types and pouch applications relate to a base year (1991), the
previous and  the next year (1990 and 1992), and a year in the
medium-term future  (1996).   Forecasts are provided and five-
year (1991-1996)  average annual growth rates are projected in
each case.   The  quantitative characteristics  of the various
pouches,  as   supplied  by  the  film  converters  and  pouch
fabricators, will relate to 1991 conditions.<P>

Our focus  is not  only on  the pouch  and its  current/likely
future position  in the  packaging industry,  but also  on the
evolution of  key players  in this  market  niche.    We  have
consulted with and identified key players throughout the chain
of pouch  production  and  consumption  -  the  substrate  and
barrier   film    suppliers,    the    processing    equipment
manufacturers, the  film converters, and the pouch fabricators
who are  the major package end-users of both food and non-food
products.   From all  of these inputs we feel that we are able
to pinpoint  the leading  resins  and  pouch  structures,  the
leading processing technologies, and the leading companies who
will influence the grow of pouches in the 1990s.<P>


<B>STUDY METHODOLOGY</B><P>

In addition  to telephone interviews with primary players from
each level  of pouch  production and consumption, we were able
to gather data and insights into the pouch and the future from
published  sources   such  as   trade  associations,  industry
conferences,  trade  publications,  and  government  agencies.
There is  no consensus  source of  information on  the volume,
value, and  industry break-down  of  pouch  consumption.    We
developed our  estimates by  merging  existing  data  on  film
demand with  quantified and non-quantified assessments offered
by key industry participants.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

This study  is intended  for use  by existing  resin and  film
suppliers and  packaging end-users,  as well  as by  companies
seeking to identify the opportunities and the growth prospects
in the  pouch business.  Plastics industry participants (e.g.,
resin  and  film  suppliers)  will  gain  some  insights  into
evolving  plastic  material  and  inter-material  competition.
Film converters  will be  interested to learn of technological
changes which  will impact  on the cost and characteristics of
pouches.   Packaging end-users  will be  able to  evaluate the
evolving cost/performance  of  the  pouch  vis-*-vis  all  the
alternative packaging  media that they either use or could use
in the various product categories.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>

This comprehensive  analysis of the plastic pouch market is an
extension of  the many recent multiclient reports in the field
of plastic  packaging media  and markets  from BCC's  Plastics
Research Division.   We cite the following reports that may be
of  interest  to  companies  in  the  broadly-defined  plastic
packaging marketplace:<P>

<MENU>P-126   The Environmental Impact on Plastic
        Packaging,                               September 1991<P>

