<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-137  BARRIER AND SELECTIVE BARRIER PLASTIC-BASED
MATERIALS AND STRUCTURES FOR PACKAGING
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-137  BARRIER AND SELECTIVE BARRIER PLASTIC-BASED
MATERIALS AND STRUCTURES FOR PACKAGING
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>YATIN THAKORE, Ph.D.
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>PURPOSE OF THIS STUDY
</B><P>

This study examines a very important segment of the packaging
industry--that of polymeric barrier packaging. It analyzes the
technology, current status and future trends of barrier and
selective barrier products.<P>

The packaging industry itself has been around for centuries, and
even barrier packaging in the form of metal or glass containers has
been around for quite some time. Even polymeric high barrier
material, such as PVDC, has been utilized since the sixties, and
the EVOH was first commercialized in the early seventies. However,
the improvements in the coextrusion technology, which enabled
efficient assembly of multilayer structures in a single pass, came
about only about 15 years ago, and the barrier plastics business
got a major boost.<P>

Use of plastic-based barrier and selective barrier structures has
grown in recent years for applications in food, pharmaceutical,
medical, chemical, and industrial packaging. Barrier structures
provide needed protection of contents, while at the same time
minimizing the escape of inside constituents. Selective barriers,
on the other hand, allow passage of gases and vapors, while barring
the passage of liquids.<P>

Today, far from being a settled business, this industry is changing
and still evolving. The activities are on several fronts in which
newer materials and structures are still needed. For example, as of
yet an ideal polymeric barrier material does not exist. Moisture
susceptibility, high cost, the difficulty in recycling or disposal,
and inadequate barrier protection are some of the problems with the
current materials. Further, coated structures such as silicon oxide
coatings may challenge some of the polymeric materials,
particularly as their costs start coming down.<P>

Some of the other areas of activities and innovations are blending
incompatible polymers to create high barriers at moderate cost,
increasing efforts at source reduction, and improving the
recyclability of the polymers.<P>

This study looks at the markets and technologies, and attempts to
identify the future course of this business. Polymeric barrier
products include both oxygen and chemical barrier materials such as
HDPE. In selective or permeable barriers, we have included
technology and markets for gas permeable films used in the
healthcare markets, and for the controlled atmosphere packaging
area (CAP) being used to pack items such as produce and baked
goods. Although this study is aimed at polymeric barriers, we have
included a short chapter on non-polymeric barrier coatings on
plastic films (metal and oxide coatings).<P>


<B>TARGETED AUDIENCE</B><P>

This study will be useful to those in the packaging industry.  It
provides them with an understanding of the markets, trends,
technologies and the overall structure of the industry. Executives
of companies involved in the manufacture or distribution of
packaging products or supplies, including materials, equipment, or
services, as well as those end users involved in packaging their
goods, will find this a useful resource. It will be valuable also
to prospective entrants to this business, organizations promoting
or serving the packaging business, analysts, venture capital and
other, investors along with industry watchers.<P>


<B>SCOPE OF THIS STUDY</B><P>

This in-depth BCC analysis examines the materials, applications,
and the markets for barrier and selective polymeric materials and
structures used in packaging. Structures analyzed include flexible
and rigid, and monolayer and multilayer. Non-polymeric surface-
coated structures (silicon oxide and metal) are also briefly
covered. Market projections through 1998 are provided.<P>

The materials include the gas (particularly oxygen) barrier
materials, and the chemical barrier material HDPE, which is a poor
oxygen barrier. The oxygen barrier materials covered (most of which
also have excellent solvent barrier properties and are used in
chemical packaging as well) are polyvinylidene chloride (PVDC),
ethylene vinyl alcohol copolymer, (EVOH), nylons, acrylonitrile
methacrylate copolymer (AN-MA), and other specialty polymers such
as certain copolyesters.<P>

Materials with oxygen permeability of below 2 (ml-mil)/(100
sq.in.-day-atm) under dry and moderate humidity conditions are
termed barrier materials; those below 0.1 are termed high barrier
materials, those between 0.1-2 are termed moderate barrier
materials. EVOH, and PVDC are high barrier materials, and the rest
are moderate barriers.<P>

Selective barriers included are those that allow relatively easy
movement of gases, while restricting the passage of liquid. These
include Tyvek polyolefin films used in healthcare packaging and
permeable films used in controlled atmosphere packaging (CAP),
which allow products such as the produce to 'breathe'.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

Research for this study consisted of extensive study of published
literature, BCC resources, and interviews with industrial,
university and government sources.<P>

Published information was searched via databases covering medical,
biological, chemical and business fields. Additionally dozens of
books, government reports, conference proceedings, company annual
reports and related marketing reports were consulted.<P>

Primary data collection was via interviews with industrial
manufacturers, end users, market watchers, and officials of
government and business associations.<P>

The information was assimilated and discussed among the BCC staff.
The basis and assumptions behind projected and forecasted markets
are clearly defined in this report.<P>


<B>NOTE ON UNITS</B><P>

There are a number of tables throughout the report which list the
permeability values of gases or water vapor. Unless otherwise
noted, the gas permeability units in this report are (cc-
mil)/(atm-day-100 sq.in.), and for water vapor (cc-
mil)/(100 sq.in.-day). Conversion factors for other units
are given in Appendix A.<P>


<B>BIOGRAPHY/QUALIFICATIONS</B><P>

The project analyst for this report, Dr. Yatin Thakore, has 13
years of industrial experience in the areas of polymeric materials.
Dr. Thakore obtained his doctorate degree from the University of
Utah in Materials Science and Engineering, with specialization in
polymers and biomaterials. He holds several U.S. and international
patents in the fields of polymeric materials, their structures, and
applications.<P>


<B>ACKNOWLEDGEMENT</B><P>

This report relies extensively on the original research and
analysis of Larry Wang, who passed away earlier this year. As a
senior market analyst at BCC, he had done many outstanding studies
on various aspects of packaging. We are deeply saddened by his
loss, and will surely miss his insight into the packaging business.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC WORK</B><P>

The following reports published by BCC are related to this subject
and are available from BCC:<P>

<UL>GA- 067  Controlled/Modified Atmosphere Packaging<BR>
   P-130 The Plastic Pouch Business: Materials, Markets,
Technologies<BR>
