<CENTER><H3><I>SUMMARY</I></H3>
</CENTER>
In this report we have examined the overall market for the
polymeric barrier and selective barrier materials and structures.
These materials are used in the food, chemical, and healthcare
sectors.<P>

The barrier polymers are defined as those with oxygen permeability
of less than 2 (cc-mil)/(100 sq.in.-atm-day) which are used
for their gas and chemical barriers, and HDPE used only for
chemical packaging.<P>

The overall market for gas and chemical barrier polymers, tie
resins, and structural polymers is estimated at 3,071 pounds
(valued at $1,571 million) in 1993, estimated to grow  at 7% to
4,144 pounds (valued at $2,236 million) in 1998.<P>


The market for these is summarized in Summary Table A.<P>


<H3><CENTER>SUMMARY TABLE A</H3><P>

        RESINS IN POLYMERIC BARRIER STRUCTURES -- MARKETS<BR>

            (Domestic market at Manufacturer's Level)<P></CENTER>

<PRE>
RESIN TYPE              LBS            IN MILLIONS      AAGR %
                    IN MILLIONS        OF DOLLARS      '93-'98

                    1993    1998      1993      1998

*Barrier            1981    2865      1008     14357
Structural          1020    1451       423       605
Tie                   70      98       140       196      7
TOTAL               3071    4414      1571      2236      7


 *In constant 1993 dollars
 +Includes chemical barrier HDPE
</PRE>
The breakdown of the barrier resin market is provided in Summary
Table B. Chemical barrier HDPE accounts for the bulk of the market
(84% by weight, about 50% by value). About 80% of the HDPE is
untreated, whereas the remainder is surface treated, blended, or
used in multilayer composites to boost the solvent barrier
properties. Use of HDPE as a chemical barrier packaging material
will increase at a healthy 8%, helped by switching from metal and
glass containers for chemicals, and from metal to plastic for
automobile fuel tanks.<P>

The oxygen barrier materials will also show a healthy 7% growth
rate for the next five years. Whereas the PVDC markets have
matured, EVOH will continue to show a strong 11% average growth
over the next five years. Growth of the other materials will also
be healthy: nylon at 8%, and nitrile polymers at 6%. The use of
these oxygen barrier polymers is divided between the food sector
(76%), chemical (16%), and healthcare (8%). The growth in the
chemical segment will be especially strong, at 12%, caused by
continued switching to plastics, due to toughened air quality and
safety standards requiring more barrier packaging, and also by
switching to plastic fuel tanks.<P>


<H3><CENTER>SUMMARY TABLE B</H3><P>

                     BARRIER RESINS MARKETS<BR>
           (Domestic markets at manufacturer's level)<P></CENTER>

<PRE>
