<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>INSULATION MATERIALS AND MARKETS:        COMPETITION , APPLICATIONS, TRENDS</TITLE></HEAD><BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=Left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO"><CENTER><H2>E-057: INSULATION MATERIALS AND MARKETS:                          COMPETITION , APPLICATIONS, TRENDS</H2>
<HR><P>    
                         
<I>Frank Renaud</I><BR>
Project Analyst<P>


<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY OBJECTIVES</B>


<P>This report presents a quantitative analysis of the competition among
thermal insulation materials used within the residential and nonresidential
construction industry.  It focuses on the competition within each market
and assesses sales trends over the next 5 and 10 years.  It explains those
factors that we expect will contribute to the gains of some materials and the
losses of others.  Our analysis emphasizes relative price differentials and
real and/or perceived technological advantages offered by different materials.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B>


<P>During the last five years, the construction industry has been in the
doldrums as the recession of 1991 and 1992 played havoc with the housing
market.  Housing starts were down from 1.376 million units in 1989 to
1.014 million in 1992.  Single-family home starts fell to 840,000 in 1992
from 1.003 million in 1989 and the roof over starts of multifamily units
simply caved in.  In 1989, those multifamily units accounted for 38.4% of
total starts.  By 1992,  that ratio had declined to 14.2%.  It had dropped to a
low of 12.5% in 1993.<P>


<P>Existing home sales also declined steadily in 1989, 1990, and 1991.  So did
expenditures for residential repairs and alterations.  The latter dropped by
over 16% in 1991 alone.<P>

<P>To make matters worse for the construction industry, the private office and
industrial plant boom of the 1980s came to an abrupt end at the beginning
of the 1990s.  Plagued by high vacancy rates in every part of the country,
builders simply stopped erecting more skyscrapers, office buildings,
manufacturing facilities, etc.<P>


<P>Unfortunately, data for sales of insulation materials for that period are at
best sketchy and far from being reliable.  We are nevertheless told that the
impact on such markets as ceiling, attic, wall, crawl space, and flat roof
insulation materials dropped drastically.  Sales prospects disappeared and
layoffs and bankruptcies spread throughout the industry.<P>  


<P>On the technology front, new products made their appearance mostly as a
result of the announced ban of the production of CFCs, a blowing agent
used in such materials as polyisocyanurate, polyurethane, and polystyrene
insulation materials.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B>


<P>In this report, we answer such questions as which material is gaining
ground within each of the markets studied.  Which one will dominate by
1999 and 2004 and for what reasons?  We believe that sales and strategic
planning professionals within the housing and insulation materials
industries will greatly benefit from our analysis.  The information included
in this report will also prove to be an invaluable guide for any analysis of
future sales or for planning capital investment projects.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B>


<P>The study begins with an overview of the housing market, past, present,
and future.  Emphasis is put on demographic changes that augur well for
housing over the next 5 to 10 years.  This section is followed by an overview
of the thermal insulation materials industry, the technical and thermal
aspects of such materials, the range of materials available, the price
differentials found for those materials, and the recently enacted government
restriction imposed for the manufacturing of some of those materials.  A 5-
and 10-year forecast concludes that section.  This section is followed by an
analysis of each of the most important insulation materials.  The topics
covered include their manufacturing process, the technical properties of
each material, their end uses, and the most important producers.  A 5- and
10-year forecast concludes each analysis.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B>


<P>A study of this kind relies heavily on published data and on the expertise of
professionals in the field.  The insight provided by those experts is most
appreciated.  We also wish to thank the professionals of the several trade
associations we contacted.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B>

<UL>

<LI>P-207R    Materials for Sidings, Windows, Doors, and Roofing
<LI>P-120R    Polymeric Foams, A Huge Sub Industry
<LI>P-211          The current Status of Plastic Recycling
<LI>E-067     Non-Utility Power Generation
</UL>
<P>

