<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-027U : PLASTICS VERSUS PAPER & PAPERBOARD
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-027U : PLASTICS VERSUS PAPER & PAPERBOARD
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Frank Renaud
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This report focuses on the quantitative analysis of the competition
between paper and plastics between 1989 and 1993.  It reviews the
production and sales of the main grades of paper and paperboard and
assesses the tonnage gained or lost during the five-year period. 
It explains, in detail, those factors that contributed the most to
those gains or losses and emphasizes the role played by competing
plastic products.  A forecast through 2004 is included.<P>



<b>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

Material or product substitution is not a new phenomenon.  Indeed,
we can argue that such substitution is at the very heart of
progress.   New technologies, differences in relative prices, new
government regulations, and the desire to be more productive are
just some of the reasons why the search for new ideas, new
products, and new materials goes on.  During the last two decades,
paper producers have learned the hard way the meaning of
competition from new materials.  They have experienced the
onslaught of a wide range of plastic products, an onslaught that
has seriously affected their own productive capacity.  Whether it
be T-shirt grocery bags or HDPE milk containers, the demand for
several paper products has suffered.<P>


The result has been that, during most of the 1980s, plastic
products gained market share, often at the expense of paper
products.  That was particularly true in the packaging and wrapping
areas.  Whether we discuss boxes, bags, or wrapping material, there
was always a plastic film or container that could do the job more
efficiently and more cheaply.<P>


In a previous report (BCC report P-027N, Plastics vs. Paper),
issued five years ago, we forecasted that the competition between
the two materials had more or less run its course.  At the time, we
believed that successful packaging needed to draw from the
strengths of both materials.  Hence, the movement to replace one
material for the other would come to an end during the 1990s and
both would grow in tandem.<P>

We also thought that an energy crisis was in the offing, a crisis that would adversely affect the plastics industry.  Though the crisis has not yet manifested itself the way we thought it would, that is, through substantially higher energy prices, it seems that it is only a matter of time before that happens.  The U.S. is now more dependent than ever on foreign oil, and the booming economies of India, China, Southeast Asia and South America are depleting the readily available sources of
supplies.  There is a time bomb ticking and it is only a matter of
time before it goes off.<P>

We also thought that the competition between paper and plastics would slow down because plastic was perceived as a nonrecyclable material.  We were partly right.  There has been a strong movement during the last five years against the use of plastic products for the very reason that those products contribute unfairly to our stock of post-consumer waste. 
Significant strides have been made to recycle plastic containers,
especially milk and soda bottles.  Other products are being
recycled but the pace of progress is much slower.  Paper, on the
other hand, has never received the bad press to which plastic was
subjected.<P>  



<b>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY</B><P>

In this update, we take an extensive look at the developments over
the last five years.  We believe that those involved in the
production or sales of either plastic or paper products that
compete with one another will greatly benefit from our analysis. 
These professionals may be involved with the production or sales of
bags, boxes, or wrapping materials of all types and sizes.  The
information included in this report will prove to be an invaluable
guide for any analysis of future sales or for planning capital
investment projects.<P>



<b>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The study includes an analysis of the competition for the following
products: cover, envelope and label papers; shipping, grocery,
shopping, and merchant bags; corrugated boxes, folding cartons, and
bleached boxboard for milk and other food services.  In each case,
a quantitative analysis of the tonnage gained or lost is provided,
together with the major factors that have contributed to the gains
and losses.  An 11-year forecast concludes each section.<P> 

<b>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

A study of this kind relies heavily on hard data and on the
expertise of professionals in the field.  The insight provided by
those experts is most appreciated.  We also wish to thank the
several associations that have contributed most generously with
their data and their interpretation.<P>

<b>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>

