<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-031X:  FILLERS AND EXTENDERS FOR PLASTICS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-031X:  FILLERS AND EXTENDERS FOR PLASTICS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>NORMA CORBITT
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>
<I>ANNA CRULL
</I><BR>
PROJECT DIRECTOR
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY
</B><P>

This technical/marketing study has been prepared as an in-depth
analysis to forecast and track significant changes in the market
for fillers and extenders used in plastics.  BCC has conducted this
study in order to update the current status of fillers and
extenders for plastics commonly used in the U.S., both thermosets
and thermoplastics, and assess the growth potential of these
materials over a five-year period extending to 1998.  Our key
objective is to present an analysis of the current and potential
market for fillers and extenders in plastics.<P>


<b>HISTORY OF THE MARKET</B><P>

Traditionally used as bulking agents, fillers now tend to be more
functional, as compounding techniques become increasingly sophisticated.  Today's fillers and extenders for plastics not only bulk,
but enhance and modify specific physical properties.  Enhancement
of desirable physical properties has produced functional, semi-reinforcing fillers that now compete with both resins via replacement and with traditional reinforcers, such as fibrous glass
and other composites, by reducing reinforcing and formulation
costs.<P>


<b>SCOPE OF THIS REPORT</B><P>

The scope of this report includes an overall view of the fillers
and extenders in plastics market.  This report both quantifies and
qualifies data gathered on this market.  Data are analyzed for
trends and economic indicators affecting the demand for plastic
fillers and extenders.<P>

This report is divided into three parts.  The first part includes
an overview of fillers and extenders in plastics as well as a
review of the current status of the industry, its structure and its
competitive aspects.  The second part of the report covers filled
polymer systems and filled resin applications, while the third part
of the report delves into the market for the various types of
fillers and extenders.<P>

The common filled thermosets and thermoplastics are covered in this
report as well as some of the common elastomers.  Rubber, latexes,
polymer-based papers, paints and thin-film coatings are not
included.  In this report, filler refers to solid or powdered
mineral, synthetic or organic-based materials.  Extenders refer to
plasticizer-like, liquid or semi-liquid additives used for bulking.
Multi-functional pigments, such as calcium carbonate, titanium
dioxide and carbon black, are included, as well as such semi-
reinforcing functional fillers as mica, microspheres and short
fiber glass fillers.  Not considered are the long fiber glasses,
carbon fibers, whiskers and other composites.<P>


<b>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

Much of the information for this technical/marketing report was
gathered through telephone conversations with supplier representatives, as well as industry and academic experts in the field of
filled polymers.  The balance of the information was gathered from
available government, trade and technical publications.  An online
data search was made of data bases to retrieve information and
cover all of the existing literature.  Licensing agreements,
company activities, patents and state-of-the-art technology were
evaluated.<P>

A review of the period 1988-1993 and predictions for 1993-1998 are
made from a synthesis of information gathered from the BCC
database.  Value projections are given in 1993 constant dollars for
U.S. sales only.  The average annual growth rates conform to the
convention for significant figures.  Where precise information was
not forthcoming, a consensus was made, using a formula of
reasonable assumptions and estimates based on a baseline obtained
from historical data.<P>


<b>VALUE OF THIS REPORT</B><P>

This comprehensive technical/marketing study will be a valuable
basic market reference and technology summary for the producers,
processors, manufacturers and others who may produce or are
considering producing plastic filling and extending compounds in
the U.S. market.  The plastics compounding industry can track
potential competition or analyze new resin/filler compatibilities
and opportunities.  Reinforcing plastic and composite manufacturers
and suppliers can use this technical/marketing report to assist in
evaluating the competitive functional fillers and extenders and
their market opportunities.<P>


<b>RELATED BCC WORK CREDENTIALS</B><P>

Current information on some portions of fillers in plastics is
covered on a monthly basis by BCC, Inc. in its newsletter:  "Flame
Retardancy News."  Related BCC, Inc. reports that may be of
interest include the following:<P>

<UL>C-020B--Antioxidants<BR>
     C-0094--Structural and Specialty Adhesives<BR>
     C-004U--Flame Retardant Chemicals<BR>
     P-067--Electrically Conductive Plastics:
               Current Developments and Future Markets<BR>
     GB-066U--EMI/RIF:  Materials and Technological Issues in the
               1990s<P></UL>

