<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-043X  THE COMPETITIVE PIPE INDUSTRY
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-043X  THE COMPETITIVE PIPE INDUSTRY
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>MARK DULLEA
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The building and construction industries are the major marketplaces for pipe.
The pipe industry thus finds itself firmly ensconced among those boom and bust
industries which ride the coattails of our nation's economic fortunes.  The
lackluster  economic growth in recent years has been hard on the building and
construction sector, and most segments of the pipe industry have shared in
these hard times.   As in other manufacturing sectors of the national economy,
retrenchment tactics have prevailed.<P>

Significant consolidation and rationalization of excess capacity has occurred
in some segments, while cost containment and improved process and quality
control measures have led to productivity gains and quality improvements
across the entire pipe industry.   Even for those segments of the business
that have experienced a gain in sales and market share, few have had the good
fortune to see those results settle to the bottom line as improved
profitability.<P>

This report endeavors to give the reader an accurate bearing on where the
industry is heading as we move into the middle of this decade.  The primary
objectives are:<P>

<UL> <LI>       To describe the industry, its importance and its future prospects.

  <LI>       To analyze the current and historical volume and value of shipments for
        each type of pipe material.

 <LI>        To forecast the volume and value for each type of pipe material
        through 1998.

 <LI>        To analyze the end use markets for each type of pipe material.

 <LI>        To analyze the changes impacting the industry.

 <LI>        To describe manufacturing methods and economics.

 <LI>        To describe recent technological developments and trends.

 <LI>        To discuss the driving forces influencing demand.

 <LI>        To analyze the primary competitive market categories and to
        determine the market share held by each competing material
        within those market categories.

  <LI>       To review exports, imports and apparent consumption.
 <LI>        To review international implications.

 <LI>        To discuss regulatory and environmental issues and concerns.<P></UL>

<B>REASONS FOR THIS STUDY</B><P>

Major changes that have taken place in the industry over the past five years
and the continuing winds of change  provide the impetus for this study.
Rationalization, restructuring and product and process improvements have
heightened competition between both differing and identical pipe materials.
Certain end uses are the focus of intense competition as producers fight to
retain or, as the case may be, increase market share; and productivity gains
have sharpened the competitiveness of the entire industry. Issues remain
unresolved with regard to the use of certain materials in certain
applications, and building codes continue to evolve.  The participants in this
industry need to be acutely aware of these developments to intelligently plan
for the future.<P>

This report brings these factors into focus and provides manufacturers,
distributors and users of pipe with the knowledge needed to make informed
decisions relating to investment, procurement or pipe material selection.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This report is intended to inform those companies involved in the production
of raw materials, the manufacture of pipe and pipe fittings, and
distributors, retailers and consumers of pipe.  The study is an analysis and
summation of interviews with hundreds of key industry officials, trade
associations and government agencies and a statistical compilation and
analysis of data obtained from these sources.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

Our subject is the Competitive Nature of the U.S. Pipe Industry and, in this
report, we define the industry as the  producers and  fabricators of pipe and
the markets which they serve.  BCC published an identically titled report in
1987 and this report brings the analysis "up to date".  The report is
logically divided into the following nine chapters:<P>

<UL> 1 - Introduction.  The reader is given the objectives, rationale, scope,
   methods and information sources for this report.<P>

2 - Summary.  This chapter gives a concise overview of the findings and
conclusions of the report.<P>

3 - Overview.  The industry and its relationship to the economy are described.
A brief historical perspective is given.<P>

4 - The Major Pipe Materials and Shipment Trends.  Each pipe material is described
and broken into its major product  subclassifications.  Volume and value data
are given for the years 1987 and 1993 and forecasts are made through 1998.<P>

5 - The Major Pipe Materials and End Uses.  Major uses of each pipe material are
analyzed and forecasts made through 1998.<P>

6 - Technological Issues.  This chapter describes manufacturing methods as well as
economics and important developments and changes.<P>

7 - International Implications.  The international aspects of the pipe industry
are discussed, including import/export statistics and apparent U.S.
consumption.  The influences of foreign investment and technology are covered.<P>

8 - Industry Structure and Competitive Markets.  The role of the distributor is
detailed.  The key competitive market categories are identified and
comprehensively analyzed.  The leading companies in each sector are named.<P>

9 - Regulatory and Environmental Issues.  A thorough analysis of current and
pending regulatory and environmental issues is made.<P></UL>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

The extensive research capabilities of the BCC staff were accessed to analyze
government and industry data on pipe consumption.  New technologies, market
developments and present and future trends were identified through patent and
literature searches and discussions with key industry sources.  Current
regulatory and environmental issues were ascertained through discussion with
industry sources, regulatory agencies and the U.S. Environmental Protection
Agency. International trade statistics were obtained from the U.S. Department
of Commerce. Manufacturing methods, process economics and major influences on
the industry were derived from discussions with a wide range of industry
sources.<P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

The substance of this report is based on interviews with principal
participants in the industry. Over 200 organizations were contacted including
raw material suppliers, pipe manufacturers, pipe distributors, pipe consumers,
federal and state governmental agencies and standards, and code making
organizations.  The U.S. Department of Commerce and various industry trade
groups were resources for historical data on the volume and value of
shipments.<P>


