<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-051U  HIGH TEMPERATURE PLASTICS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-051U  HIGH TEMPERATURE PLASTICS</H2>

<HR><P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>CONTEXT OF THE REPORT</B><P>

It has become axiomatic in the plastics industry to regard the
development of new resins as too capital-intensive, expensive and
fraught with risk with regard to ultimate market acceptance.  This
may hold true for the higher-volume commodity resins, but it is
clearly not true of the specialty, higher-performance types of
thermoplastics and thermosets.  Nowhere is the search for new
materials more intense nor the possible rewards for such efforts
greater than in the field of high-temperature polymers.<P>

By 1980 the plastics design engineer had only a narrow palette of
plastics to choose from in order to produce a part that could
withstand long-term heat resistance of 300oF and short-term heat
excursions up to 500(F and above, as well as deliver equally
critical mechanical/electrical/processing features.  Among the
thermoplastics there were the fluoropolymers that were ideal for
extrusion applications such as wire and cable insulation, but these
resins were not easily adapted to injection molded parts with
complex geometries.  There were the sulfone-based resins such as
polysulfone and polyphenylsulfone, and polyamideimide which had
proven itself in small parts that had to operate in hostile
environments.  Among the thermosets, there were only a few
commercial grades of bismaleimide on the market requiring heavy
glass or carbon fiber reinforcement to overcome this resin's
inherent brittleness, and silicone offered excellent thermal
properties, but it could not be processed with conventional
processing equipment.  Meanwhile there were many condensation- and
addition-type polyimides being actively pursued under Government
contracts, but up to that time they remained largely laboratory
curiosums rather than commercial realities.<P>

Over the past decade, from 1980 right up to 1991, the pace of
research and commercialization of high-temperature plastics - in
this country and abroad - has accelerated dramatically.  These
global research programs among the thermoplastic resin
manufacturers have yielded a vast - in fact, perhaps, excessive -
menu of imide-, sulfone- and ketone-based polymers, along with the
startling new performance features of liquid crystal polymers.  The
thermoset manufacturers have brought out a whole range of
polyimides with excellent mechanical performance at elevated (500-
700oF) temperature for consideration by the military and commercial
aircraft engine builders today and other (e.g., automotive)
manufacturers for the future.  They have also upgraded the thermal
and mechanical performance of all the major thermosets - the epoxies,
phenolics, vinyl ester cyanate esters, bismaleimides,
etc. - through compounding with high-temperature thermoplastics and
modifying the basic thermoset formulations.<P>

In effect, the search for higher-temperature performance extends
right through the whole contemporary resin classification system,
and this is leading to increased competition among the suppliers
and increased options among the end-users.  Manufacturers of
commodity resins such as polystyrene, nylon and PVC have recently
introduced "high-temperature" grades of their resins.  Formerly
intractable resins such as polyphenylene oxide and maleic anhydride
have been harnessed to high-temperature applications through the
medium of alloying and blending with more processable resins.
Alloying and blending has also been a route to synergistic
combinations of thermal and mechanical performance in the field of
polyimides and liquid crystal polymers.  Moreover, there are whole
new resins such as polyetherimide (1982) and polyphthalamide (1991)
available to the high-temperature plastics decision-makers.<P>

<B>SCOPE OF THE REPORT</B><P>

In this report we cover the full range of "old" and "new" high-
temperature plastics competing against alternative materials such
as metals, ceramics, glass, etc. and against each other in the
major end-use markets where thermal performance is critical -
namely,<P>

<MENU>          - aerospace<BR>
          - aircraft interiors and exteriors<BR>
          - automotive under-the-hood and underbody parts<BR>
          - electrical/electronic assemblies and parts<BR>
          - medical devices and ware<BR>
          - missiles<BR>
          - others</MENU><P>

The resins that we have isolated for consideration are those that
can meet specific thermal performance criteria in the virgin resin
state - principally a continuous use temperature of 300oF and
above.  This recognizes the fact that numerous fillers such as
glass fibers can enhance the thermal properties of plastics, but a
penalty in either processability or mechanical performance or both
is normally incurred.<P>

Moreover, high-temperature plastics are now supplied in various
forms such as<P>

<MENU>          - molding compounds (liquid, powder and pellets)<BR>
          - film<BR>
          - foam<BR>
          - sheet<BR>
          - prepregs<BR>
          - fibers<BR>
          - stock shapes for subsequent machining</MENU><P>

In this report we cover all these forms with the exception of
fibers which will be treated in a separate, forthcoming report from
BCC.<P>

From a geographical standpoint, this report provides a
comprehensive update on developments on the supply side among
foreign (e.g., European and Japanese), as well as domestic, high-
temperature resin manufacturers.  However, we draw most of our
examples of high-temperature plastic applications from the U.S.
marketplace, and our consumption totals relate primarily to current
and likely future U.S. demand for these materials.<P>



<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE REPORT</B><P>

BCC has covered the field of high-temperature plastics in multi-
client and custom reports on several occasions over the past decade
when the list of these resins and grades grew so markedly.  It has
also conducted other studies that touched in part on key markets
for high-temperature plastics (e.g., aircraft, advanced composites,
electronics).  Thus we bring years of research expertise and a
wealth of industry contacts out in the field to this present
research program.  The result, we feel, is an accurate,
comprehensive and in-depth analysis of the driving forces at play
(e.g., changing part design requirements, regulations, economics of
high-temperature plastics processing), the key players in this
business, the evolving industry structure, and the quantitative
short-term and long-term prospects for these high-value-added,
high-temperature resins in the decade ahead.<P>

The insights and the data that we have put together here come from
an extensive review of the domestic and foreign plastics literature
and from a broad-based survey of key market participants.  We are
thus able to quantify the amount of resin that is not only capable
of high-temperature performance, but actually used in that
connection - now and through the coming decade.  This information
should be a valuable input to existing companies supplying or specifying high-temperature resins, as
well as to other companies
contemplating entering or expanding their presence in this
specialty niche of the plastics industry.<P>



<B>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>

BCC has published and will soon be publishing other reports that
touch upon key materials and markets of interest from a high-
temperature resin perspective.  We cite several of these reports
below and their actual/target dates of publication.</B><P>

<MENU> P-023N    Advanced Polymer Matrix Composites (1988)<BR>
     P-113     Plastic Industrial Parts:  Bearings, Gears,
               Fasteners, Seals (1988)<BR>
     P-117     Plastics in Aircraft Interiors (1990)<BR>
     P-121     Plastics in Non-Packaging Medical Applications
                (1990)<BR>
     P-053R    Transparent Plastics (1991)<BR>
     P-123     Plastics/Elastomers Under-The-Hood Applications
                (1991)</MENU><P>


