<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-053N: RIGID NON-PACKAGING    
TRANSPARENT PLASTICS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-053N: RIGID NON-PACKAGING    
TRANSPARENT PLASTICS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Melvin Schlechter
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The objective of this study is to provide an analysis of transparent plastics 
in terms of current and forecasted markets. New developments in clear plastics 
expanded usage in existing and new applications and competition between 
polymers exhibiting optical clarity will be covered.  The competitive scenario 
between glass and clear plastics will also be described.  The competition 
between transparent plastics will be discussed in detail.<P> 

Important suppliers of clear plastics, their product lines, and other 
important factors that impact the market will be discussed.<P> 


<b>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

The 1990s has spawned the search for niche markets by most plastics suppliers, 
somewhat irrespective of potential volume.  Selection criteria focus on 
growing specialty markets with opportunities for respectable profits even 
though sales volumes may be less than desired.<P> 

Transparent plastics could be a possibility for a niche market since the 
category encompasses many types of polymers.  In addition to acrylics and 
polycarbonates, many styrene-based materials, along with commodity and 
specialty polymers, qualify as having clear grades.  Opportunities in several 
application areas are in need of reappraisal in regard to transparent or clear 
plastics.<P> 


<b>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The term "transparent" or "clear" is obviously a subjective one.  Most relate 
clarity of plastics to percent of light transmission as defined by ASTM test 
D-1003.  Light transmission percentages above 85% usually are accepted as 
transparent.  Other related ASTM tests are D-523 and D-542.<P> 

Clear plastics are commercially available in many forms, e.g., injection 
molded, extruded, blow molded, thermoformed, etc.  Many extruded products are 
converted to films.  The many uses of these films (commodity, specialty, 
coextruded, plastic food, medical packaging, etc.) could be the subject of a 
separate report.<P> 

Blow-molded plastics are hollow and most are converted to bottles or 
containers, while thermoformed plastics are similar to injection molded except 
that they are usually thinner and require less expensive equipment and capital 
expense. <P>

This report will cover rigid, clear, non-packaging plastic parts which include 
injection molded, non-film extrusion, and thermoforming (including cast 
sheet).  The major plastic products excluded from this report will be flexible 
and hollow materials (including films).<P> 


<b>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

A comprehensive review was undertaken of literature relating to clear 
polymers, their applications and technology, and significant new developments.  
Included in the review were supplier trade literature, texts, and monographs.<P> 

Following the collection and analysis of this information, extensive 
interviews were conducted with many producers, suppliers, and fabricators of 
transparent plastics.<P> 

All dollar values are in 1994 dollars, "millions" are often abbreviated as 
"MM", growth rates are annually compounded, and tradenamed products appear in 
upper-case letters.<P> 

The terms "transparent" and "clear" are used interchangeably.  The acronyms 
PS, PP, and PC are often used to denote polystyrene, polypropylene, and 
polycarbonate, respectively.<P> 

Methylmethacrylate and MMA are also used interchangeably, as are polymethylmethacrylate and PMMA.  Methylmethacrylate polymers are synonymous with
PMMA.<P>

<CENTER><HR WIDTH=50% SIZE=4>
