<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-075U  OPTIMIZATION OF MECHANICAL PROPERTIES OF
THERMOPLASTICS THROUGH ALLOYING
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-075U  OPTIMIZATION OF MECHANICAL PROPERTIES OF
THERMOPLASTICS THROUGH ALLOYING</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>LARRY WANG</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>Goals and Format</B><P>

Recent developments in blending and alloying technologies have led to
the proliferation of new products, methods of blending and many new
applications for thermoplastic blends. This detailed report addresses
these recent changes and developments in the field of polymeric
blends, including new compatibilizers and new applications in
automotive and non-automotive products.<P>

One of the principal reasons why alloys and blends are so popular is
the achievement of superior properties at often reduced cost. Also,
the less stringent requirements for the development of alloys than for
the development of entirely new polymers, which usually take several
years from research to full commercialization.<P>

<B>Scope and Format</B><P>

This study is an in-depth qualitative and quantitative description of
properties, applications, markets and suppliers of thermoplastic
alloys and blends. It also deals with consumption figures for
different types of alloys and different applications and forecasts
this data through 1996. The report also deals with the
compatibilization of the otherwise immiscible blends and with impact
modification of hard and sometimes brittle thermoplastic materials.
Other aspects of blending-alloying technology including the types and
preparation of interpenetrating polymer networks (IPNs) are also
described in detail.<P>

<B>Contribution and Target Audience</B><P>

This study is designed for manufacturers of thermoplastic alloys and
blends as well as suppliers of additives for such blends as
compatibilizers, impact modifiers, reinforcing fillers and fibers and
coupling agents. It will assist them in making decisions relative to
markets, property requirements for specific uses, production levels
and potential sales of their products. It will also provide them with
information relative to competitive products.<P>

The information included in this report will be also useful to
processors and distributors active in the field of thermoplastic
alloys and blends as well as additives. It will also be of value to
investment firms and market analysts advising potential investors.<P>

<B>Methodology</B><P>

This study consists of five major sections:<P>

<MENU>1. Overview<BR>
2. Technological Aspects of Alloying and Blending<BR>
3. Alloys and Blends by Type<BR>
4. Markets and Applications<BR>
5. Suppliers of Alloys and Blends</MENU><P>

In the Overview, the scope of alloying and blending as well as the
historical perspective are delineated. The terms related to alloys and
blends are defined and there is a brief discussion of miscibility and
compatibilization of blends. A description of competitive polymeric
products such as reinforced thermoplastics, RIM, SMC and thermosets
is followed by a brief description of major markets. Types of alloys
are listed together with their present and projected consumption
figures. International dimension and the listing of major alloy and
blend manufacturers conclude this section of the study.<P>

The chapter on Technological Aspects of Alloying and Blending deals
with the problems in alloying and blending as related to miscibility,
compatibility, thermodynamic considerations as well as the phenomenon
of synergy. It deals with the modification of major properties and
their mechanisms, process control, reactive blending and polymer
tacticity. The types of compatibilizers available are discussed in
some detail. The types and characteristics of IPNs are also discussed.
Impact modifiers and their effect on blend properties of different
types of alloys are elaborated.<P>

The section of this report dealing with the types of alloys and blends
describes in-depth the properties, applications, consumption figures
and manufacturers of individual types of alloys and blends. The types
of alloys are classified according to their major thermoplastic
component. The following types of thermoplastic alloys are described:
polyphenylene oxide or ether (PPO and PPE), ABS, nylons,
polycarbonate, polyesters and PBT and miscellaneous blends which
include those based on acetals, polysulfone, SMA, polyarylate,
polyurethane and ASA. Minor engineering alloys and blends are also
briefly described. The chapter concludes with the discussion of
commodity-based alloys, mostly those based on PVC, polypropylene,
other polyolefins and polystyrene and IPNs.<P>

The chapter dealing with Markets and Applications describes and
analyzes two major markets for thermoplastic alloys and blends:
automotive and non-automotive. Automotive applications which consume
a large volume of thermoplastic alloys are stressed. In this context,
thermoplastic alloys are compared to major competitive materials such
as steel, RIM and SMC. The partnership between car and thermoplastic
alloy manufacturers is described and analyzed. Major suppliers of
thermoplastic alloy parts for the automotive industry are listed. The
automotive market is divided into three sections: exterior, interior
and under-the-hood applications. Special consideration is given to
exterior automotive panels and bumpers.<P>

Non-automotive applications such as business machines, appliances,
tools, consumer products, electrical and electronic parts, and
building and industrial products are also elaborated.<P>

The final section of this report deals with the suppliers of alloys
and blends. They and their products are detailed starting with the
most important suppliers (General Electric) and ending with those
suppliers who contribute less than one per cent of the market. The
information on sales of alloys by major manufacturers in volume and
percentage of the market controlled is also provided in this section
of the report.<P>

<B>Information Sources</B><P>

Information sources for this study include technical and commercial
magazines, government statistical reports, interviews with numerous
representatives of manufacturers and users of thermoplastic alloys and
blends, private publications, patents, papers presented at various
conferences and informal discussions with their authors. Selected BCC
Opportunity Reports have also been used as a source of information.
These include:<P>
<MENU>     P-015N- Engineering Resins<BR>
     P-026 - Thermoplastic Elastomers<BR>
     P-075R - Alloys, IPNs, Liquid Crystals<BR>
     P-085N - What is New in Barrier Packaging of Food and Non-Food
         Products?<BR>
     P-107 - Medical Packaging.</MENU><P>


