<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-081A  PLASTICS IN TOYS & OUTDOOR PLAYGROUND EQUIPMENT
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-081A  PLASTICS IN TOYS & OUTDOOR PLAYGROUND EQUIPMENT
</H2>

<HR><P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>OBJECTIVES OF THE REPORT</B><P>

     "We don't sell toys, nobody in the toy industry sells toys.  We sell
     plastics; that's what we sell.  We sell it in different forms from our resin
     suppliers.  They sell it as a pellet, we sell it in the form of a toy.  The
     safest type of toy you can make today is a plastic toy, and as we continue
     to design toys we only think of one thing - plastic.  We don't develop toys
     in wood or metal or anything ----.  So, plastic is here to stay, we'll always
     be a plastic industry, and as the industry grows - which it will - the
     industry will continue to go after different markets (new toy concepts).
     Consequently, there will be growth in plastics - I would say 5 percent
     minimum per year."<P>

<B>Hasbro Official</B><P>

The above panegyric on the role of plastics in the design, manufacturing and
marketing of toys captures the enthusiasm that U.S. and global toy and recreational
equipment vendors have for these materials in their current decision-making.  The toy
and recreational equipment business is relatively recession-proof, so the consumption
of all materials has steadily increased over the recent past and will continue to do so
over the coming years.  And the economic, environmental and design advantages of
plastics as a group over traditional toy and recreational equipment materials (wood,
metals, rubber, textiles, etc.) have led to the gradual replacement of these materials
and a more prominent role for both the commodity resins and selected engineering
resins that can offer cost-effective mechanical strength, clarity, impact resistance, and
other critical qualities required in toys.<P>

Yet, despite the size and scope of the opportunities for plastics - over 800 million
pounds of resins consumed as of 1991 and probably over 1 billion pounds by 1996 -
the toy industry has seldom been studied from the standpoint of the evolving inter-
materials competition, as well as the evolving preferences for specific plastic materials
and plastics processing methods, for low- to high-volume toy part programs.  In this
research program, BCC has set out to determine and quantify wherever possible the
opportunities that the toy business offers to resin manufacturers, plastics
compounders, plastics processors, additive manufacturers, and all the other players
on the plastics supply chain.<P>

One basic objective in this report, therefore, is to illuminate for all the companies in
the toy and plastics industries the current and likely future role of plastics based on
evolving economic, demographic, environmental and industry-specific considerations.
Toy companies will benefit from the data and insights offered on trends in plastic
material decision-making among their domestic and, in some cases, foreign
competitors.  Plastics companies will benefit from the details offered on the evolving
pricing, processing and performance requirements for plastics in both colored and
clear toy part programs, large and small parts, and from the candid assessments
offered on the current pallette of plastic material grades promoted for use in toys of
all types.  They will also learn the performance enhancements that the domestic toy
manufacturers are seeking from plastics for their next generation of products.<P>



<B>SCOPE OF THE REPORT</B><P>

The toy industry embraces a vast number of products designed to both entertain and educate children.  In this report we focus on three basic categories of toys:<P>

<UL>dolls<BR>
traditional toys (including novelties)<BR>
outdoor playground equipment<P></UL>

Dolls are a well-defined segment of the toy industry.  Outdoor playground equipment
is brought into scope, not only because this is a large and fast-growing medium for
entertaining children outside the home (in the backyard of residences, in schoolyards
and preschool playgrounds, at institutions, restaurants, etc.), but it is also
characterized by lively competition among materials - mainly wood, metals and
plastics - for structural and non-structural parts (e.g., slides, crawl tubes, rails, roofs,
etc.).  Traditional toys are the residual or "all other" toy category, including pre-school
toys, play figures, games and puzzles, cycles and ride-on vehicles, activity toys, video
games, simulated sports gears, novelties, etc.<P>

The interviews we conducted were with U.S. toy manufacturers, and we tended to
concentrate on those companies with at least some domestic manufacturing
capabilities because these are the primary toy industry customers for the U.S. plastics
industry participants.  However, in those cases where leading U.S. companies
consulted have little or no domestic manufacturing capabilities, we still attempted to
determine their plastic material preferences and the internal and external influences
on that decision-making in offshore production facilities.<P>

As for the data presented in this report, we were able to draw from statistics
generated by both the toy industry and the plastics industry covering the period 1980-
1991 for several key series.  In our interviews with officials at toy and plastics
industry associations and at leading companies in both fields, we concentrated on
verifying the published 1991 data, determining the trends already evident in the
current year (1992), and then forecasting out to the year 1996, based on their
assessments.  The resulting estimates from all these sources should be accurate within
very small tolerance margins.<P>



<B>RESEARCH METHODOLOGY</B><P>

Our sources for the qualitative and quantitative assessments offered here were as follows:<P>

<UL><LI> toy industry associations such as the Toy Manufacturers
        Association (TMA),<P>
    <LI> plastics industry associations such as the Society of the Plastics Industry (SPI),<P>
    <LI> government publications on trends in the U.S. toy industry such
        as those from the U.S. Department of Commerce,<P>
     <LI> plastics and toy industry trade and company literature,<P>
     <LI> telephone interviews with leading U.S. toy companies,<P>
     <LI> telephone interviews with leading custom plastics processors
        serving the U.S. toy industry, and<P>
     <LI> telephone interviews with leading resin manufacturers and other
        plastic material suppliers.<P></UL>

We received tremendous cooperation from all these sources, particularly the leading
U.S. toy companies where officials with either product design or materials R&D or
plastics purchasing responsibilities generally provided us with a wealth of data and
insights with respect to their current and future approach to specific grades of resins
and plastics processing methods.  Thus, the forecasts we present here for the U.S. toy
industry in general and for specific sub-markets can genuinely be regarded as industry
consensus figures.<P>



<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE REPORT</B><P>

For those companies either already in or contemplating entering the materials supply
line to the toy industry, this report represents a valuable set of independent insights
into one key set of materials in common usage in a vast number of part programs -
namely, plastics.  For the main companies along the plastics supply chain - some of
them already servicing toy industry accounts and others for whom the toy industry
is still an untapped source of sales - this report represents both a comprehensive guide
to this industry and a cost-effective sales/marketing tool to respond to evolving
material requirements among the industry leaders.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>

BCC has already published several multiclient technical/economic reports that touch
upon plastic materials and processing methods that are key constituents of the plastic
toy part manufacturing business.  Some of these reports are the following:<P>

<UL>P-015N    "Engineering Thermoplastics"<BR>
          P-053R    "Transparent Plastics"<BR>
          P-076     "Styrenics and Their Markets"<BR>
          P-078     "Large Molded Parts" (including
                    rotational molded parts)<BR>
          P-080     "Plastics UV Stability<BR>
          P-124     "New Olefin Resins"<BR>
          P-133     "PVC and The Environment"<P>

