<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-081B OPPORTUNITIES IN PLASTICS IN HOUSEHOLD APPLICATIONS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-081B OPPORTUNITIES IN PLASTICS IN HOUSEHOLD APPLICATIONS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>SCOPE OF THE REPORT</B><P>

The appliance industry has grown to become a major set of
opportunities for plastics, both in this country and around the
world. BCC last looked at this marketplace back in the late
1970s. Since then plastics technologies have developed to the
point where these materials can cost-effectively replace non-
plastic materials (metals, wood, glass, et al.), and they can
also facilitate the creation of whole new appliance types made
possible by the light weight, functionality and design freedom of
plastics.<P>

The term "appliance" can be defined in a variety of ways because
appliances come in various shapes and forms, and they are used in
both residential and non-residential environments. Our focus in
this report is first and foremost on electricity-powered
appliances designed for use in the home.<P> 

Secondly, we concentrate
on functional appliances designed for use throughout the
household, and these include large and small kitchen appliances,
personal care products normally used in bathrooms and bedrooms,
portable or installed air conditioners and humidifiers that can
be used in any room, and the relatively new kitchen waste
compactors and disposers. The household units that we exclude
from our analysis here are what one might categorize as
"entertainment" appliances, that is, radios, televisions, VCRs,
electronic videos games, and so on. We also exclude lighting
fixtures (portable and installed) insofar as these units are
probably best addressed in the context of plastics in building
and construction.<P>

We also deal exclusively in this report with those appliances
manufactured in the U.S. for either domestic sale or export. Our
logic here is related to the methodology we selected to conduct
this report, and that is to consult directly with all the leading
U.S. manufacturers of large and small household appliances. It is
impossible, without research facilities in the Far East and
Europe, to cover the markets for plastics in those regions with
the same detail and accuracy as one can cover the U.S.
marketplace. Thus, even though we collected in the course of our
research program a sense of the evolving plastics preferences for
appliance parts produced outside of the U.S. and we pass along
such information in this report, our clientele are primarily U.S.
resin manufacturers, plastics processors and compounders, and
appliance OEMs. And data and insights into the U.S. market for
plastics in appliances are of the greatest relevance to these
companies.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY OF THE REPORT</B><P>

Our approach to the objectives of identifying and quantifying the
types and amounts of plastics consumed in household appliances
(in the past, currently, and for the foreseeable future)
proceeded through the following four research stages:<P>

<UL>   I   -a thorough review of the plastics and appliance industry
        trade literature over the past few years (1987-1992)<P>
   II  -a series of consultations with officials at plastics and
        appliance industry associations<P>
   III  -a survey of over 50 U.S.-based manufacturers of large
        and small appliances<P>
   IV  -a survey of roughly 30 resin manufacturers and plastics
        processors with significant positions in the current
        plastic appliance material and part supply chain</UL><P>

Stage I provided us with a good sense of the applications within
the broadly defined appliance industry where plastics actually do
or potentially could play a role.<P> 

Stage II provided us with data
relating to the past trends in U.S. appliance production and in
plastics consumed within the appliance industry. Officials at the
Association of Home Appliance Manufacturers (AHAM) and the
Society of the Plastics Industry (SPI) were particularly helpful
in this respect. Stage III was absolutely critical in developing
accurate assessments of the evolving plastic material preferences
among the major U.S. manufacturers of large and small appliances
and the volume of plastics consumption, often on an application-
by-application basis. And then Stage IV served to confirm and
refine the quantitative and qualitative assessments drawn from
Stage III with respect to the future plastics preferences and the
future pace of growth of plastics in the household appliance
business.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE REPORT</B><P>

This report is actually the second part of a trilogy of reports
covering:<P>

<UL><LI> plastics in toys and outdoor playground equipment,<BR>
<LI> plastics in household appliances, and<BR>
<LI> plastics in housewares.</UL><P>

These reports (individually and collectively) offer a unique, in-depth perspective on the role of plastics in items commonly found
in the home. The report on toys and outdoor playground equipment,
published in May 1992, provided data and insights into plastics
drawn from all the leading manufacturers of these articles, and
it pointed to the opportunities ahead for plastic material
manufacturers, compounders and processors if they could meet
evolving  cost/performance parameters. Now this report offers a
detailed probing of the current plastics mind-sets among the
design engineers who are developing the household appliances of
the future. It illuminates their cost sensitivities and their
shifting performance objectives that together will determine
their eventual selections of plastics to serve as parts of their
assemblies. It also points to the actual/perceived advantages and
disadvantages of the various thermoset and thermoplastic resins
and resin blends in terms of the new economics and emerging
environmental implications of plastics utilized in all these
large and small appliances.<P>
 

<CENTER><HR WIDTH=50% SIZE=4>
