<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-086R  GEOSYNTHETICS:
New Markets and opportunities for Geotextiles, Geomembranes,
Geosynthetic Clay Liners and Geomatrices
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-086R  GEOSYNTHETICS: New Markets and opportunities for Geotextiles, Geomembranes, Geosynthetic Clay Liners and Geomatrices </H2>

<HR><P>

<I>MARK M. MORRISON</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST<P>
<I>ANNA CRULL</I><BR>
PROJECT DIRECTOR<P>


<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

Geosynthetics continue to be a growing technology and market, with expanding applications in land reclamation, waste and hazardous waste site construction, and a variety of construction problems.  Although some of the materials have been on the market for as much as 45 years, the markets are not mature in many
ways.  There are areas for significant growth over the next 10 years, with
room for new products and competitors.  However, there are some definite
uncertainties about market penetration, profitability, particularly in
geomembranes, and some technical issues regarding materials acceptability for
some applications.  Nevertheless, many segments of the markets addressed are
less adrift in uncertainty now than 5 years ago because of new regulatory
requirements which have been put in place.<P>

For much of the diverse industry
the growth that is expected will be accelerated during the next 5 years
because of expected investment in the U.S. infrastructure.  For some of the
competitors involved in these markets, there is significant upside growth
potential through arrangements with non-U.S. competitors to distribute,
engineer, and sell materials in Europe, and throughout much of the world.  Some firms expect profitability over the next 5 years to depend on growth in
international sales due to government regulations based in part on present
U.S. environmental regulation.<P>

The present push of the new U.S. President is
to institute spending plans to accelerate roadway and public works repair.
These factors would make for faster growth than is predicted in this report,
in which rather moderate growth is forecast based on a maturing of the market.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

The present state of the industry is changing fairly rapidly.  There is an
active industry organization with good access to technical advancement.
Within the U.S., reports are generally that engineering firms often do not
have adequate engineers trained in using these materials.  With these changes
and difficulties, a technology/marketing report update is needed.<P>

This technology/marketing report, covering geotextiles, geomembranes and
geomatrices, describes the market growth, the developing technology trends,
industry leaders, and industry needs.  This study is directed toward
understanding the present and potential markets for the materials involved.
Key patents are abstracted and characteristic applications for the materials
are given.<P>

This technical marketing report on geotextiles, geomembranes, geosynthetic
clay liners, and geomatrices details several very distinct and different types
of materials, all generally referred to as geosynthetics.  The emphasis is on
the material base, structure of the industry and company involvement.
Essentially it is a market that has evolved from commodity resins and has become a specialty of its own.  Such a report, covering the three
classifications of materials, fits together quite nicely in that the
applications for the materials have a lot of overlap.  In many applications, geomembranes are used in combination with various geotextiles to stabilize the subsoil.  In certain applications geomatrices may compete where some geotextiles are used.  This BCC Business Opportunity Report addresses these problems.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This report will be valuable to those involved in the material supplying
business to evaluate business opportunities and technology trends, as well as those firms in the engineering end of the business, in evaluating further integration possibilities.  The report should prove useful to engineering firms to understand the state and growth of the market and to understand and react to market challenges.  BCC and the analysts involved wish to thank those companies, agencies, and university researchers who have made information available and provided other verbal information for this report.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This report divides the diverse geosynthetic industry into three parts:
geotextiles, geomembranes, and geomatrices.  The words geotextile,
geomembrane, and geomatrix are not new to most users.  The word geomembrane
should not be confused with the word membrane as commonly used with the
permeable thin film membranes of separation science.  These membranes are
distinct and are the subject of other technical/marketing reports and
newsletters.  Many of the spun-bonded or other nonwovens may appear to have
common characteristics with the materials of the same name in separation
science.  The materials for geotextiles are generally stronger, sturdier, and
applicable for much larger-scale operations than those of the filtration
industry.  The word geotextile is reserved for those materials used in
connection with "earth" and "engineering" activities.<P>

For geotextiles, also known as industrial or construction fabrics, there are
two main subsectors, the woven and the nonwoven textiles.  Geotextiles as
woven or nonwoven fabrics have applications in civil engineering such as
interfacing with soils to create reinforced structures for roads and
underlayment, or applications to enhance the hydraulic properties of soils.<P>

The major functions of geotextiles used with a soil are filtration and/or
separation.  The structure of the fabric becomes especially important in such applications as liquid filters or solid-liquid separators, including controlling the water table, as well as drainage, irrigation, and erosion control.   Vastly different applications and performance characteristics and testing procedures are related to each of the primary subsectors.  The most important uses for geotextiles are related to construction, such as roadbeds or airstrips, or in reinforcements such as soil stabilization, drainage, and erosion control.  The nonwoven geotextile market accounts for about 65% of the sales volume, estimated at $315 million in 1993.<P>

The major uses for the geomembranes or performance elastomers are in large-
volume linings, such as waste water ponds, landfills, and hazardous waste
storage pits.  What each type of material has in common is that it is used on
the ground, and it either replaces, supplements or creates a civil engineering
application.  It is usually based on synthetic organic polymers.<P>

Geosynthetic clay liners have developed as a distinct composite material
category largely over the last 5 years.  They encompass several versions of products which deliver high quality, low permeability clay (bentonite) in a user-friendly form for construction.  These materials offer technical advantages in terms of reliability in a landfill or hazardous waste impoundment, and potential savings in construction costs and in the efficiency of siting materials storage.  The materials are often specified in addition to geomembranes in construction projects.  Market demand has not yet fully developed.  Market concerns for the profitability of geomembranes could cloud the short-term profitability for geosynthetic clay liners; however, geosynthetic clay liners should experience significant long term growth.<P>

An additional part of the market is geomatrices.  These are generally 3-D materials that are used alone or with geotextiles to augment the confinements and add stability or drainage.  This is probably the most rapidly
evolving market of the three, and is the hardest to define.  For the purposes
of this report, geonets and geogrids are included in the section on
geomatrices, but that division is admittedly arbitrary.<P>

The geosynthetic industry structure is a diverse one and includes the primary
polymer manufacturers, textile companies, and rubber compounders.  In general
geosynthetics can be considered as a group to have matured to the same extent
as other specialty polymers and elastomers.  Each section includes lists of
market leaders and comments about products available, along with typical
applications.<P>

This study is directed toward accessing as completely and as fairly as
possible the present and potential markets for the materials involved.
Information for this report was collected by extensive industry contact with
people active in the use and production of polymer materials and the finished
materials, by review of technical literature, patents, computer-retrieved
information, and the author's experience with geomatric materials, especially
in the underdeveloped parts of the world.  Key portions of patents are
information can be found in greater depth, especially as related to
geomembranes in included in this report and cited where appropriate.  Other
patents and the BCC Inc. monthly newsletter, "Waste Treatment Technology
News."<P>

This comprehensive technical/marketing report provides forecasts for
geomaaterials for the near- to mid-term (2003), and defines the technical and industrial developments and key changes in market activity and attitudes.  This document is intended to be as accurate in technical, economic, and business areas as possible.  The quoted technical data are dependent on the accuracy of the manufacturers.  This report is not intended to constitute a legal or accounting document, a specific business plan for any product or an endorsement of any given product.  Neither the author, nor BCC Inc., as the publisher, assumes any liability for loss or damage as a result of reliance on this material.  The author and analysts wish to thank all of the manufacturers, engineering companies, and end-users who have demonstrated such a high degree of cooperation.<P>

