<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-099R  PLASTICS IN ESD APPLICATIONS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-099R  PLASTICS IN ESD APPLICATIONS</H2>

<HR><P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>OBJECTIVES OF THE STUDY</B><P>

Static electricity is a natural phenomenon that affects every modern production
facility in some way or other, and in several contexts it constitutes a serious hazard
to people and products.  Insofar as it can be generated by continuous processing
equipment where speed of material throughput is essential, it must be drained off so
as not to create a shock to workers and sensitive electronic monitoring and production
equipment.  Insofar as it can affect the film used in food packaging, it can attract dust
that can contaminate the package contents.  It can also be generated in a healthcare
service context (e.g., a hospital room) where sensitive life-support monitoring
equipment is vulnerable to an electrostatic discharge (ESD) event.  And it is obviously
a critical concern in the production, storage and transportation of ammunition where
a simple static charge (spark) can prove to be catastrophic in its effects.<P>

Although static has been recognized from the very dawn of the industrial age as a
potential hazard, its most prevalent and widespread effects on productivity and
quality control have been felt in the modern microelectronics industry.  Here the
effects of unwanted static can disrupt any part of the product supply chain - from the
microelectronics component stages to the assembly stages to the use of the equipment
out in the field.  Many of today's microelectronics components can be damaged or
destroyed if exposed to charges of less than 100 volts and, for some, sensitivity to ESD
extends down to 10 volts.  And this potentially destructive effect is totally invisible;
it has to be caught by electronic monitoring equipment before it goes further down
the supply chain.  Thus, computer systems, medical diagnostic equipment, telephone
exchanges, etc. are all vulnerable to ESD.  The annual loss of output attributable to
ESD is conventionally estimated at $10 billion, and it could be even higher than this.<P>

Part of the solution to this problem of static electricity is to eliminate or limit insofar
as possible those factors in the work environment that can generate, store and
transfer static charges to ESD-sensitive equipment.  Every aspect of the workplace
must be assessed from this perspective.  The classic ESD event is a triboelectric
charge that an office worker brings into the work environment or generates on the
flooring.  If this worker subsequently comes into contact with an ESD-sensitive device
before that charge can be drained off safely to ground, there can be ESD-induced
damage.  Thus, for many years now and over the past decade in particular, the
workplace environment has been modified to reduce or eliminate this risk.<P>


Static control programs have very significant implications for plastics.  Many of the
items in the workplace are made of materials that are non-conductive in nature - that
is, unable to dissipate or transfer a static charge to ground in a controlled, predictable
manner.  Plastics (e.g., in film, foam, and rigid part configurations) and paper fall into
the category of insulative materials whereas the metals are, to varying degrees,
conductive.  In order to continue to capture the design freedom, processability and
other economic advantages of plastics, they must be modified and made neutral to
static charges.<P>

In this report we offer comprehensive coverage of the current routes to rendering
plastics antistatic, static dissipative and conductive.  We then examine the specific
applications where ESD is a primary design parameter and where plastics play a vital
role - items such as film bags to package microelectronic components, floor mats to
provide worker comfort, molded and formed materials handling containers and
accessories, wrist straps and ground cords, etc.  For each of the plastic films, sheet
and compounds utilized, we identify the leading manufacturers and discuss their
current position and likely future strategy in this market, based on our consultations.
In the same way, for each application utilizing plastics either in whole or in part, we
identify the leading manufacturers of these items and discuss their current and likely
future materials preferences (plastics and non-plastics).<P>



<B>SCOPE OF THE STUDY</B><P>

Static electricity represents a hazard in five primary markets - namely:<P>

<MENU>   - continuous processing plants<BR>
       - electronic/electrical equipment manufacturing<BR>
       - food packaging<BR>
       - healthcare services<BR>
       - military hardware and electronics.</MENU><P>

Another that is just emerging as an opportunity for antistatic plastics is automotive
fuel delivery systems where flexible fuels have to be accommodated in the future.
Whereas our analysis and summary data relate to all these fields, the majority (70
percent) of the consumption of antistatic plastic items is in the production of
commercial electronic/electrical equipment.  Therefore, we focus most of our efforts
on this segment of the business.<P>

Moreover, there are myriad actual and potential applications for static-free plastic
compounds and products.  Our analysis and data relate to all actual applications, and
we have concentrated primarily on the following:<P>

<MENU>  - film and film bags<BR>
       - flooring (tiles, mats and other flooring systems)<BR>
       - foam<BR>
       - footwear<BR>
       - gloves<BR>
       - materials handling equipment (extruded, formed and molded)<BR>
       - work surfaces<BR>
       - wrist straps</MENU><P>

In addition to exploring in detail all these applications, we have covered in detail all
the materials and methods used to render plastics antistatic or conductive, and these
include<P>

    <MENU>   - chemical antistat agents<BR>
       - conductive coatings<BR>
       - conductive fillers (carbon blacks, metallic
         particles and fibers, etc.)<BR>
       - metal coating of plastics and plastics fillers<BR>
       - radiation curing<BR>
       - topical sprays<BR>
       - others at the R&D stage.</MENU><P>

And, finally, whereas we alert our readers to data, developments and practices in this
field outside the U.S. wherever possible, the data presented here relate primarily to
U.S. markets and future trends in U.S. materials usage and product sales in volume
and value terms.<P>



<B>RESEARCH METHODOLOGY AND SOURCES</B><P>

In putting together this report we relied on four primary research sources - namely,<P>

<MENU>    - telephone interviews with industry participants<BR>
       - analysis of product literature and pricing information
 from these companies<BR>
       - a thorough review of the trade literature<BR>
       - attendance at ESD-related conferences and a review<BR>
         of proceedings from these conferences.</MENU><P>


The telephone interviews were overall the most valuable source of data and insights
into current trends in ESD theory and practice generally and into the plastics used
in static control products in particular.  We interviewed between 150-200 industry
participants in the following market segments:<P>
<DD>(a) the regulatory agencies,
<DD>(b) the associations dealing with ESD standards,<BR>
<DD>(c) the resin manufacturers and compounders producing antistatic grades of
   plastics,<BR>
<DD>(d) the antistatic/conductive additive manufacturers,<BR>
<DD>(e) the manufacturers of antistatic/conductive materials other
   than plastics,<BR>
<DD>(f) the static control product manufacturers, and<BR>
<DD>(g) a sample of static control product end-users.<P>

From all these consultations, we were able to calculate realistic quantitative estimates
by material and by product and to refine our understanding of the evolving
dynamics/terminology of this business, in terms of standards and testing, materials
and product design.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY</B><P>

This study is designed to assist companies already in or contemplating entering the
static control product business, either from a material or product standpoint.
Although the emphasis is on plastics, the analysis at all points considers the
competition to plastics - from paper, metals, rubber, etc.  The estimates that we put
forward are distillations of data generated and/or views held by key industry
participants.<P>

There has been a good deal of recent "hype" regarding the current and future size of
the static control product business.  Our remit was to provide a candid, comprehensive
and clear assessment of where this business is as of 1991, and where and how fast it
is likely to grow over the medium-term future (out to 1996).  As such, it should be a
valuable input to companies already in this marketplace and to those contemplating
entry into this business.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC STUDIES</B><P>

BCC has covered the field of plastics and non-plastic materials in the fields of ESD,
EMI/RFI shielding and electronics in general for many years in its multi-client
reports.  A sample of these studies includes the following:<P>

<MENU>P-064R Plastics in Business Machines (5/86)<BR>
P-068  Inherently Conductive Polymers (9/88)<BR>
P-098  Plastics in Electrical Connectors (11/91)<BR>
 P-099 ESD:  Opportunities for Plastics in Static Control
 Product Markets (10/87)<BR>
GB-066NPlastics EMI Shielding (5/89)</MENU><P>

In addition, BCC has conducted several custom (single-client) studies in each of these fields for domestic and foreign customers.<P>


