<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-102  INDUSTRIAL HOLLOW PLASTIC PARTS:
MARKETS BY TECHNOLOGY
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2> P-102  INDUSTRIAL HOLLOW PLASTIC PARTS:
MARKETS BY TECHNOLOGY</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>WILLIAM MURRAY</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>CONTEXT OF REPORT</B><P>

BCC has covered the production of large plastic parts several
times in the past, but in each instance it has been focused on
the application.  In this report we have examined the methods of
producing hollow plastic parts.  Parts such as automobile fuel
tanks, underground chemical storage tanks, pressure vessels,
drums, and many others fall into the scope of this report.  Blow-
molded plastic bottles (less than 2 gallons in size) are
excluded, while larger carboys are included.  The report look
most closely at three processing methods:<P>

                Blow Molding
                Rotational Molding
                Filament Winding<P>

While the majority of hollow plastic parts are produced using
these three methods, some injection molding, reaction injection
molding, structural foam molding, and others are used in specific
applications.  They are discussed, but not in detail.  The report
also looks at the soluble core processing method that is a
direct, more economical replacement for the lost core process.<P>

Each of the processes is competitive in that they are all methods
of producing hollow plastic parts.  However, there seems to be
very little direct competition in the marketplace.  Each process
offers distinct advantages over the other, whether it be in the
types of materials that can be used, the kind and cost of
machinery, or the cost economics of differing volume production
runs.<P>

Have improved processing methods allowed plastics to replace
other materials in holow part programs?<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY OF THE REPORT</B><P>

BCC has once again surveyed the range of plastics processors in
order to develop realistic estimates of the use of plastics in
the production of hollow parts.  We initially referenced all the
relevant literature and company reports/releases dealing with the
resins, machinery and designs used to manufacture hollow plastic
parts.  We followed up this stage by reviewing the recent patents
on materials and processing methods.  We then consulted with
officials at leading companies and small businesses as well, at
every stage of the production of a hollow plastic part such as:<P>

                resin manufacturers
                machinery manufacturers
                captive and custom molders
                hollow part end-users.<P>

We also consulted with associations dealing with the different
processing methods and applications.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THIS REPORT</B><P>

As in previous BCC reports on plastics processing, this report
will be a valuable input for those companies active in the field
of selling (or contemplating selling) materials and machinery in
the market for hollow plastic parts.  It will also be very useful
to those companies already processing plastics to make hollow
parts.<P>


<B>PREVIOUS BCC RELATED REPORTS</B><P>

BCC has published several recent reports that cover the whole
range of plastics processing methods for both packaging and non-
packaging applications.  Among them are the following:<P>

    P-078  "Large Molded Parts: Competing Processes and Markets"
    P-029X "Blow-Molded Plastic Bottles"
    P-077R "The Rigid Container Business"SUMMARY<P>



