<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-112R  DEGRADABLE PLASTICS: IMPACT ON LITTER AND SOLID
WASTE DISPOSAL
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-112R  DEGRADABLE PLASTICS: IMPACT ON LITTER AND SOLID
WASTE DISPOSAL
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>FRANK RENAUD
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This report provides an analysis of the impact that degradable
plastic products will have in helping solve the problem of
disposing of post-consumer plastic waste.  We believe that it is
within this context that the strategic importance of degradable
plastics can best be appreciated.  Hence, the study looks at the
present and future status of the degradable plastics industry.  It
probes the present and future demand and supply levels of various
types of degradable plastics, the technological difficulties now
encountered, and the breakthroughs foreseen.  The report also
identifies the major producers and their strategies, as well as the
end-uses for degradable plastic products.<P>



<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>



At the onset of the environmental movement a few short years ago,
degradable plastic products were seen as a panacea for the disposal
of post-consumer plastic waste.  How better to deal with plastic
refuse than to have it disappear into thin air!  This enthusiasm
brought about a flurry of activity.  However, over-enthusiastic
manufacturers of diapers, grocery and trash bags ended up promising
more than they could deliver.  The very concept of degradability
quickly became mired in confusion.  Misleading claims led to legal
actions.  Today, whenever degradable plastic products are mentioned, consumers are more likely to express a healthy dose of
skepticism than all-out enthusiasm.<P>


Nevertheless, scientific research into this important area of
plastics technology is going forward.  New approaches, new
products, and an increasing number of manufacturers and converters
have joined the ranks of the pioneers.  Today, the industry is
alive, and new developments promise further, if not guaranteed,
growth.  It is appropriate, therefore, that we take a comprehensive
look at these new findings and new products and assess expectations
over the next ten years.<P>


Another reason for doing this study is the need to emphasize
degradability as one of several solutions to our waste disposal
problems.  For example, we all know by now that the success of the
Plastics Industry during the last 15 years has been overwhelming.
Sales and production of virgin resins have increased at a record
pace, and few markets have remained untouched by the onslaught of
new plastic products.<P>


The flip side of that success is the volume of plastic products now
being discarded every year.  The volume of post-consumer plastic
waste is building up rapidly.  Given the increased level of
environmental awareness and the alleged decline in landfill
capacity, alternate solutions have to be found to dispose of this
rapidly accumulating tonnage of waste.<P>


Among the various solutions offered, incineration and recycling
appear to be the most promising on technological and economic
grounds.  Incineration, unfortunately, is proving unacceptable on
environmental grounds.  It has also become obvious that recycling
alone will not be sufficient to handle all of the post-consumer
plastic waste expected over the next decade.  According to our own
estimates (see BCC reports P-125, The Secondary Recycling Plastics
Business, and P-132, Technology of Plastic Waste Recycling), by
the year 2000 we are expected to recycle less than 6 billion pounds
of HDPE, PET, LDPE, etc.   That will represent a mere 7% of
the total stock of post-consumer plastic waste expected that year.
The other 93% (more than 50 billion pounds) will still
continue to be discarded in landfills unless another solution can
be found.<P>


It is the contention of this report that, over the next 10 years,
degradable plastics will begin playing a crucial role in helping
solve our waste disposal problems.<P>



<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY</B><P>

This report will prove most useful to all those actively involved
in trying to find solutions to the disposal of post-consumer
plastic waste.  More particularly, recyclers, composters, incinerators, and manufacturers of degradable resins, additives, and other
degradable products should benefit from our analysis.  These
professionals will find in this report a one-stop source of
information on the present and future status of an increasingly
important segment of the plastics industry which has had its image
tarnished but is also making a strong comeback.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The study is limited to three main areas-namely, the biodegradability and photodegradability of synthetic resins and the
degradability of natural plastics.  By concentrating on those three
major topics, we are better able to provide a more comprehensive
coverage of both recent and expected future developments.<P>



<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>



This study could not have been completed without the input of the
large number of scientists and manufacturers that we contacted.
Their insights have proved to be extremely valuable, and we thank
them for their contribution.  We must emphasize, nevertheless, that
the conclusions reached are our own, and we are solely responsible
for the views expressed in the report.  We have also made use of
the voluminous literature published in trade and scientific
journals.  Research on degradability is expanding if we can judge
by the number of scientific papers published on that topic.<P>



<B>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>



BCC has published several important studies in the area of waste
management and plastics recycling.  The following should be of
particular interest to BCC clients:<P>



