<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE> P-120R POLYMERIC FOAMS, A HUGE SUB-INDUSTRY
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2> P-120R POLYMERIC FOAMS, A HUGE SUB-INDUSTRY </H2>
<HR><P>
<I>HOWARD KIBBEL </I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B>


<P>BCC's last study devoted to the plastics foam industry, published
in 1990, characterized the raw materials, foams, markets,
technologies and the key companies at each level of foam
fabrication and consumption.  In the interim three-year period a
great deal has occurred in terms of environmental factors that
already are affecting not only the overall markets for foam
products but also the market shares of individual foam-grade
resins.  These issues relate to solid waste (e.g., recycling),
consumer safety (e.g., flammability) and atmospheric protection
(e.g., ozone-depletion/global warming).  We are now able to discuss
those issues in greater detail and apply demand forecasts based on
a better understanding as to what level of impact these
environmental issues have on foam consumption.</P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B>

<P>This study deals with the rigid and flexible foams employed for
their insulative and cushioning properties in a variety of major
markets, such as transportation, building and construction,
packaging, electrical/electronics, appliances and home products
(e.g., bedding, furniture and rug underlay).  In addition, we have
included structural foam products which compete against traditional
molded plastics due to their cost/performance advantages.</P>

<P>The demand data presented are supported by market trends, affected
not only by conventional market factors such as pricing,
intermaterial competition and industry macroeconomics but also the
environmental issues of recycling, flammability and ozone
depletion/global warming, which have become accepted factors in
determining material usage.  Current and forecast demand data are
presented for the years 1990, 1992, 1993 and 1998.  These data
points represent the most accurate description of the current
demand situation, and provide an insight into the short-term growth
that can be expected.  For most of the data tables, five-year
average annual growth rates are calculated for the period 1993-
1998.  In some cases, growth rates are calculated for the eight-
year period from 1990-1998.</P>

<B>METHODOLOGY</B>

<P>The research for this study included personal contacts with key
participants among the users of foam products in all markets, resin
suppliers, suppliers of foam systems, foam molders and raw material
suppliers.  The information gathered from these primary sources
formed the basis for our estimates of current resin usage in foam
markets.  Their forecasts for future demand of resin and product
were merged with our analysis of industry trends and the
probabilities of resin consumption to meet future demand.  Our
final analyses and projections are based on a combination of a
consensus among the primary contacts and our understanding of the
impact of trends from an historical perspective.</P>

<P>In addition, we reviewed secondary sources of information such as
trade publications, trade associations, company literature,
industry conferences and on-line databases to supplement our
understanding of the markets, applications and trends affecting the
resins used in portable electronics devices.  Data from government
sources yielded information on the macroeconomic trends in the
relevant industries.  Also, the analyses of environmental issues
impacting on foam markets are based on legislative- and regulatory-
type information gathered from governmental agencies at the
national, state and local levels.  Finally, trends and technologies
of foam  products outside the United States are reviewed to
demonstrate foreign influence on the U.S. foam industry.</P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B>

<P>The foam industry is a major segment of the U.S. plastics industry,
accounting for 5-10% of resin consumption.  Foams offer insulative
and cushioning characteristics to industrial and consumer products,
which contribute not only to energy conservation and protective
shipping but also to source reduction (i.e., less material that
ultimately is added to the wastestream) and lower manufacturing
costs.</P>

<P>Prior to the 1990s, the plastics industry had only marginal effects
from environmental issues.  This study was commissioned not only to
review new foam materials and technologies developed since the
earlier study but also to provide companies participating in the
foam industry with an analysis of the level of impact from
environmental issues.  The study can be useful, as well, to
financial institutions and venture capitalists interested in
emerging technologies with large growth potential, and to foreign-
based companies seeking to understand the dynamics of U.S. foam
markets in an atmosphere of anti-plastics legislation and
government regulation.</P>

<B>RELATED BCC STUDIES</B>

<P>BCC traditionally has followed the various industries in which
plastics resins are consumed.  These studies typically cover
plastics demand and performance criteria, competing materials,
relevant technologies, major players, market trends and government
legislative and regulatory impact on plastics.  There are several
recently-published studies, cited below, which deal with some
aspect of the technologies, materials and markets for foam
products.</P>

<UL>

<LI>GB-166   The Changing Refrigeration Industry                6/93

<LI>P-112R   Degradable Plastics: Impact on Litter & Solid      1/93
         Waste Disposal

<LI>P-139    Environmentally Impacted Additives for Plastics    8/92

<LI>P-081B   Opportunities for Plastics in Household            6/92
         Appliances

<LI>P-126    The Impact of Environmental Issues on Plastics     8/91
         Packaging
</UL>


