<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-120U POLYMERIC FOAMS: A HUGE SUB-INDUSTRY
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-120U POLYMERIC FOAMS: A HUGE SUB-INDUSTRY
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>J. CHARLES FORMAN, Ph.D.</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>

</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>



In the slightly more than two years since BCC's last study on the
polymeric foams industry, significant changes continue  to  occur
in  this  major segment of the plastics production and processing
industry.<P>


Products  and  markets change as technology and  society  change.
Polymer   foams  find  their  primary  applications  in  consumer
products,  such  as  cushioning for  furniture  and  automobiles,
thermal  insulation for construction and packaging,  and  similar
end uses which are driven by the business cycle.<P>

Most  of  the  markets for plastic foams are the same  ones  that
existed  a  few years ago; however, there are a couple of  faster
growing  newer  markets, such as expanded polypropylene  foam  in
auto  bumpers and foamed PVC in house siding, windows/doors,  and
other construction shapes.<P>

Polymers  are foamed for reasons of cost and performance.  Foamed
plastics are lighter than non-foamed articles made from the  same
resin,  and therefore require less resin and achieve lower costs.
Equally  or more important, foamed plastics have properties  that
are  not  attainable  with non-foamed ones.  The  insulating  and
cushioning  qualities of the gas bubbles in a foamed article  are
obvious  attributes, but less obvious is the fact that  a  foamed
article  is  often  stronger  than its  non-foamed  analog.  Thus
structural shapes and forms, such as piping and wall siding,  can
be stronger when foamed.<P>

What  has driven these markets in this decade and caused the most
significant changes have been environmental and public perception
issues.  Environmental issues include:<P>

   -  Consumer  safety issues, ranging from fire  resistance  and
flammability  to  concerns  over the use  of  plastic  which  are
claimed   (almost  always  erroneously)  to  be  health   hazards
(especially carcinogens).<P>

   -  Solid waste disposal and recycling, a continuing public and
political "hot button" of the 1990s.<P>

   - Atmospheric protection, caused by concerns and actions taken
regarding   blowing  agents  used  to  produce  foamed
plastics.<P>
Because  of  concerns  over the earth's ozone  layer  and  global
warming,  chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) have been banned  and  their
first  group of replacements, HCFCs, are also planned for  phase
out  early  in  the  next century.  Volatile hydrocarbon  blowing
agents are under increased control as air polluting VOCs.<P>
Our  goal  is to describe the most common and popular  commercial
polymeric   foams  and  their  applications,  their   technology,
competing  plastic and foams and those made from other materials,
and  future trends.  We estimate and forecast markets for plastic
foams of several kinds, in many different important markets  such
as construction, transportation, and packaging.  The polymers and
applications that we cover are discussed below in "Scope."<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

Polymer  foams touch our lives every day, in unseen  applications
such  as  the insulating sheathing on our houses and  inside  our
refrigerators,  and in visible end uses such as the  foamed  seat
cushion  and the polystyrene "hot cup" used for fast food coffee.
These products are important items in the economy, and because of
the  environmental issues noted above, represent  an  interesting
dynamic of the American society in the 1990s.<P>

The  plastic  foam industry is a major segment  of  the  American
plastics  industry, accounting for about 10% of  total  commodity
resin  consumption.   Foamed products, such  as  those  used  for
insulation and protective shipping, reduce energy consumption and
product damage, and thus lead to lower manufacturing costs,  less
waste, and other good results.<P>

BCC performed this study to provide a comprehensive reference for
those  interested and/or involved in these products;  this  is  a
wide  and varied group of chemical and other companies that  make
and use polymer foams, process technology and equipment designers
and  marketers,  politicians  of all  stripes,  and  the  general
public. We have sorted through and condensed information  from  a
large  amount  of  literature and other  reference  materials  to
compile this report.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This  report  is  intended to assist those  involved  in  several
different segments of the U.S. industrial and commercial business
sectors,  primarily  those  whose main  interest  is  in  thermal
insulation  (construction, appliances,  and  the  like),  comfort
cushioning    (furniture,   auto   seats,   and   other    uses),
transportation  (other  automotive  parts  such   as   protective
cushioning, bumpers, and other parts), and packaging.<P>

These organizations and people include those who are involved  in
the  development,  formulation, manufacture,  sale,  and  use  of
foamed  polymers  and  polymer foaming processes,  and  ancillary
businesses  such  as processing equipment, additives,  and  other
support  chemicals  and  equipment.  These  include  process  and
product  development  experts,  process  and  product  designers,
purchasing  agents, construction and operating personnel,  market
staff, and top management. BCC feels that this report will be  of
great  value to technical and business personnel in the following
areas, among others:<P>

  - Marketing and management personnel in companies that produce,
market, and sell polymeric foams.<P>

   - Companies involved in the design and construction of process
plants  which manufacture polymeric foams and those that  service
these plants.<P>
   -  Companies  that  supply  chemicals,  equipment,  and  other
materials to plastic foam producers and users.<P>
    -  Basic  research  personnel  in  academia,  goverment,  and
industry.<P>
  - Financial institutions that supply money for such facilities,
including  banks,  merchant  bankers,  venture  capitalists,  and
others.   Such  institutions need to identify and know  areas  of
potential trouble as well.<P>

   - Personnel in end-user companies and industries; these are  a
wide  ranging  group  of  companies in industries  as  varied  as
automobile manufacturing and healthcare products packaging.<P>

   -  Personnel in  government at many levels, not  only  at  the
federal level (such as the federal EPA), but also state and local
health,  environmental, and other regulators who  must  implement
and enforce the laws regarding public health and safety.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This  BCC  study  covers  in depth many  of  the  most  important
technological,    economic,    political,    and    environmental
considerations  in  the  U.S. polymeric foams  industry.   It  is
primarily  a  study of U.S. markets, but because  of  the  global
nature  of  polymer and packaging chemistry it  touches  on  some
noteworthy  international activities; these are  primarily  those
that   can   have   an  impact  on  the  U.S.  market   such   as
imports/exports and foreign firms which operate here.<P>

All market figures are rounded to the nearest million pounds, and
all  growth  rates  are compounded (signified as  average  annual
growth  rates  or AAGRs). Because of this rounding,  some  growth
rates  may  not agree exactly with figures in the market  tables.
All market figures are at the manufacturer's or producer's
level.<P>

This  report in segmented into 10 sections, of which this is  the
first.<P>

Section  II,  Summary, encapsulates our findings and conclusions,
and  includes summary major market tables.  It is the place where
the  busy  executive can find the major findings of the study  in
summary format.<P>

Section  III  is  an overview to the industry, starting  with  an
introduction to the petrochemical industry that is the source  of
polymers, and the plastic resin industries which make the  resins
that  go  into  polymer foams. We introduce polymeric  foams  and
discuss each of the major foamed plastics and its principal  foam
structure.   We  end  with a discussion of  some  competing  foam
materials. Our intent in this section is to introduce the  reader
to the field of polymers and foamed plastics and foam
structures.<P>

Section IV discusses and forecasts markets for foamed plastics by
material  types.  These include three classes of major  commodity
resins  used  to  produce  foams: polyolefins,  polystyrene,  and
polyvinyl chloride. We focus on the largest foamed polymer group,
the  polyurethanes (PURs). We also include some  specialty  foams
such  as  phenolics and structural foams, and  also  analyze  and
forecast  markets  for plastic foam blowing agents  and  PUR  raw
materials.<P>

We  start  this  section  with our overall  market  analysis  and
forecast  for the major types of polymeric foams, for  base  year
1995  and  forecast  year  2000.  Then,  in  each  subsection  we
describe  each type of foam in more detail, discuss its important
applications, and forecast its market in more detail.<P>

Section  V  discusses and forecasts the markets by  polymer  foam
application. We have categorized applications into seven specific
major   groups:   appliances  (primarily   thermal   insulation),
building/construction    (primarily    insulation     and     PVC
profiles/shapes), electrical/electronics (with the largest market
in acoustical and noise control foams), furniture and furnishings
(mainly  comfort  cushioning),  medical  applications,  packaging
(both  functional  and  product protection),  and  transportation
(primarily cushioning). We end with a group of other applications
ranging from sports equipment to shoe insoles and powder puffs.<P>

Section  VI is devoted to technologies, starting with some  basic
polymer  chemistry, manufacture, and properties of plastics  used
in  producing  plastic  foams. We  go  on  to  conventional  foam
technologies.   We then cover some new polymer foam technologies,
including   new   blowing  agents  and  polyol  technology,   and
microcellular  foams.   We  end  with  a  discussion  of  polymer
recycling technology.<P>

Section VII covers the structure of the polymeric foams industry,
with  emphasis on the major domestic producers and suppliers  and
trends  in  the  industry.  We briefly discuss and  analyze  some
international  aspects  of  the business,  including  the  global
nature  of  the business, major foreign owned supplier  companies
which operate in the United States, and trends outside the United
States.<P>

Section VIII covers environmental, regulatory, and public  policy
issues,  items  of  increasing importance to  the  polymer  foams
industry.   Environmental considerations rate the  most  emphasis
because  of  the  rapid  change in blowing agent  technology  and
markets, health and safety, and waste disposal/recycling.<P>

Section  IX  consists of profiles of some 80  supplier  companies
which  BCC  considers to be among the most important and/or  best
representatives of this business.<P>

Section  X  is a glossary of some important terms, abbreviations,
acronyms,  etc. used in the chemical, polymer, and polymer  foams
industries.<P>

Some topics and materials covered in the text of this report  are
not  included  in our market forecast tables. A good  example  is
microcellular  foams,  an  exciting but  not  yet  commercialized
technology.  We include these for completeness; however, they are
either really outside the market scope of this study, or are  too
new to have yet developed a measurable commercial market.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY AND INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Searches  were  made  of the literature, including  many  of  the
leading  trade  publications, as well as technical compendia  and
government  publications.  Product  and  market  information  was
obtained  whenever  possible  from the  companies  involved.  The
information  for  our corporate profiles was  obtained  primarily
from  the companies, especially the larger publicly owned  firms.
Other sources included directories and articles.<P>

