<CENTER><H2>TITLE</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>NAME</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The hose and tubing industry is a moderately large and broad-based sector of the North American economy and it serves many masters.  The industry can be logically separated into three hose sectors:  automotive hose, general 
industrial hose, and hydraulic hose; and two tubing sectors:  industrial 
tubing and medical tubing.  Each of these sectors contains several 
subcategories. Demand within all sectors, with the exception of medical 
tubing, ebbs and flows with the health of the national economy.<P> 

Hose and tubing fabrication methods have become more or less standardized, 
with the major producers achieving comparable levels of efficiency. Quality 
control measures have been and are continuing to be upgraded to meet 
International Standards Organization (ISO) standards, to reduce rejection 
rates and to ensure against product liability claims.  Manufacturers work 
closely with compounders and producers of resins and elastomers to introduce 
improved hose and tubing materials.<P> 

Regulatory and environmental standards are pushing the limits of available 
product capabilities, especially in the motor vehicle sector.  Certain 
materials are gaining share at the expense of others as the entire industry 
adapts to these new demands.<P> 

In that resins and elastomers are integral to describing this industry, this 
report contains a detailed description and analysis of each of the major 
resins used in hose and tubing applications.<P> 

It provides the reader with a comprehensive understanding of the markets for 
hose and tubing in North America and of the major raw materials employed.  It 
gives an accurate bearing on where the industry is heading as we move into the 
latter part of this decade.<P> 

This report:<P>

 <LI>        Describes the industry, its importance to the economy and
          its future prospects<P>

 <LI>        Provides a brief historical perspective on the industry<P>

  <LI>       Analyzes each sector of the hose and tubing market and
          describes the primary types of hose and tubing in use
          within each market segment<P>

 <LI>        Gives the volume and value of hose and tubing shipments
          for the years 1988 and 1993, and provides a forecast of
          volume and value for the year 1998<P>

<LI>         Analyzes the primary competitive markets and determines
          market share held by competing manufacturers within each
          market and in subsectors within those markets<P>

   <LI>      Describes the primary types of hose and tubing materials
          and identifies the specific resins, elastomers and
          thermoplastic elastomers employed in each market and
          market subsector<P>

  <LI>       Analyzes the current and historical volume and value of
          shipments for each type of hose and tubing material in
          each market category and makes a forecast for the year
          1998<P>

  <LI>       Analyzes the important changes impacting the industry<P>

<LI>         Describes manufacturing methods and economics<P>

<LI>         Identifies the important suppliers of resins and
          elastomers to the industry<P>

<LI>         Describes recent technological developments and trends
          within the industry<P>

<LI>         Reviews exports, imports and the U.S. balance of trade<P>

<LI>         Discusses regulatory and environmental issues and
          concerns

<LI>         Profiles the most important producers of hose and tubing
          products.<P>


<b>REASONS FOR THIS STUDY</B><P>

Important changes have occurred within this industry in recent years and the 
pace of change will likely quicken as environmental and regulatory 
requirements continue to tighten.  Competition for market share is keen within 
all hose and tubing sectors, and capacity use remains low in some sectors in 
spite of strong demand. Repositioning and new product introductions within 
certain high performance sectors are especially active.   The development of 
novel technologies has enabled certain producers to gain an edge while 
improvements in manufacturing economies have aided others.<P> 

On the raw material side, demand has recovered significantly but plenty of 
capacity is in place.  Prices, which held relatively static for the prior five 
years, began to rapidly escalate in late 1993 and 1994.  Use of thermoplastic 
elastomers is climbing in all markets at the expense of traditional materials, 
and high performance thermoplastics such as nylons and fluorocarbons are 
growing as quality and longevity win out over economy.<P> 

The participants in this industry need to be acutely aware of these 
developments to intelligently plan for the future.  This report brings these 
factors into focus and provides manufacturers, distributors, users, and raw 
material suppliers with the knowledge needed to make informed decisions 
relating to investment, procurement and material selection.<P> 


<b>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THIS STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This report provides up-to-date technical and market information concerning 
the manufacture, distribution, regulation and shipments of hose and tubing.  
It also provides historical and forecast data on the volume and value of the 
elastomers and resins used as the raw materials for hoses and tubing and 
describes the competitive environment surrounding the industry.  It shows the 
market share held by the important producers in each major market segment and 
profiles the most important companies.  It is intended to inform producers and 
distributors of hoses and tubing and their raw material suppliers, as well as 
users of hoses and tubing and other parties interested in this multifaceted 
industry.<P> 


<b>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The scope of this report is North America with a strong emphasis on the U.S.  
The important types of hose and tube are differentiated into rubber, 
thermoplastic, and thermoplastic elastomer, according to the elastomer or 
resin used. Much emphasis is placed on the analysis of hose and tube markets 
and hose and tube materials.<P> 

We have not included metal tubing in this report.  Metal tubing is used 
primarily in markets where plastic and rubber are simply inappropriate, such 
as air-conditioning and refrigeration condensers.  There is an overlap in 
certain applications and we make note of these when appropriate throughout the 
report. Hydraulics is an example of a sector where metal tubing competes with 
plastic and rubber hose; and the semiconductor where metal tubing competes 
with plastic and rubber hose; and the semiconductor and pneumatic control 
industries exemplify applications where metal tubing competes with 
thermoplastic and TPE-based tubing.<P>

Metal tubing continues to be displaced by 
rubber and plastic materials.  The rate of conversion has slowed quite 
dramatically in sectors such as hydraulics but remains very strong in the 
semiconductor sector.  We comment on those market segments where metal tubing 
is competitive and offer some insight into the importance of the specific use 
as it relates to volume gain or loss to rubber and plastic hose and tubing.<P> 


<b>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

The extensive research capabilities of the BCC staff were accessed to analyze 
markets, consumption trends and supply and demand.  New technologies, market 
developments and present and future trends were identified through patent and 
literature searches and discussions with key industry sources.  Current 
regulatory and environmental issues were ascertained through discussions with 
industry sources, relevant agencies and literature searches. Manufacturing 
methods, process economics, international trade statistics and major 
influences on the industry were derived from discussions with a wide range of 
industry and government sources.<P> 


<b>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

This report is an analysis and summation of interviews with hundreds of key 
industry officials, trade association representatives, consultants, users of 
hose and tubing, and governmental personnel.  Statistics on shipments were 
obtained from the U.S. Department of Commerce and from industry trade 
association sources.<P> 


