<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-125  THE SECONDARY RECYCLING PLASTICS BUSINESS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-125  THE SECONDARY RECYCLING PLASTICS BUSINESS</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>FRANK RENAUD</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This report provides a comprehensive study of the present and
future recycling rates for various plastic resin markets.  It
analyzes, in detail, the stock of plastic material available for
recycling, by types of plastic resin and by life expectancy
groups.  Those stock estimates are compared to the amounts of
plastic resin being recycled and recycling rates are derived.
Forecasts for stocks, amounts to be recycled and recycling rates
are provided through the year 2000.  The report also identifies
the most important recyclers and their productive capacity.  It
focuses on the technological problems encountered and the
breakthroughs recorded and expected.  Other topics covered include
the end-use markets for the recycled resins and the financial
considerations affecting present and future recycling efforts.<P>



<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>



In 1990, plastic resin sales in the U.S. totaled 61.5 billion
pounds, 5.5 per cent more than in 1989.  Between 1979 and 1990,
plastic resin sales more than doubled, placing the plastics
industry among the top industrial performers of the decade.  Yet,
the plastics industry has been unable to rest on its laurels.  For
the last three years, it has been embroiled in an environmental
controversy threatening both its future rate of growth and its
ability to compete effectively against alternative materials.<P>


Concerned consumers have become acutely aware of the severity of
the waste disposal problems facing their communities.  For reasons
that remain mostly unclear, plastic products, especially plastic
packaging products, are perceived as major contributors to those
problems.  In the process, legislators are constantly being
pressured to enact a wide ranging number of laws restricting
either the sale or the uses of plastic products, especially
packaging products.<P>


Most of those worries seem to be misplaced, however.  So far,
scientific evidence has shown that plastic products are not major
contributors to our waste disposal problems.  At most, plastic
products make up only 18 per cent of our landfills when waste is
measured by volume and maybe as little as 7 per cent to 8 per cent
when it is measured by weight.  In contrast, paper and paperboard
products contribute more than 5 times that level in terms of
weight and more than twice in terms of volume.<P>


Regardless, the plastics industry has taken note of the criticisms
directed at its products and it has reacted positively.  In a
previous report on the plastics and paper bag markets (The
Changing Bag Markets: Highlighting Intermaterials Competitions,
BCC Report #P-082), we described at length the achievements of the
plastics industry and its efforts to introduce degradable bags.
More promising, however, are the recycling efforts of the plastics
industry.  In the last two years alone, there has been a virtual
avalanche of new recycling projects started across the country.
So far, efforts have concentrated on the collection, sorting and
recycling of plastic packaging material, especially soft drink PET
bottles and HDPE milk and HIC bottles.  Efforts are also under way
to recycle other plastic products such as T-shirt bags, film and
polystyrene containers.  Little is being done, however, to recycle
durable and semi-durable products such as toys and household
appliances.<P>


Markets for recycled resins continue to be developed.  The most
promising new developments focus on utilizing recycled pellets to
make the same products that were recycled.  This is known as
"closing the loop."  By the end of this decade, we believe that a
large range of plastic containers and a host of other non-
packaging plastic products, regardless of resins, will contain
some fraction of recycled resins in their structure.  Some of the
recycled pellets will compete with virgin resins for a share of
the markets.<P>


It is therefore important, at this stage of development, to take a
close look at what is being done, in which area and by whom.  We
also need to look at the opportunities faced by this young
industry as well as at the drawbacks that may hamper its future
growth.  We need to address the financial problems encountered and
the opportunities that are developing.<P>



<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY</B><P>



This report hopes to emphasize two sets of problems: the growing
stock of non-packaging recyclable material during the 1990s and
the low recycling rate of this type of plastic material.  The
report also highlights the limits and opportunities of present and
future recycling efforts.<P>

To achieve our objectives, we focus on the recycling rate.  We
first calculate, for each type of resin, how many pounds of resins
are available for recycling and compare those estimates to the
number of pounds of plastic resin that are actually being
recycled.  We also look into such questions as who the main
players are, how profitable recycling is, and what is being
manufactured with those recycled resins.<P>


By performing this analysis, we are better able to evaluate the
future of the recycling industry and its role within the broader
context of the plastics industry itself.<P>



<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>



This study is limited to those plastic products that are being or
will shortly be recycled.  As such, we will study the following
resins: high density polyethylene (HDPE), polystyrene (PS),
polyvinyl chloride (PVC), low density polyethylene (LDPE),
polyethylene terephthalate (PET) and polypropylene (PP).<P>


In the first section of the report, we review some of the most
important issues concerning the future of the plastic recycling
efforts.  We analyze, for example, the role of plastics in
landfills, the legal climate facing both the plastic resin
manufacturers and the sales of plastic products, and the
technological problems that need to be resolved by recyclers.<P>


In the following sections, we focus on individual resins.  For
each one, we define three groups of recyclable stocks and compare
those estimates to the amounts of resin being recycled to derive a
recycling rate. We tackle such issues as the collection, sorting
and processing difficulties hampering recycling efforts.  We
identify the major recyclers and their productive capacity.  We
also look into the economics of recycling and the end-use products
for recycled resins.  For each resin, we also provide long-term
recycling rate forecasts.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>



This study relies heavily on two types of inputs.  First, we
obtained important insights from our discussions with a large
number of company officials, both in the marketing and technical
areas, involved in the recycling of plastic products.  Second, we
also benefited from the scientific and business literature that is
rapidly becoming available.  The recycling of plastic products is
being studied not only by the technical departments of plastics
companies themselves but by a host of other interested parties
such as university research laboratories, environmentalist groups,
municipal services departments in charge of waste management and
industry trade organizations.  We have incorporated the
contributions of the various groups that have been most generous
in sharing with us their concern and extensive knowledge.<P>



<B>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>



BCC has been actively studying plastic packaging and recycling for
more than 15 years.  It has published numerous reports in that
field and the following should be of interest to BCC clients:<P>

<MENU>GB127   The Solid Waste Recycling Business<BR>
