<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-126  THE IMPACT OF ENVIRONMENTAL ISSUES
ON PLASTIC PACKAGING
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-126  THE IMPACT OF ENVIRONMENTAL ISSUES
ON PLASTIC PACKAGING</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>HOWARD KIBBEL</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>BACKGROUND</B><P>

This report deals with the solid waste management issues,
especially recycling, which have had (and will continue to have) a
significant impact on the materials used in packaging, the manner
in which they are processed, packaging forms, and the markets for
plastic packaging.  It discusses in detail the attempts by all
participants in the packaging market to provide packaging that
satisfies consumer demands for environmentally-friendly products
while remaining cost-effective.  It reviews food and non-food
flexible and rigid packaging forms and the major markets that these
products serve.  Specific packaging forms such as bags, liners,
coatings, bottles, cups, closures, etc. and the markets they serve
are discussed in detail.<P>

The analyses in this report are specific to the plastics packaging
market and do not deal with the collection, identification,
separation, and processing techniques involved in plastics
recycling.  Those issues are covered in a companion study published
recently by Business Communications Company (BCC).<P>


<B>OBJECTIVES</B><P>

In this report we discuss how the recycling decision-makers
influence plastic packaging.  Most important among these are the
Federal, state and local lawmakers who have the power to mandate
the use of certain materials or (vice versa), preclude the use of
certain materials which do not satisfy the requirements of the law.
The inability of these lawmakers to pass consistent legislation
relating to solid waste issues is the primary reason that forecasts
of future plastic packaging demand are difficult to quantify.  The
many variables involved include which states or localities will
pass recycling or degradability legislation, to what degree will
that legislation impact which plastics, and when will the
legislation become effective (e.g., implementation timetable).<P>

Legislators, however, do not operate in a vacuum; they should be
responsive to the constituencies they represent.  While the vast
majority of the U.S. public are generally in favor of protecting
the environment, they are not united on what options will best
accomplish that goal.  They are easily influenced by printed and
visual media offerings.  The most outspoken spokesperson for the
public on this subject, the environmentalist, has risen from the
masses to lead the charge in favor of environmentally-friendly
products and opposed, violently, those products which they deem
unfriendly.  It is the impact of these environmentalists, who
created "green consumerism", that this study reviews since they
have had the most influence on consumer end-use packaging and
consumer-legislator packaging issues.<P>

In response to the outcry from consumers and legislators for
"better packaging", the packaging end-user has turned to the
package designer and he in turn to the material supplier and
fabricator to redesign packages and alter materials and material
processing so that packaging markets would not be lost. The study
shows how the package designer communicates his concerns about a
package's ability to meet environmental protection requirements to
those who take his design from conception to product, the material
suppliers and the fabricators.<P>

The plastics industry has addressed solid waste management issues
through material substitution, source reduction (e.g., downsizing),
changes in processing technology, new polymer grades, new additive systems, and by creating
degradable technologies.  Each of these is reviewed in  terms of its success
in accomplishing environmental objectives, achieving satisfactory recyclable
materials, maintaining performance properties, and maintaining acceptable
cost structures. The study analyzes how competing material industries have dealt
with and succeeded/failed in their efforts to meet environmental needs.

Solid waste management issues have created opportunities for some
plastic materials and meant loss of markets for others.  Each of
the packaging forms is analyzed in terms of what future markets
would exist if there were no environmental impact and what they
might be, based on expected levels of impact.  These calculations
include an analysis of the existing and proposed legislation by
state.  State data are factored into total U.S. consumption by
packaging form and market.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND METHODOLOGY</B><P>

This report is intended to be an objective assessment of the many
factors that influence packaging design, packaging processing, and
packaging materials.  Information sources include trade
associations, relevant published literature, and many interviews
with packaging end-users and companies supplying resins, additives,
and machinery to the packaging market.<P>

The problems and opportunities for plastic packaging are measured
in terms of relative environmental impact, both negative and
positive.  For each packaging type and market, the study gives a
brief overview of the practical use of that product, examples of
how products are changing as a result of environmental
considerations, and statistics are given showing the estimated
growth of that product as if there were no environmental impact,
compared to expected growth because of environmental influences
(although for some products there may be no impact at all).  The
data are supported by text which explains the issues that affect
the forecast.  Data are provided for 1990, the current year (1991),
1992, and an estimate for 1996, with average annual growth rates
calculated for the five-year period from 1991-1996.<P>

In all cases, the descriptions and data relate to the changes in
products, materials, additives, equipment, and markets.  This study
does not pursue the markets for recycled packaging products which
go into other markets, only those products which are returned for
use in the packaging industry. The descriptions relating to
equipment refer not to the conversion of recycled product into
recycled resin, but rather to the modifications made to plastics
processing equipment to accommodate the manufacture of recycled
resin alone or in combination with virgin resin.<P>

<B>SUMMARY</B><P>

The net impact from all environmental factors is estimated to be
the loss of about 700 million pounds of virgin resin in 1991 or 4.7
percent of the  demand originally forecast for the plastic
packaging industry.  By 1996, BCC estimates that 2.2 billion pounds
of virgin resin will be lost due to environmental factors,
representing 13 percent of the 17 billion pounds of forecast demand
for plastics packaging.  The largest impact in 1991 is attributed
to source reduction, a common, continuing feature in plastic
packaging, accounting for more than 55 percent of total virgin
resin loss. By 1996, however, the establishment of recycling
infrastructures for all plastic packaging materials will make the
use of recycled material the number one environmental factor
accounting for almost 50 percent of virgin resin loss.  The
relative impact from each environmental factor, in terms of pounds
of virgin resin loss is shown in Figure I.<P>

Each of these issues will have varying impacts depending on market
usage and material consumed.  For rigid packaging source reduction
currently has the greatest impact accounting for almost half of its
virgin resin loss.  The use of post-consumer recycled material
(PCR) has the second greatest influence today, but BCC estimates
that the huge amount of PCR going into bottles (accounting for the
largest virgin resin loss in any packaging product) will make
recycle content the number one environmental impact on rigid
packaging by 1996.  Substitution effects during the five year
period will remain constant at about 13-17 percent virgin resin
loss.  Degradability, oriented to flexible packaging only, will
have zero impact for the 1991-1996 period.<P>

In flexible packaging, source reduction is (and will continue to
be) the most important environmental factor, although the increased
use of PCR will reduce the current 65 percent of total virgin resin
loss to 44 percent by 1996.  Recycle content, in spite of FDA's
reluctance to allow recycled material in food packaging, will
become the third most influential environmental factor in 1996
displacing degradability.  Substitution will maintain its number
two ranking for the five-year period at 24-28 percent of total
virgin resin loss.  Although the demand for degradable polymers
will increase in the 1991-1996 period, the higher growth forecast
for PCR will drop degradability to last among the environmental
factors for flexible packaging. During the 1991-1996 period, the
growth rates of the various environmental factors will be: source
reduction (6 percent); degradability (12 percent); substitution (17
percent); and, recycle content (41 percent).<P>

The rankings and percentages of the four environmental factors are
shown in Table 1.<P>

