<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-127  FLUOROPOLYMERS: TRENDS, DEVELOPMENTS, MARKETS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-127  FLUOROPOLYMERS: TRENDS, DEVELOPMENTS, MARKETS</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>MELVIN SCHLECHTER</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>SCOPE OF THE STUDY</B><P>

Fluoropolymers hold  a unique  position among the specialty or
engineering thermoplastics.  They are unparalleled in terms of
their ability  to resist  chemical attack,  and as a group they
almost all  qualify as high-temperature resins--that is, able
to resist  long-term thermal excursions above 300 degrees F.  In light
of their  inherent lubricity  and  durability,  they  are  the
materials of  choice in  several applications  such as  plastic
bearings,  gears   and  other   vital  industrial   parts   in
replacement of metals which are vulnerable to corrosion.<P>

The  fluoropolymer  business  began  in  1938  when  a  DuPont
research chemist  sawed apart  an  apparently  empty  cylinder
containing tetrafluoroethylene  gas.   Plunkett, the  research
chemist, performed  this  operation  because  Fron  refrigerant
gases seemed  to disappear  from the  cylinder and  yet weight
measurements indicated  that matter  of some  sort  was  still
present.   In the  cylinder he  found a  white, waxy substance
which was  later to  be called  Teflon.    This  material  was
initially used in the Manhattan project during World War II as
a  coating   for  volatile  elements  in  radioactive  isotope
production.   Teflon did  not appear  in volume  as a commercial
product until the 1950s.  In effect, that time was required to
fully   understand    the   exact    nature   of   these   new
"fluoropolymers,"  their   properties,  and   their  potential
applications in the various manufacturing industries.<P>

The original  fluoropolymer discovered in the DuPont research
lab was  polychlorotrifluoroethylene  (PCTFE).    DuPont  also
commercialized  ethylene-tetrafluoroethylene   (ECTE)  in  the
1940s and  introduced fluorinated ethylene-propylene copolymer
(FEP) in  1960.  The company went on to develop polyvinylidene
fluoride (PVDF) in 1961 and commercially introduce it in 1965.
Then  in   1972,  the  company  introduced  one  of  the  last
fluoropolymer    resins,     perfluoroalkyltetrafluoroethylene
copolymer (PFA).<P>

Today, the  term "fluoropolymer"  covers  a  whole  family  of
resins and  elastomers brought  to the  market by  DuPont  and
other domestic  and foreign  resin  manufacturers.    All  the
fluoropolymers (of  course) contain  fluorine, and the bulk of
these high  -performance materials are fluorocarbon (plastics)
resins,    mostly     analogs    of     ethylene    such    as
polytetrafluoroethylene, polymers of chloro-trifluoroethylene,
fluorinated ethylene,  etc.   Another group  of fluoropolymers
with a  different set  of properties  beyond  high-temperature
resistance and  chemical resistance  are the  fluoroelastomers.
One important  group of fluoroelastomers, for example, are the
polyfluorocilicones.      Both  the  fluorocarbon  resins  and
fluoroelastomers can be homopolymers or copolymers.<P>

Recently a  third category  of fluoropolymers  has  come  into
commercial prominence.   These  are  the  low-molecular-weight
materials  with   a  fluorine   base,  with  varying  chemical
structure  and   functional  advantages  that  go  beyond  the
original fluoropolymers.<P>

A final  category of  fluoropolymers is made up of a series of
miscellaneous   products    which    include    CTFE    fluids,
perfluoromembrane surfactants,  fluoropolymer composites,  and
developmental materials.<P>

Thus, the  fluoropolymer  family  of  resins,  elastomers  and
miscellaneous fluorine-based  plastic materials  that form the
scope of  this  study  are  listed  below,  along  with  their
acronyms:<P>


<B><CENTER>TABLE 1</CENTER>
<CENTER>FLUOROPOLYMER RESIN AND ELASTOMER ACRONYMS</CENTER></B><P>


<PRE><CENTER>RESINS</CENTER><P>

Acronym         Full Chemical Structure

CTFE/VDF        chlorotrifluoroethylene-vinylidene fluoride
                copolymer<BR>

ECTFE           ethylene-chlorotrifluoroethylene copolymer

ETFE            ethylene-tetrafluoroethylene copolymer

FEP             fluorinated ethylene-propylene copolymer

PCTFE           polychlorotrifluoroethylene

PFA             perfluoroalkyl-tetrafluoroethylene copolymer

PTFE            polytetrafluoroethyloene

PVDF            polyvinylidene fluoride

PVF             polyvinyl fluoride

TFE/HFP         tetrafluoroethylene-hexafluoropropylene
                copolymer

<CENTER>ELASTOMERS</CENTER><P>

HFP/VDF         hexafluoropropylene-vinylidene fluoride
                copolymer
 
TFE/P           tetrafluoroethylene-propylene copolymer<BR>

TFE/PFMe        tetrafluoroethylene-perfluoromethylether
                copolymer</PRE><P>


<B>OBJECTIVES OF THE STUDY</B><P>

The major  objective of  this report  is to  provide  existing
players and  companies directly  or indirectly  interested  in
these resins with an up-to-date and reliable assessment of the
fluoropolymer market.  Key elements of this objective are:<P>

<DD>  (a) develop meaningful  market estimates  in volume
    (pounds) and  value (dollars) terms for the present (1991)
    and the medium-term, (1996) <P>

<DD>  (b) segmenting these  volume and  value  data  into
major application areas<P>

<DD> (c) identification  and   analysis   of   important
    worldwide fluoropolymer  suppliers as  to specific products
    and overall sales and market shares,<P>

<DD> (d) assessing the  various factors  impacting  this
marketplace,<P>

 <DD> (e) describing the synthesis/production of the more
    commercially important fluoropolymers,<P>

 <DD> (f) contrasting the advantages and disadvantages of
    each of  the major  fluoropolymer types,  vis-*-vis  other
    plastic materials inside and outside this group, and<P>

<DD> (g) evaluating the  recent and likely future growth
    in  European   and  Japanese   markets,  as  well  as  the
    suppliers, wherever possible.<P>

In effect,  new product developments here and elsewhere in the
world have  necessitated a  complete reappraisal  of the  many
fluoropolymers. Demands  of the  marketplace  have  shifted  in
terms  of   reassessing  the   cost/performance  of  individual
fluoropolymers.   Moreover, restructuring  of the industry has
significantly  changed   the  competitive   positions  of  key
suppliers.   Thus, a  timely review  of fluoropolymers here at
the beginning  of the  1990s is called for and offered in this
study.<P>


<B>RESEARCH METHODOLOGY</B><P>

The data and insights offered in this study were gathered from
various sources.   Information  was  initially  gathered  from
suppliers' literature  to  ensure  that  their  products  were
properly represented  in terms  of tradenames,  properties and
processing parameters,  and suggested  or actual applications.
Further correspondence  and telephone conversations with major
fluoropolymer suppliers sorted out any lingering discrepancies
from the trade literature.<P>

A thorough search of the trade literature was the next step in
the information  gathering process.   Sources  included  trade
magazines, U.S.  government and  trade association data, and a
variety of  contacts within  the  industry  developed  by  the
author over twenty years in the industry.<P>

Following the  development of  preliminary  market  estimates,
"fine-tuning"  of   the  numbers  generated  was  accomplished
through consultations  with major fluoropolymer suppliers which
included the  following:   Allied-Signal, Atochem,  Ausimont,
Daikin America,  Dow Corning, DuPont, Ethyl, General Electric,
Halocarbon Properties,  Hoechst-Celanese, ICI  America,  Solvay
Polymers and The 3M Company.<P>

Beyond current  and likely future market estimates, the issues
addressed with  the officials  from these  companies  included
major driving forces in this segment of the plastics industry,
trade practices,  industry realignments,  emerging  competitive
strategies, etc.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY</B><P>

Companies   already    in,    contemplating    entering,    or
directly/indirectly affected  by developments  in the  broadly
defined  fluoropolymers   business  will   benefit  from  this
comprehensive competitive analysis insofar as it addresses the
following key issues:<P>

<MENU> -   the global nature of this business<P>
  -   the ease of entry into this business<P>
  -   why several  key  fluoropolymers  still  have  only  one
supplier<P>
  -   why end-use applications drive most of these materials<P>
  -   how environmental  pressures  can  foster,  rather  than
      impede, the growth of selected fluoropolymers<P>
  -  why joint ventures and licensing arrangements will
     continue as a vital part of this business<P>
  -  how recent acquisitions have caused some restructuring of
     leading producers/suppliers<P>
  -  the effect of an additional domestic supplier with an
     offshore resin production facility<P>
  -  the possibility of developing other fluorine-based
systems.</MENU><P>


<B>OTHER RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>

BCC has published several studies that touched directed on the
role of  fluoroplastics  as  high-performance  materials.    A
selection of these studies is as follows:<P>

<MENU> GB-148  Connector Materials (11/91)<BR>
