<HEAD><TITLE> P-129  PLASTICS IN MEDICAL TUBING
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2> P-129  PLASTICS IN MEDICAL TUBING </H2>
<HR><P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B>


<P>One of the fastest growing sets of opportunities for plastics is in
the manufacturing of medical devices.  Once dominated by traditional
materials such as glass, carbon and stainless steel, rubber et al.,
the manufacturing of medical devices has benefitted from quantum leaps
in productivity stemming from the commercial availability and medical
industry acceptance of a wide range of plastics that can be processed
into molded and extruded parts, film and sheet.</P>

<P>The materials used in flexible medical tubing have to satisfy a wide
range of performance and processing criteria - perhaps the widest of
any application where plastics are currently specified, inside or
outside of the medical device business.  First and foremost, they must
be flexible, durable and strong with a low coefficient of friction to
withstand fluid flow pressures and to facilitate flow.  They must be
highly resistant to chemicals and to temperature variations, not only
to satisfy end-use requirements, but also to tolerate the conditions
encountered in various sterilization methods.  They must be
biocompatible and inert in contact with blood, tissue and other body
fluids/matter.  Transparency is at times convenient and at other times
vital in order to monitor visually or electronically the flow of
contents through the tube.  And in the final analysis all these
properties must be delivered cost-effectively in standard extrusion
or co-extrusion processing equipment.</P>

<P>The dominant material in flexible medical tubing since the 1940s when
plastics first began to replace the natural rubber and natural rubber
latex is flexibilized polyvinyl chloride (PVC).  In fact, PVC is
commonly specified for other medical device components such as bags,
trays and rigid molded parts.  PVC has the multiple
advantages of low raw material cost, good processability in
conventional extrusion equipment operated by medical device OEMs and
custom plastic part suppliers, durability across a wide range of
durometer values, water-white transparency in thin- or thick-wall
tubing, and relative bio-inertness.  However, PVC has one drawback
from the standpoint of medical tubing performance parameters - namely,
the presence of leachable plasticizers and other compounding additives
for enhanced performance or processability that can compromise its
reaction with blood, tissue and other critical medical/pharmaceutical
fluids and matter.</P>

<P>This performance limitation applying to PVC has attracted other resin
manufacturers and compounders into the burgeoning flexible medical
tubing business - first polyethylene, then nylon, polyurethane,
thermoplastic (styrene-, propylene- and urethane-based) elastomers,
and even the high-performance specialty resins such as silicone and
fluoropolymers.  Each of these resins brings particular advantages to
the flexible medical tubing marketplace in one or more applications,
but they also have their own peculiar limitations in either
performance, raw material and/or processing cost terms.  Thus, the
search continues to this day to develop new plastic materials or
variations of existing ones to either replace the current industry
standard, PVC, in the high-volume tubing applications or to capture
niches where the mid- and high-performance resin
manufacturers/compounders have set their sights.</P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B>

<P>In this report we offer the results of a detailed survey of key
players along the chain of flexible plastic medical tubing
manufacturing - that is, the resin manufacturers and compounders
active in the field of medical grade plastics for tubing, additive
manufacturers, medical tubing extruders and distributors, and medical
device manufacturers that incorporate tubing into their units.  From
the resin manufacturers and compounders we elicited information on the
grades that they currently offer for medical tubing, the prices of
these grades, the target applications for these grades, and their
sense of evolving plastic material preferences in the various tubing
applications.  From the extruders and medical device OEMs we elicited
information on the current and likely volume of business in plastic
medical tubing by major application, the evolving
economic/environmental imperatives impacting on plastic material
decision-making, and their sense of the materials that will either
gain or lose market share in medical tubing over the coming years.</P>

<B>METHODOLOGY OF THE STUDY</B>

<P>Beyond our direct telephone consultations with over 50 companies on
the supply chain of plastic flexible medical tubing, we surveyed the
relevant plastics and medical industry literature to refine our
understanding of the key issues at play in this market.  We also
consulted with key officials in U.S. regulatory agencies to obtain
copies of past or pending legislation or guidelines with direct or
indirect implications for material decision-making in flexible medical
tubing.</P>

<B>OTHER RELATED BCC STUDIES</B>

<P>BCC has covered the field of plastic medical tubing as part of other
multiclient and single-client studies with a similar or broader
research remit.  Some of our more recent multiclient studies in this
connection are the following:</P>

<UL>
     <LI>"Plastics in Non-Packaging Medical Applications" (March 1990)
     <LI>"Hose and Tubing Markets" (July 1990)
</UL>
 


