<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-131 THE CHALLENGING THERMOPLASTICS POLYESTER BUSINESS</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-131 THE CHALLENGING THERMOPLASTICS POLYESTER BUSINESS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>HOWARD KIBBEL</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>OBJECTIVES OF THE STUDY</B><P>

The plastic  resins industry  has reached  the mature stage of
its commercialization.   No  longer do  plastics grow  at  the
annual double-digit  rates seen  in  the  development  stages.
From 1946  to 1971,  the plastics  industry  experienced  13.5
percent average  annual growth  .  From 1971 to 1996, however,
annual growth  will have  been about 5-6 percent.  In a future
scenario which  will see  annual plastics  growth at less than
four percent,  the thermoplastic  polyesters as  a  group  are
expected to  experience six  to seven  percent annual  growth.
This study examines the reasons for this above-average growth,
examines the  implications for  the  plastics  industry  as  a
whole, and  the critical  participants  in  the  thermoplastic
polyester business.<P>

Thermoplastic polyesters  serve three separate functions--they
are used  as   packaging materials,  engineering  resins,  and
performance polymers.   Their successful penetration into each
of  these  segments  is  based  on  different  criteria.    In
packaging, for  example, competition  between  PET  and  other
thermoplastics (and  non-plastics) involves  issues of barrier
properties, microwaveability,  sterilizability, recyclability,
and cost.<P>

Engineering applications  require a  balance between  cost and
performance.    Mechanical,  thermal,  electrical,  and  other
physical properties  determine which  polymer will be selected
(assuming the  cost is  not prohibitive).  But, in performance
polymer applications  the cost/performance  balance is shifted
toward performance.   In  such applications  the ability  of a
material to  perform better  than its  competition  in  severe
environments supersedes the extra cost required.<P>

This study  attempts to identify the circumstances under which
market  penetration  is  justified  and  how  successful  that
penetration has been and will be in the future.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT OF THE STUDY</B><P>

This study  views the  family of thermoplastic polyesters from
every  phase   of  their   production  through  their  use  in
"engineering-type"  applications   such   as   transportation,
electrical/electronics, industrial,  and  appliances,  and  in
packaging, PET's  major outlet.   It  answers the questions of
what polymers  are being  used, in  which markets, how much is
consumed, and  why particular  polymers are  used or not used.
Intermaterial  competition  is  evaluated  in  three  ways  --
comparisons of one supplier's grades versus another within the
same polymer  type, comparisons  within a  polymer group (e.g.
engineering resins, performance polymers) of the thermoplastic
polyesters versus  similar thermoplastics, and the competition
between the thermoplastic polyesters and non-plastics.<P>

As with  all aspects  of the plastics industry, any evaluation
of competitive  performance characteristics  must include cost
comparisons. The  chemistry for  preparation from  monomer  to
polymer is  described for  each polymer with an explanation as
to how  feedstock prices  affect the  ultimate price  of these
polymers and,  in turn,  how pricing  might  favor  or  hinder
market penetration.   Cost  data include price per unit volume
as well  as for  price per  unit  weight  to  present  a  fair
competitive scenario.<P>

The companies  who participate  in the thermoplastic polyester
business  generally   specialize  in  engineering  resins  and
performance polymers.   This  study profiles their activity in
the United  States but  includes a discussion of their foreign
relationships which  impact on  the ability  to  market  these
polymers globally.    The  profiles  of  the  resin  suppliers
include market  shares within  each polymer  type, capacities,
and grade  offerings.   The study  discusses the  impact  from
those  companies   on  the   periphery  of  the  thermoplastic
polyester business,  such as feedstock suppliers, compounders,
processors, and recyclers.<P>

The quantitative data supplied for the various polymers relate
to a  base year  (1991) and  a medium-term  future year (1996)
with average annual growth rates calculated for that five-year
period.   Data for 1989 and 1990 are shown to establish trends
prior to the forecast period.<P>


<B>STUDY METHODOLOGY</B><P>

In addition  to telephone  conversations with  the major resin
suppliers and  compounders, our  research included the product
literature  offered   by  those   companies,  government  data
publications, industry  conferences, and  trade  publications.
The current  and forecast  demand data  provided represents  a
consensus from  among the resin suppliers.  The discussions of
trends  and   outlook  are  based  on  our  conclusions  after
comparing the suppliers' objectives with market needs.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

This study  is intended  for use  by existing  resin and  film
suppliers, as  well as  by companies who process, compound, or
recycle thermoplastic polyesters.  It can be used by those who
wish to  determine the  opportunities and  growth prospects in
the  several   market  segments  in  which  the  thermoplastic
polyesters  participate.    Insights  into  new  technological
developments indicate  how existing  markets can be penetrated
and how  new markets will be opened where these materials have
been previously excluded.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>

This analysis of the thermoplastic polyesters is the latest in
a  series  of  studies  reviewing  the  polymers  and  related
materials which  comprise the U.S. plastics industry.  The BCC
studies shown  below may  be of  interest to companies who are
following the growth of thermoplastics and thermosets, and the
interpolymer competition  that is  inherent  to  the  plastics
industry.<P>

