<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-132  TECHNOLOGY OF PLASTIC WASTE RECYCLING
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-132  TECHNOLOGY OF PLASTIC WASTE RECYCLING</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>FRANK RENAUD</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY OBJECTIVES</B><P>

In a previous report, we analyzed in detail the prospects for the
recycling of post-consumer plastic waste during the 1990s.  We
found that the production of recycled resin could quadruple over
the coming 10 years.  In this report, we follow up by asking two
questions: (a) do we have the technological know-how to meet this
forecasted level of output? and (b) which equipment manufacturers
will benefit most from this development?<P>


This report has therefore two objectives.  First, it looks at the
technological aspects of such crucial steps as the collection of
plastic material, the sorting technologies required, the prospects
for the continued success of the mechanical and thermal
technologies as well as for the various chemical technologies now
on the drawing boards.  It analyzes the technological problems
associated with the manufacturing of products made of recycled
resins.  Throughout, the report also seeks to forecast the growth
in the sales of equipment needed over the coming decade.  Second,
the report also peers into the future and provides insights into
the forthcoming generation of promising new technologies and
equipment aimed at removing some of the obstacles now besetting the
recycling of post-consumer thermoplastic waste.<P>


The report, therefore, takes a critical look at the wide range of
recycling technologies and equipment now available to recyclers and
at the rate of growth in the sales of equipment.  It seeks to
identify the technologies that will be capable of sustaining the
forecasted growth of the post-consumer recycling business over the
coming decade.  We believe that today's dedicated recycling
technology is still in its infancy and that the expected
developments within the next few years will be a boon to the
recycling industry as well as to the equipment manufacturers.<P>



<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>


In a previous report (BCC report #P-125, The Secondary Recycling
Plastics Business), we concluded that in 1990, the industry
recycled 1.1 billion pounds of post-consumer plastic waste.  That
represented 2.9 per cent of the total volume of plastic waste
available for recycling that year.  We also noted that most of the
activity, so far, has focused on the recycling of plastic packaging
material, especially milk and soft-drink bottles.  However, the
latter group makes up less than half of the total stock of
recyclable material.  The industry has yet to make a dent in
recycling the even larger volume of durable goods such as plastic
household appliances, toys, pipes and other non-packaging products.
Our forecast calls for a rapid increase in the volume of such
recyclable material during the 1990s.<P>


We also noted in that report that the technology available to
recycle post-consumer plastic waste was in its infancy.  Very
little has been done to develop and market machinery and equipment
unique to the recycling of post-consumer waste.  Recyclers now use
mostly "virgin resin machinery" adapted, in an ad hoc fashion, to
their needs.  Recycling technologies, together with inadequate
equipment and machinery, were identified as obstacles holding back
more rapid developments of recycling efforts.<P>


In this report, we focus on the collection, the sorting and the
mechanical/thermal and chemical recycling processes.  We analyze
not only the type of equipment available for each of those key
steps but also their growth in sales.  We look into the critical
collection and sorting equipment now in use.  We examine the types
of equipment available for the granulation, shredding, extrusion
and pelletizing steps.  We look at the impact the increased
production of recycled resins will have on the sales of virgin
resins.  We also analyze the roles played by additives and the
properties of finished recycled products themselves.  We provide
some insights into the numerous emerging chemical recycling
processes.<P>


By taking a closer look at each stage of the recycling process, we
are in a better position to understand the limits of post-consumer
waste recycling efforts and the opportunities that will open up for
equipment manufacturers.  By reporting on the research being done,
we can better assess the outlook for plastics recycling over the
next 10 years.<P>


There are at least two other reasons for focusing on the equipment
and technological aspects of post-consumer plastic recycling now.
First, the plastics industry is under intense pressure to increase
its recycling rate of not only plastic packaging but of all plastic
products.  Unless the industry widens its recycling efforts, it
will continue to lag behind other industries such as paper, glass
and aluminum.  In some instances, because some resins are under
heavy environmental pressures, recycling will also ensure the
survival and continued growth of those resins and plastic products.
In other instances, it could help shape legislative actions that
will influence the future growth of most plastic resins.<P>


Second, the development of new technologies will benefit both the
recyclers and the manufacturers of the equipment themselves.  Those
manufacturers can only benefit from a rapidly growing recycling
business.<P>



<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY</B><P>



For each of the post-consumer waste recycling steps, we analyze the
present and forthcoming technologies.  We also include a
quantitative and qualitative profile of the competition among the
equipment manufacturers.  We provide in-depth analysis of those
factors that obstruct present recycling efforts and those that
promise to unleash a more rapid growth.<P>


The study is aimed at groups and individuals within the plastics
recycling community and at the equipment manufacturers.  We believe
the information included in this report is unique.   The reader can
find, in one place, information about the present status of the
technology of plastics recycling as well as a discussion of where
that technology is heading over the next 10 years.<P>



<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>



The study is limited to the various stages related to the recycling
of thermoplastic post-consumer plastic waste.  Therefore, we look
into the all-important collection and sorting technologies that
promise a steady supply of post-consumer plastic products to
recyclers.  We discuss the role of Municipal Recovery Facilities
(MRFS) and the possible establishment of Plastics Recovery
Facilities (PRFS).  We analyze the present and forthcoming types
and sales prospects of equipment and machinery used in the
mechanical/thermal processes (granulation, extrusion, pelletizing).
We also analyze developments in and expectations for the use of
chemical processes such as glycolysis, methanolysis, refinery
recycling, etc.  We study the characteristics and properties of
products manufactured with recycled plastics.  In this instance, we
focus only on those products that "close the loop."  The latter
section also includes an analysis of the use of new additives.
Throughout, we focus on the status of present-day operations and,
for each section, we provide an outlook for expected developments.<P>



<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>



This report relies on a wide variety of sources.  We are especially
thankful to the hundreds of recyclers and equipment manufacturers
contacted.  They have been willing to share their remarkable
expertise as well as their research findings.  However, they cannot
be held responsible for the views expressed in the following pages.<P>


We have also made wide use of publicly available sources of
information.  These include journals devoted to the plastics
recycling business, the data published by various government
agencies, the Society for the Plastics Industry, the Society of
Plastics Engineers, etc.  Members of these various groups have also
shown patience and interest in this report and we are thankful for
their input.<P>



<B>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>


BCC has been actively studying plastic packaging and recycling for
more than 15 years.  It has published numerous reports in that
field and the following should be of interest to BCC clients:<P>

<UL>P-027N  -  Plastics Versus Paper and Paperboard<BR>
