<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-133 PVC AND THE ENVIRONMENT: RESIN REPLACEMENT OPPORTUNITIES
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-133 PVC AND THE ENVIRONMENT: RESIN REPLACEMENT OPPORTUNITIES</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>HOWARD KIBBEL</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>OBJECTIVES OF THE STUDY</B><P>

It is  now apparent  to everyone  in the  plastics industry  that
concern for the environment will not abate in the 1990s.  It will
grow as  we  examine  our  living  patterns  and  our  commercial
practices from  the standpoint  of the  impact on  resources  and
waste management.<P>

The EPA,  charged with  the  responsibility  of  caring  for  the
environment,  is  pursuing  a  policy  of  source  reduction  and
development/improvement  of  recycling  infrastructures  for  all
basic  materials.     Concurrently,   OSHA,  the   Department  of
Transportation, and other government regulatory agencies continue
to monitor  and improve  manufacturing practices which affect the
consumer and  worker in  terms of  safety.   It is in this era of
environmental concerns  that the  PVC industry is faced with loss
of market  share as  plastics usage  is scrutinized with the view
toward its impact on our society's well-being.<P>

This study  is concerned  with the efforts of the PVC industry to
counteract negative perceptions of its environmental-friendliness
while actively  promoting its  materials not only as contributors
to a  better standard  of living  but also as equal partners with
other polymers  in supporting  good environmental  practices.  We
will identify  and quantify  those areas where PVC does not offer
an environmental advantage vis-*-vis another polymer.<P>

The commission  of this  study was  prompted by  our initial view
that there would be dramatic changes (i.e., losses) in PVC demand
arising from consumer and processor desires to switch from PVC to
plastics or  non-plastics which  are perceived  to be  more  pro-
environment.   The main  questions to  be answered were: how much
PVC demand  would be  lost to  other materials;  which materials;
what would be the level of recyclate replacing virgin resin; and,
which companies  would be the beneficiaries and losers from these
impacts.<P>

PVC reached its level of importance in the U.S. plastics industry
because it  is the  most versatile  of all  plastics due  to  its
blending capability with plasticizers and other additives.  It is
used in  a wide  range of applications from thick, rigid pipe and
siding to  thin film  for surgical  gloves or food packaging.  In
addition, its  cost-performance characteristics  rate it  as  the
material-of-choice for  many applications.  Thus, understandably,
processors and  end-users alike  are reluctant  to shift to other
materials which  might be more expensive, would require different
equipment, and  create the need for more research and development
to satisfy the requirements of their specific products.<P>

Indeed, our  conversations with processors, compounders, and end-
users  indicate   that  they   would  discontinue   PVC  only  if
legislatively forced  to do  so.   Since we  have concluded  that
anti-PVC sentiment  will not  cause such  legislation,  the  most
likely impact  on PVC  demand for the next five years will be the
traditional market factors of cost and performance.<P>


The PVC  industry, with  nine billion pounds of demand, is second
only to  polyethylene in  terms of  importance  to  the  plastics
industry.  We will show that the impact from environmental issues
will affect  only a  small percentage of PVC markets, in terms of
lost share, during the next five years.  The environmental impact
on PVC will be more affected by changes in processing technology,
new polymer grades, and greater use of recycled material.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT OF THE STUDY</B><P>

This study  views the  PVC industry  from 1991 through 1996.  The
quantitative data  that we  offer for PVC and competing materials
in the  various markets  include domestic  demand for  the  years
1989, 1990, and a forecast for 1996.  Average annual growth rates
are calculated for the 1991-1996 period.<P>

The  scope   of  the   study  includes:  an  explanation  of  the
environmental issues  which are likely to impact on PVC; past and
pending    environment-related    legislation    involving    PVC
specifically or  the markets  in which PVC competes; and, how the
other material  industries are coping with environmental factors.
These analyses  supplement our  quantitative measurement  of  the
loss or gain by PVC due to environmental issues and the materials
which will  have resultant benefit or liability.  In addition, we
have identified  the key players at each level of PVC manufacture
and use,  together with  changes in processing technology and new
polymer grades caused by environmental pressures.<P>

The cause  for substitution  of one  material for  another is not
always clearly  explained.  We have made every effort to separate
environmental  factors  from  cost  and  performance  factors  to
develop our quantitative analyses.<P>


<B>STUDY METHODOLOGY</B><P>

In addition  to telephone  interviews with  primary players  from
each level  of PVC manufacture, we have gathered data and insight
from industry  specialists in  trade associations  and government
regulatory agencies.    These  contacts  were  supplemented  with
information obtained  from  the  technical  and  marketing  trade
literature and  supporting data from previous BCC reports.  Thus,
we  believe  this  study  represents  an  accurate  view  of  the
consensus for  the current  and forecast  degree of impact on the
various PVC markets from environment-related issues.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTIONS OF THE STUDY</B><P>

This study  is intended  for use  by  existing  resin  companies,
processors,  compounders,  and  end-users  of  PVC  resins.    In
addition, companies who specialize in recycling will gain insight
into the  developing infrastructure  and  potential  markets  for
recycled  PVC.  Companies  which  compete  against  PVC  will  be
interested in  the growth  opportunities for  their materials  as
replacements for  PVC where  environmental  considerations  cause
material selectors  to abandon  the traditional  cost-performance
factors  in  qualifying  materials.    Finally,  those  companies
considering entrance  into the  PVC business  will learn  of  the
current environmental  factors which  will alter  the anticipated
growth of PVC markets.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>

This comprehensive  analysis of  the environmental  impact on PVC
markets is an extension of the many recent multiclient reports on
polymers published  by BCC's Plastics Research Division.  We cite
the following  reports that may be of interest to companies which
are monitoring developments in the PVC industry.<P>


<UL>P-129 -  Plastics in Medical Tubing,                          10/91<BR>

P-126 -  The Environmental Impact on Plastic Packaging,        8/91<BR>

P-125  - The Secondary Recycling Plastics Business,            8/91<BR>

G-070N - Wire, Cable & Fiber Optics,                           5/91<BR>

P-2000 - World Plastics 2000: A Global Plastics Planning Guide for 1990s,     3/91<BR>
        

P-209 -  Materials For Siding, Windows and Roofing,           11/90<BR>

P-063U - The Changing Plastics Film Markets,                   7/90<BR>

P-121 -  Plastics in Non-Packaging Medical Applications,       3/90</UL><P>

