<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-136 ELECTROACTIVE POLYMERS: NEW SURGE OF INTEREST IN THE 1990s
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-136 ELECTROACTIVE POLYMERS: NEW SURGE OF INTEREST IN THE 1990s</H2>

<HR><P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

From its commercial beginnings in the late 1930s up to recent years, the fundamental
marketing strategy of the plastics industry has been to develop and refine polymeric
materials that could replace "traditional" materials - metals, wood, rubber, glass,
paper, et al. - in existing, high-volume and/or high-value applications.  By the 1960s
there were transparent plastics such as polycarbonate and polymethyl methacrylate
to compete against glass, engineering grades of thermoplastics and thermosets to
compete against wood, thermoplastic and thermosetting elastomers to compete against
rubber, and so on.<P>

Whereas there are also advanced composites with high-modulus fibers available to
compete against the great strength of steel, the one characteristic of steel and other
metals that has consistently eluded polymer scientists is electrical conductivity.  Thus,
until recently, the route to mimicking the conductivity of metals (particularly copper
and steel) was to either compound into the inherently insulative resin a conductive
filler (e.g., metal or carbon powder or fiber), coat the plastic film or part with a
conductive metal solution, or simply bond the plastic film or part to a conductive
metal substrate.  This did achieve a measure of conductivity, but there were generally
compromises in terms of processability or performance or total part economics.<P>

Thus, the search for "inherently conductive" polymers commenced in earnest in
corporate, academic and government-supported research laboratories around the world
- in the U.S., Europe and Japan, in particular.  And in the 1950s and 1960s, as the
implications of the microelectronics revolution became apparent to all, the search for
such materials accelerated further, taking on the trappings of the search for the Holy
Grail.<P>

In the mid-1970s, quite by accident, the first polymer capable of conducting
electricity - polyacetylene - was discovered at the University of Pennsylvania.  The
announcement of this discovery quickly reverberated around the polymer science
community, and the intensity of the search for others magnified dramatically.  By
1984-1985 the number of patents issued in the field of electrically conductive polymers
had shot up, and by 1987 the first application - a polymer electrode in a miniature
("button") battery - was registered.<P>

Here in the early 1990s the commercialization of electrically conductive polymers is
still in its infancy.  Production of these materials has been scaled up from grams to
pounds, but overall global production and consumption totals are still negligible.
However, just as there was an air of inevitability to the success of conventional
insulative plastics (polyolefins, nylon, epoxy, et al.) in the 1940s, there is a similar
air - indeed, a conviction - of inevitability to the success of these new conductive
polymers in the 1990s and beyond.  No one is yet predicting billions of pounds of sales
by the year 2000.  But in the early years and decades of the 21st century, the
processes and the products in a host of vital industries:<P>

<UL>             -   aircraft/aerospace<BR>
             -   automobiles<BR>
             -   biotechnology<BR>
             -   chemical processing<BR>
             -   electrical/electronic equipment<BR>
             -   military hardware</UL><P>

will be completely transformed by the integration of these conductive polymers into
an ever-widening menu of materials.<P>

U.S. and global manufacturers and their material/part suppliers have always faced a
choice between the known and the unknown in materials decision-making.  The
companies that are willing to plumb the unknown and learn to enhance their total
processing/performance spectrum will enter the next century as vital competitors in
the evolving global marketplace for products and services.  Those that don't will soon
face technological obsolescence and disappear.  This certainly applies all along the
product/service supply chain in the industries cited above and others as well.<P>

The companies that succeed in developing and marketing electrically conductive
polymers and other novel molecular transformations will be those driven by "patient
money."  These are hardly materials that offer quick rewards "going right down to the
bottom line."  Rather, this is a field where careful, time-consuming and very often
cooperative research will eventually be rewarded with applications beyond any
contemporary crystal ball-gazing.  And in our research we have identified many
companies - in North America, Europe and Asia - determined to participate in those
applications in the future with materials currently dubbed "exotic."<P>

<B>SCOPE OF THE REPORT</B><P>

Since the initial wave of patents relating to material composition and method of
preparation of the various electrically conductive polymers began in the early 1980s,
there have been numerous symposia and seminars devoted to these topics.  The
plastics trade literature has also covered these novel materials, speculating on likely
future applications.  Thus, there is a rich and growing database on the nature of these
materials.<P>

What remains to be offered is a comprehensive and candid assessment of the practical
dynamics of introducing these novel materials into existing applications and markets
and a quantification of the volume and value of business likely to be generated.  This,
then, is our remit in this report.<P>

The scope of this report, therefore, is basically threefold.  First, we offer summary
descriptions of the dozen or so most promising polymers and polymer blends offering
high conductivity (i.e., low volume and surface resistivities) when modified (doped).
Then we provide an in-depth assessment of the leading players on both the supply and
the demand side of the electrically conductive polymers equation.  Thirdly, we provide
a realistic chronology for the penetration of these materials into the target
applications and markets to arrive at consumption volume and value of sales estimates
from 1992 through 2000 out to the year 2010.<P>

<B>METHODOLOGY OF THE REPORT</B><P>

Our research program proceeded along three tracks - namely,<P>

<UL> -  a thorough review of the patents in the field of electrically
conductive polymers<P>
-  a similarly thorough review of the plastics and chemicals
 industries' trade literature and conference proceedings<P>
-  telephone interviews with officials at key university and
government research laboratories, as well as companies
interested in the actual/potential supply/use of these and
related materials.</UL><P>

From earlier BCC research in this field, we already had a U.S. patent database
covering the period 1970-1985.  We supplemented this with a new search of the U.S.
patents assigned over the period 1985-1991.  This allowed us to chronicle the advance
of this research work and commercial inroads from the very beginning up to the
present date.  It also allowed us to identify the changing cast of key players in this
field over the past 20 years.<P>

We also reviewed articles and papers on these polymers and related issues (processing
and performance) over recent years (1988-1991).  We followed this up by contacting
officials at over 70 U.S. and foreign companies, universities and government agencies,
which have been or are still actively pursuing opportunities in this field.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE REPORT</B><P>

This report is designed to provide a cost-effective set of data and insights to
companies either already in or contemplating entering the field of electrically
conductive polymers.  The data that we provide as of 1991-1992 are accurate and
verifiable to the maximum extent possible, and the projections of future material
production and consumption are not "wild-eyed," but rather realistic, based on the
assessments of companies with existing commitments.  For companies already in this
field, we attempt to point out possibly profitable alliances of a research or marketing
nature.  For companies contemplating entry, we set out as precisely as possible the
costs of entry and some attractive candidates for acquisition.<P>

Ultimately, our intention is to provide a clear, candid assessment of these evolving
materials and technologies to companies planning to make commitments in this
business today and out to the year 2000.<P>


<B>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>

BCC has already researched and published many reports touching upon electrically
conductive polymers and their actual/potential markets.  For example, we have
covered the field of electrically conductive polymers on their own in earlier reports
(1983 and 1988).  We have also covered these materials as part of a total spectrum of
materials in the recent reports listed below.<P>

<UL> C-112  -   Membrane Trends for the 1990s<BR>
   G-070N -   Growth Opportunities in Wire, Cable & Fiber Optics<BR>
   G-072R -   Electronic Display Materials and Devices<BR>
   G-076R -   Electronic Sensors:  Markets, Direction, Technologies<BR>
   GB-066N -  Plastics EMI Shielding<BR>
   GB-073R -  Fiber Optics Materials:  Changing Technologies & Opportunities<BR>
 GB-086R  -   The U.S. Battery Industry<BR>
