<CENTER><H2>P-139  ENVIRONMENTALLY IMPACTED PLASTICS ADDITIVES:
WINNERS AND LOSERS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>HOWARD KIBBEL</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>OBJECTIVES OF THE STUDY</B><P>

The environmental issues which face the plastics resins industry are becoming a major
influence in the way resins are produced and marketed.  Of no less concern is the
impact on the materials which are added to resins to improve their property
performance, processability, and final cost.  In the 1990s, a fourth function has been
added for these materials--an ability to promote the pro-environmental qualities of
polymers.<P>

This study identifies and quantifies the effect of those additives which will have the
greatest contribution in satisfying polymer suppliers' efforts to maintain market share
while under environmental pressures.  As with any case of a change in the status quo,
there will be "winners and losers."  Thus, the study will review and analyze the
materials and their suppliers which are at risk from material substitution and those
which will be the beneficiaries of that substitution.<P>

In addition, the demand for several of these additives will be affected in terms of
increased or decreased use, as in recycling where greater loading levels will be needed
to process recycled resins in some cases or less/no additive will be needed since they
already exist in the recycled material.  This study will separate those instances where
environmental factors rather than cost and performance factors have led to changes
in demand.<P>



<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT OF THE STUDY</B><P>

This study distinguishes between those additives whose demand will be significantly
impacted by environmental issues and those   we discovered had little or no
environmental pressures. Of the twenty-eight additive categories we identified for
potential analysis, nine are reviewed in depth--flame retardants, foaming agents,
stabilizers, plasticizers, colorants, compatibilizers, coupling agents, impact modifiers,
and degradability additives.  The biocides, polyurethane catalysts, and mold release
agents, having only moderate environmental impact are discussed qualitatively, and
the remaining additives were excluded for lack of relevance.  Among the latter are
antiblocking agents, antioxidants, organic peroxides, polyester initiators, antifogging
agents, antistats, crosslinking agents, curing agents, deodorants/odorants, emulsifiers,
low-profile additives, lubricants, processing aids, slip agents, surfactants, thickening
agents, UV stabilizers, and viscosity depressants.<P>

The study views plastics additives from the current (1992) time through the next ten
years.  All quantitative data shown for additives demand and other materials are
keyed to 1991, 1992, 1997, and 2002.  Average annual growth rates are calculated for
the 5-year 1992-1997 and 1997-2002 periods.<P>

The scope of the study includes: a discussion of the environmental issues which affect
the use of additives; past and pending legislation which specifically restricts the use
of polymer compounds; similar regulatory issues; the role of additives as contributors
to plastics' pro-environment characteristics; and the impact on additive demand from
environmental issues.  In addition, we have identified the major players who supply
the various additives and the compounders/processors which, along with the resin
suppliers, are the major users of additives.<P>



<B>STUDY METHODOLOGY</B><P>

In addition to telephone interviews with the major players in additive production and
use, we have gathered data and insight from trade associations and government
agencies.  These contacts have been supplemented with information obtained from the
technical and marketing trade literature and relevant data from previous BCC studies.<P>


All BCC estimates of future demand, both with and without environmental impact,
are based on our interpretation of the information received from an extensive list of
industry specialists.  Thus, we believe this study represents an accurate view of the
current and forecast impact on plastics additives from environmentally-related issues.<P>



<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

The plastics additives industry consumes more than 11 billion pounds of material,
accounting for 15 percent of the total weight of plastic compounds consumed annually.
It is a one billion dollar industry involving more than 900 companies.  While
replacement of heavy metals in pigments and vinyl stabilizers and removal of halogens
from flame retardants have already been initiated to meet environmental standards,
the role of additives in facilitating recycling will provide a major boost in future
additive demand.  Consequently, their position as a major factor in plastics warrants
an analysis on the extent of environmental impact.<P>

This study is intended for use by existing resin suppliers, additive suppliers,
compounders, processors and recyclers, with an interest in evaluating how the
environmental pressures on additive use will affect their businesses.  Our
comprehensive analyses show  which additives are likely to lose market share and
those which will be the beneficiaries of those losses.  The conclusions drawn from
these analyses can aid companies in developing new additive systems and guide those
companies considering entrance into additive markets as to where the areas of growth
and decline will occur.<P>



<B>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>

There are several recent BCC studies which have addressed portions of this study,
relating to additive consumption and/or environmental issues impacting the plastics
industry.  Listed below are such studies which may be of value in supplementing the
reader's interest on these subjects.<P>

<UL>P-131   PVC and the Environment                               5/92<P>

P-126   The Environmental Impact on Plastic Packaging         9/91<P>

P-124   New Olefin Resins Via New Polymerization &   Compounding Technologies                                5/91<P>

