<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-141  PLASTIC DURABLES:
ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-141  PLASTIC DURABLES: ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>FRANK RENAUD</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The goal of this report is to provide a detailed and comprehensive
multi-client study of the U.S. market for clean coal technologies,
products, and systems and potential business opportunities.  The
objectives include a thorough coverage of the underlying social,
political, economic, energy, and environmental issues driving the
clean coal technology and air pollution control business, as well
as assessments of new and potential products and systems.  Another
important objective is to provide realistic market data and
forecasts for low-sulfur coal, related air pollution control
equipment, instrumentation, and related chemical technologies.<P>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

The main reason for doing this study is that during the past five
years there has been a growing concern about the environment in the
United States.  This has manifested itself in the emergence of
Green political initiatives and an expanding number of
environmental standards, air emission targets, and regulations.
For the clean coal technology business, the most important has been
the passage into law of the Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990.
Recent directions in the legislative and regulatory arena indicate
that environmental pressures -- despite the recession -- remain
important to the public and legislators.   In addition, it is
assumed that these pressures will intensify in the years to come,
engendering further changes in the clean coal technology business.<P>

<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The clean coal technology industry is not a precisely defined
sector and has not yet been assigned in any of the major economic
classification codes or activities.  Indeed, even air pollution
control and environmental protection does not fit any one standard
definition or classification.  Air pollution control is usually
defined as including the suppliers of equipment, technologies,
products, and services which monitor, prevent, and limit damage to
air quality.  Clean coal technology would deal with those
technologies, products, and services that monitor, prevent, and
limit damage to air quality arising from the burning of coal.  This
is the definition of the industry used in this report which
includes "end-of-pipe" air pollution control equipment,
instrumentation and monitoring equipment, low-sulfur coal, and
chemical products used in coal desulfurization and denitrification.<P>

Basically, the scope of the report is limited to those goods which
monitor, prevent, and limit damage from air pollution arising from
combustion of coal  at stationary sources such as electric power
generation plants and industrial facilities.  The scope of the
report does not include the cost of ancillary equipment and
components (piping, wire and cable, electrical devices, etc.),
construction-related costs (field erection and construction labor,
concrete foundations, sitework, etc.), and general engineering and
environmental services.  Many of these technologies and chemicals
can be used to treat flue gases arising from the combustion of
other fossil fuels.  To the furthest extent possible, revenues
associated with technologies to reduce sulfur dioxide and nitrous
oxide emissions from these other fossil fuels are not included
within the scope of this report.<P>

As the number of environmental issues of major concern increase,
the definition proposed by some industry observers has been
broadened to include the supply of energy-efficient equipment,
which contribute to reducing greenhouse gas and other emissions. This report does not include this type of equipment because to a
certain extent the substitutionary adoption of such technologies
may be motivated by financial incentives rather than environmental
policy initiatives.  In addition, the report does not include
advanced clean coal technologies such as fluidized bed combustion
(FBC), pressurized fluidized bed combustion, (PFBC) integrated
gasification combined-cycle (IGCC), and other advanced coal
conversion/-combustion technologies.  The report also does not
include chemicals used in traditional coal preparation processes
(wet-washing, froth flotation, etc.).<P>

Within the report some duplication does exist.  Revenue estimates
of catalysts used in selective catalyst reduction (SCR) systems are
presented in the section dealing with chemicals.  The reported
revenues include catalysts used for both the initial "charging" of
these systems and replacement demand.  In the section dealing with
SCR systems, the revenue estimates of the SCR systems reflect their
net sales value, about 60-70% the value of which is
catalysts.  This duplication is taken care of in the summary by
removing the value of catalysts -- about $25 million in 1993 --
from the total.<P>

The scope of this report is comprehensive, covering the present
status of and future prospects for clean coal technologies in the
United States.  It covers the many issues concerning the merits and
future prospects of the clean coal technology business, including
low-sulfur coal, technologies and equipment  for sulfur dioxide and
nitrous oxide removal, ESP upgrades, boiler modifications,
instrumentation and monitoring, and related chemical products.  It
also covers in detail the socio-political, economic, energy, and
environmental issues that so many regard as critical to the
industry's current state of change.<P>

The report provides a review of the clean coal technology industry, its structure and the many companies involved in supplying these goods.   The competitive position of the main players in the market and the strategic options they face are also discussed, as well as such competitive factors as marketing, technical services, distribution, and
operations.  The report also looks at the varieties of basic
research, product development, and commercialization that are being
conducted in the area of clean coal technology.<P>

The value of revenues for clean coal technology products -- in
million of U.S. dollars -- represents the value of the products
sold.  This value reflects the net sales price, f.o.b. plant or
mine, to the customer, net of discounts, allowances, and freight
charges.  As used in this study, the term revenues is equivalent
to, and used interchangeably with, the terms demand and sales.
During the discussion of the individual market segments, revenues
are related to indicators in the tables which are  used for
comparative purposes.  They do not imply that the indicator used
(e.g. electric utilities' new plant and equipment expenditures)
represents the sole market for that product.<P>

All growth rates mentioned in the tables and in the text are based
on the average annual rate of growth from 1993 through 1998 or from
1998 to the year 2003.  The compounding method of calculating
growth rates is used.  Because current dollar measures are used,
these growth rates thus reflect the growth in volume or real growth
and the growth including the effects of price changes and changes
in product mix.  The effects of inflation are  eliminated by
including unit sales data or by the use of price indexes to provide
measures of real growth.<P>

<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

This study provides the most complete accounting of ongoing clean
coal technology developments in the United States currently
available in a multi-client format.  It provides the most thorough
and up-to-date assessment that can be found anywhere on the
subject.  The study also provides extensive quantification of the
many important facets of the market developments in the United
States for clean coal technologies, products, equipment, and
systems.  This, in turn, contributes to the determination of what
kind of strategic response companies may adopt in order to compete
in this dynamic market.<P>

<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Initially, a comprehensive and exhaustive search of the literature
on clean coal technology was conducted.  These secondary sources
included technical journals, technical books, marketing literature,
other product/promotional literature, annual reports, security
analyst reports, and other publications.  In addition, there were
formal and informal interviews with coal producers, electric
utilities, air pollution control equipment producers,
instrumentation producers, suppliers of environmental services,
technical experts, government officials, trade association
officials, and personnel of the companies themselves.<P>

<B>RELATED BCC CREDENTIALS</B><P>

Founded in 1971, Business Communications Co., Inc. (BCC) is known
throughout the world for its technical-economic reports and
services.  The company has studied major market, economic,
environmental, and technological developments that have
characterized industry during the past two decades to produce
reports, newsletters, and conferences.  In the process, BCC has
focused on advanced materials, high-technology systems and
components, and novel processing methods, since the development and
marketing of these phenomena assert a profound influence on
manufacturers and users on a worldwide scale.<P>

BCC clients include almost every major corporation in the U.S., Canada,
Western Europe, and Japan.  Of related interest to the subject of
air pollution control are such BCC reports as:  Air Pollution
Control Techniques, Equipment, and Services in Europe; Air
Pollution and the Market for Monitors and Sensors; Hazardous Waste
Control; Environmental Services for Indoor Air Pollution; Electric
Utilities:  New Directions; The U.S. Energy Future: Environmental/Social Costs Quantified;  Waste-to-Energy:  Impact, Directions and Trends; Catalysts for Organic Synthesis; Zeolites: Markets and Opportunities; Advanced Waste Management Technology; Chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs); Solvent Recycling, Disposal and Substitution; Environmentally Acceptable Coatings:  The Industry;
and Environmentally Acceptable Soldering & Cleaning Materials and
Systems in Electronics.  The company has also conducted reports on
a wide variety of water treatment, hazardous waste, membrane
technology, plastics packaging, solid waste, recycling, and energy
issues.<P>
BCC also publishes the monthly newsletters Waste
Treatment Technology News, Atmospheric Pollution & Abatement News,
Energy, and Energy Conservation News.<P>

