<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-142  THE EVOLVING MARKET FOR CAULKS AND SEALANTS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-142  THE EVOLVING MARKET FOR CAULKS AND SEALANTS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>MELVIN SCHLECTER</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The objective of this report is to provide a basic understanding and
independent investigation of the chemical products, applications, technology,
and competitive scenario of the caulk/ sealant market.<P>

Included in this assessment will be credible market estimates and forecasts
along with key factors which will impact the market.  The replacement of
lower-performance materials by higher-performance versions will be
highlighted.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

Primary reasons for undertaking this study are to reassess a large specialty
chemical market which has been undergoing difficult times and to present a
reasonable future outlook.  Many of the companies in caulks/sealants are also
involved in adhesives as well.<P>


<B>SCOPE & FORMAT</B><P>

The definition of a sealant in Hawley's Condensed Chemical Dictionary reads as
follows:  "any organic substance that is soft enough to pour or extrude and is
capable of subsequent hardening to form a permanent bond with a substrate."
There is no definition of "caulk" in almost any chemical dictionary, and the
reader is referred to "sealants."<P>

For this report, a sealant is defined as any material used to fill a void and
prevent passage of liquids, solids, or gases between two substrates.  This
definition includes caulks, preformed, non-cured, and partially cured
materials.  Surface coatings such as paints and roofing materials are excluded
from this definition.<P>

All caulks are sealants, but not all sealants are caulks.  The term "caulk"
was first used to describe materials such as hemp fibers impregnated with tar
or pitch (oakum), or putty - a mixture of chalk with linseed oil.  Development
of synthetic polymers along with subsequent formulation technologies led to
the term "sealant," a term now used collectively for caulks and newer
formulated materials based on these synthetic polymers. Most products
considered as caulks or sealants are pourable (able to be applied with a
special gun-like apparatus) and also termed "gunnable."  Most homeowners
readily recognize the caulking gun.<P>

To simplify reading of this report, caulks and sealants will be referred to as
"caulks/sealants" for the remainder of the report.<P>

This report includes only form-in-place gaskets and pre-formed gaskets
designed for weather stripping applications.  Examples are silicone formed-in-
place gaskets used by the auto industry (oil pan and axle hub sealing) and
polyurethane or PVC foam for weather stripping.  Faucet washers, O-rings, and
after-market oil pan gaskets, etc., are excluded.<P>

There are several other polymer-based materials that are excluded because
their primary function is more of a cementing (adhesive) than sealing
function.  These include the following:<P>

<UL>--- epoxies ... used as in situ polymerized materials in adhesives, flooring,
protective coatings, and laminates<P>

--- phenolics ... two-package systems of silica or carbon fillers containing
an acid setting agent (p-toluene sulfonic acid) and an A-stage phenolic resin<P>

--- unsaturated polyesters ... fibrous glass-reinforced unsaturated polyesters
often filled with silica or calcium carbonate used as plastic cements in sewer
pipe and in plastic concrete<P>

--- urea resins ... kaolin-filled urea-formaldehyde resins used to seal cracks
in underground irrigation pipes<P>

--- furan resins ... two-package resin cements used extensively as mortars,
and grouts for brick and tile</UL><P>

It is also important to clarify the difference between adhesives and
caulks/sealants, especially since they are often produced and marketed by the
same company.<P>

An adhesive, as defined by Hawley's Condensed Chemical Dictionary is "any
substance, inorganic or organic, natural or synthetic, that is capable of
bonding other substances together by surface attachment."<P>

Many adhesives also function, in a secondary manner, as a caulk/ sealant in that a void is filled between the substrates thus preventing the passage of gases, liquids, or solids.  Similarly, some caulks/sealants have substantial adhesive properties ("tack"), and serve to hold two substrates together.  As technologies advance caulks/sealants are being formulated with epoxies to improve their adhesive qualities.<P>

The determinant of whether a product is a caulk/sealant or an adhesive in this
report is the product's primary intended use often a subjective judgment since
suppliers often claim dual functionality for their caulk/sealant and adhesive
products. Truthfully, it is often difficult to differentiate since the product
adequately performs both functions - one example will suffice.<P>

In structural glazing - a construction process where glass panels in high rise
buildings are held in place by caulks/sealants - silicone products may be used
without any mechanical means of fastening.  This can be clearly defined as an
adhesive application since the silicone material is being used to bond the
glass and metal surfaces together. On the other hand, it also serves as a
caulk/sealant because it prevents the passage of gases, liquids, or solids
through the joint.  This report would include the use of silicone materials in
this application as a sealant, primarily because it has appreciable volume.<P>

The report will initially describe and analyze caulk/sealant chemicals and
will include resins, elastomers, and additives.  After the discussion of
caulk/sealant product forms, application markets will be covered followed by a
review of technologies.  R & D/new products, standards and testing, and
application equipment are the next sections of the report.  Industry structure
including distributors, competitive situation, major producers/suppliers,
marketing, acquisitions/divestitures, and pricing comprise the next section. The report concludes with a discussion of government regulations/environmental concerns, company profiles, and the Appendix.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

Within this framework of definitions and categories, information was initially
gathered from suppliers' trade literature to ensure that their products were
properly represented in terms of properties, tradenames, and suggested or
actual applications.<P>

Further correspondence and telephone conversations with major caulk/sealant
suppliers sorted out any lingering discrepancies.<P>

A thorough literature search was the next step in the information-gathering
process. Sources included trade magazines, U.S. government and trade
association data, and a variety of contacts within the industry developed over 20 years.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Some of the sources included:<P>

<UL>--- Chemicalweek<BR>
--- Chemical & Engineering News<BR>
--- Chemical Marketing Reporter<BR>
--- Kirk-Othmer, Encyclopedia of Chemical Technology<BR>
--- U.S. International Trade Commission<BR>
--- Department of Commerce<BR>
--- Chemcyclopedia (American Chemical Society)<BR>
--- Adhesives Age<BR>
--- Adhesives & Sealant Council</UL><P>

Following development of preliminary market estimates, further refinements of
values were accomplished via contacts with major companies involved in the
caulk\sealant business which included: Ashland Chemical, Bostik, Courtaulds
Aerospace, DAP Inc., Dow Chemical, Dow-Corning, Eastman Chemical, Essex
Specialty Products, H.B. Fuller, GE Silicones, Gibson-Homans, BF Goodrich,
Loctite, Macklanburg-Duncan, Morton International, Thiem Automotive (National
Starch & Chemical), Pecora Corp., Koch/Protective Treatments (Koch/PTI), Rhone-
Poulenc, Rohm & Haas, Schnee-Morehead, 3M Company, Tremco, Uniroyal, and
Wacker Silicones.<P>

In regard to market information and forecasts, all dollar values (1992 and
1997) are given in constant 1992 dollars - with no provision for inflation for
1997 values.  All growth rates are annually compounded based on constant 1992
dollars.  Tradenames appear in upper case letters.<P>


