<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-143  POLYMERIZATION TECHNOLOGY TRENDS & MARKETS FOR
UPGRADED COMMODITIES: HIGHLIGHTING POLYOLEFINS AND POLYSTYRENE
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-143  POLYMERIZATION TECHNOLOGY TRENDS & MARKETS FOR
UPGRADED COMMODITIES: HIGHLIGHTING POLYOLEFINS AND POLYSTYRENE
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>MELVIN SCHLECTER</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The objective of this report is to provide a basic understanding of the events
surrounding the "commodity polymer revolution," highlighting polyolefins and
polystyrene.<P>

Reasonable market estimates and forecasts along with a proposed timetable are
included.  The impact of these new products on conventional commodity and
specialty products will be highlighted.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING STUDY</B><P>

Although growth across many plastics sectors has leveled, polymer modification
is experiencing renewed vigor.  In fact, some recent catalyst developments can
now be considered as important as the breakthroughs of the 1950s and 1960s.
And now, these new commodities are competing in both new and old market
niches.<P>

This study therefore clarifies the changing scenario and assesses the
realistic commercial penetration possibilities of these new materials over the
next five years.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The materials covered in this report include polyethylenes, polypropylenes and
polystyrene.  Each of these, of course, has distinct commercial sub-
categories, but not all of them are involved in the "polyolefin/polystyrene
revolution."<P>

This new comprehensive BCC study examines the major technological advances
occurring in metallocene-based single site catalysts, as well as Spherilene,
Unipol, and Catallog processes.  To "round-out" the scenario, random
polypropylene copolymers, bimodals, LDPEs, and Dow's octene/LLDPEs are also
discussed.<P>

There are several problems that became evident and are dealt with in this study:<P>

          -   What constitutes a "new" product?<P>
          -   What is meant by "new materials"?<P>
          -   How do we deal with the complexity of
              technology, especially in terms of relating
              polymer structure to properties and eventually to
              potential applications?<P>
          -   How may we break through the reticence of
              many key companies to discuss details of their
              technologies and potential markets?<P>
          -   How best may we separate the hype in the trade
              press from the realities of the marketplace?<P>
          -   What's really the truth when intense competition
              among producers often cause them to be critical
              of the efforts of other companies?<P>
          -   How do we know what the future holds for these
              products when none is available in "commercial"
              quantities as of the end of the third quarter of
              1993?<P>
          -   How do we best asses the long term impact of
              these new products to the year 2000 and beyond?<P>

As to the definition of a commercial product, there appear to be five levels:<P>

<UL>          -   in development<BR>
          -   trial runs completed (pilot plant)<BR>
          -   some product available for testing (lab)<BR>
          -   product being evaluated by users<BR>
          -   product actually been sold<P></UL>

None of the "new" products have reached the last stage.<P>

Therefore, a "new" product will be defined as one which should reach full
commercialization by 1998.  Clearly, several are already being tested by
processors/potential end-users.  When discussed in a general context, these
will be called "new polyolefins/polystyrenes" and will be cited as such in the
report (without the quotation marks).<P>

Additional concepts dealt with in this report:<P>

<LI>   Those new materials which include only polyethylenes and polypropylenes
will be called "polyolefins" (without quotation marks).  When discussing the
various new polyethylenes, the term "polyethylenes" will be used (without
quotation marks).<P>

<LI>   Many of the markets which will be targeted by these new products are
discrete, while others are very broad, e.g., specialty films.  Indeed, the
one area of agreement is that the initial impact will be in "specialty"
markets in the $1+ 20c/lb area.  A major bone of contention is if and when
these new polymers will impact commodity markets.<P>

<LI>   The market data will be segmented into definable and non-definable areas.
Actual estimated values will appear in the former and not the latter.

<LI>   The "polyolefin/polystyrene revolution" is real and follows on the heels of
other important milestones:<P>

<UL>1930s  ... development of high-pressure process for polyethylene<P>
   1950s  ... discovery of stereoregular polyolefins (isotactic
        polypropylene)<P>
    1970s  ... development of low-pressure gas phase technology for
        linear polyolefins (UNIPOL)<P>
   1990s ... development of metallocene single-site catalysis<P></UL>

<LI>   There have been other non-polymerization catalyst technology-related
advances in the polymer field such as polymer alloys/blends and development of
thermoplastic elastomers (TPEs).<P>

<LI>   It must be stressed that metallocenes are not the only "new" catalyst
polymerization technologies, e.g., Himont's CATALLOY and SPHERILENE,
bimodals, Union Carbide's UNIPOL II, and others.  All of these and
others will be covered in this report.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

Information was gathered from suppliers' trade literature followed by an
exhaustive analysis of trade magazines from 1990 to the present.<P>

Technical texts were consulted to clarify important points, and extensive
interviews were conducted with major polyolefin/polystyrene producers.<P>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Some of the sources included:<P>

<UL>Chemicalweek<BR>
 Chemical & Engineering News<BR>
      Chemical Marketing Reporter<BR>
      Modern Plastics<BR>
     Plastics Technology<BR>
     Plastics News<BR>
   Rubber & Plastics News<BR>
  Rubber Technology - 3rd Edition (Maurice Morton)<BR>
    Encyclopedia of Chemical Technology (Kirk-Othmer)<BR>
   Encyclopedia of Polymer Science & Engineering (Wiley)<P></UL>

Extensive interviews were conducted with the major companies involved,
including: Amoco, Chisso, Dow, Exxon, Fina, Himont, Mobil, Phillips, Quantum,
Union Carbide, etc.<P>

In regard to market information, all values were given in pounds because
prices for the new polyolefins/polystyrenes are widely divergent and
continually changing.<P>

Growth rates for these materials were excluded because they were all starting
from a base volume of zero.  Tradenames (and catalytic process names) appear
in upper case letters.<P>

