<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-147  POST-POLYMERIZATION POLYMER MODIFICATION:
MATERIALS & APPLICATIONS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-147  POST-POLYMERIZATION POLYMER MODIFICATION:
MATERIALS & APPLICATIONS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I> MELVIN SCHLECTER
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The objective of this study is to provide a market analysis of
polymer property modifiers developed via post-polymerization
processes as opposed to those properties imparted by new catalyst
polymerization technologies.<P>

Market estimates and forecasts will be included for selected major
property modifiers, and their polymer substrates. Major
applications will be discussed in qualitative terms. Important
property modifier suppliers, their product lines, and other
important factors that impact this market will be discussed, and
estimated sales and market shares provided where feasible.<P>


<B>REASONS FOR DOING STUDY</B><P>

There is continuing interest in upgrading both commodity and
specialty polymers.  Recently, there has been a great deal of
activity in catalyst polymerization technologies as one means of
improving polymer properties.<P>

Another major technique to upgrade polymers is via post-polymerization methods during compounding. Improved property modifiers
along with the introduction of new modifying materials has prompted
interest which led to this study.<P>

Impact modifiers, reinforcing agents, compatibilizers, coupling
agents, and nucleating/clarifying agents were selected for this
study because of their advantageous affects on polymer properties.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This study describes the chemistry, properties and markets for
structural modifiers, use with specific polymer substrates and
overall applications.  The report provides current estimates and
five-year forecasts by property modifier types in both pounds and -
dollars.<P>

The difference between modifiers and additives is not really clear.
Modifiers are generally used to change a specific property, while
additives add a characteristic to a polymer.  The latter normally
includes: flame retardants, colorants, heat/light stabilizers, etc.<P>

This report also covers polymer alloys/blends since they are
involved with compatibilizers and are often impact modified.<P>

The polymer property modifiers quantitatively reviewed in this
study are:<P>

<UL> - impact modifiers<BR>  
-  nucleating agents<BR>
-  compatibilizers    <BR>
-  reinforcing agents<BR>
  -  coupling agents<P></UL>

Where feasible, volumes of polymers modified will be included.<P>


<B>EXCLUSIONS</B><P>

Since any additive to a polymer is, in essence, a modifier because
it affects properties of the substrate, this field (modifiers/-
additives) is very large.<P>

Generally, this report will focus on thermoplastics, although some
discussion of thermosets will be included.  By necessity, the
following will also be generally excluded:  antiblockers,
fragrances, fillers, plasticizers, antioxidants, light & heat
stabilizers, catalysts, flame retardants, colorants, blowing agents
and processing aids.<P>

The confusing issue of how to deal with elastomer-containing
thermoplastics vs. various polymer alloys/blends is a thorny one.
For the purposes of this study, where the elastomeric component is
significant, the product will be considered a polymer alloy/blend
and will be generally excluded.<P>

Whereas the elastomeric portion is not significant, it will be
viewed as a modifier of a thermoplastic and thus included.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

Information was gathered from supplier's trade literature followed
by a detailed analysis of trade magazines from 1990 to the present.<P>

Technical texts were consulted to clarify important points, and
extensive interviews were conducted with major polymer property
modifier producers and suppliers.<P>



<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Some of the sources included:<P>

<UL>--- Chemicalweek<BR>

--- Chemical & Engineering News<BR>

--- Chemical Marketing Reporter<BR>

--- Modern Plastics<BR>

--- Plastics Compounding<BR>

--- Plastics Technology<BR>

--- Plastics News<BR>

--- Rubber & Plastics News<BR>

--- Rubber Technology - 3rd Edition (Maurice Morton)<BR>

--- Encyclopedia of Chemical Technology (Kirk-Othmer)<BR>

--- Encyclopedia of Polymer Science & Engineering (Wiley)<P></UL>

Extensive interviews were conducted with individuals and major
companies involved in all aspects of polymer modification.<P>

All dollar values are in current 1993 dollars, "millions" are often
abbreviated as "MM," growth rates are annually compounded, and
tradenamed products appear in upper-case letters.<P>

The terms "alloy," "blend," and "alloy/blend" are used
interchangeably.<P>

