<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-150 PLASTIC ENCLOSURES IN PORTABLE ELECTRONICS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-150 PLASTIC ENCLOSURES IN PORTABLE ELECTRONICS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>HOWARD KIBBEL
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY OBJECTIVES</B><P>

One may argue that the trend toward miniaturization in the
electronics industry was consumer-initiated or it was manufacturer-initiated.  However, there is no doubt that the availability of
portable electronic devices has led to a resurgence of the U.S.
electronics industry after a few years of slowed growth in the late
1980s to early 1990s.<P>

This study analyzes the emergence of the portable electronics
device as a major factor in the electronics industry, with
particular attention shown to the impact that such devices have had
on the type and volume of plastics employed vis-*-vis larger,
stationary devices, or in some cases, how new products created new
markets for plastics which did not exist before the 1990s.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This study is basically a review and analysis of plastics resins
and electronics products.  It is a supplemental version of a study
done in 1992 on plastics enclosures for electronics products.
However, that study did not discuss in detail the types of products
targeted in this study, namely such portable electronic devices as:<P>

<UL> - laptop/notebook/pen-based computers<BR>
-  navigational devices<BR>
-                  video games<BR>
- telephones & other communications devices<BR>
-  calculators<BR>
-                   musical keyboards<BR>
- blank media<BR>  
-            data organizers<BR>
- audio/visual products<BR>  
- watches and other timepieces<BR>
- spell checkers<BR>
            -      translators<P></UL>

The plastics involved span the spectrum from the commodity to
engineering-type resins.  The primary materials included are ABS,
polycarbonate, polystyrene, PVC, modified polyphenylene oxide and
blends of those resins. Cost/performance comparisons of these
competing resins rationalize the material selection process for
specific products.  Our conclusions are based on discussions with
the primary players in resin supply (including compounders) and the
plastics molders which serve the electronics industry.  The key
plastics molding technologies are highlighted with specific
emphasis on trends in such technologies arising from the different
requirements for portable devices compared to stationary devices.<P>


In addition to the data on resins and products, we have identified
the major issues which impact on the use of portable electronics,
namely electronic industry macroeconomics, the influence of
foreign-based manufacture, shielding regulations and standards and
consumer attitudes toward electronic products which provide the
functionality of stationary devices but offer the portability
characteristics of convenience and flexibility.<P>

Current and forecast demand data are presented for the years 1990,
1992, 1993 and 1998.  These data points represent the most accurate
description of the current demand situation, and provide an insight
into the short-term growth that can be expected.  Five-year average
annual growth rates are calculated for the period 1993-1998.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

The research for this study included personal contacts with key
participants among the OEM electronics manufacturers, resin
suppliers, molders and compounders.  The information gathered from
these primary sources formed the basis for our estimates of current
resin usage in portable electronics enclosures.  Their forecasts
for future demand of resin and product were merged with our
analysis of electronics trends and the probabilities of resin
consumption to meet future demand.  Our final analyses and
projections are based on a combination of a consensus among the
primary contacts and our understanding of the impact of trends from
a historical perspective.<P>

In addition, we reviewed secondary sources of information such as
trade publications, trade associations, company literature,
industry conferences and on-line databases to supplement our
understanding of the markets, applications and trends affecting the
resins used in portable electronics devices.  Finally,
macroeconomic data and import/export data from government sources
yielded information on the importance of portable devices within
the overall electronics industry and the influence of foreign-based
manufacture on U.S. demand.<P>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

Although the market for portable electronic devices is changing
rapidly with the constant introduction of new, enhanced products,
the plastic materials which will be employed during the next five
years are relatively constant.  This study will benefit plastics
resin suppliers and electronic industry officials (e.g., materials
design engineers, plastics purchasing agents and new product
design/marketing teams) by providing information on the important
trends in plastic material preferences for enclosures and the logic
behind those preferences.<P>

The portable segment of the electronics industry is the driving
force for overall electronics growth.  These products are
increasingly gaining in share versus stationary devices as the
market is expanding beyond the traditional commercial office,
laboratory and manufacturing environments into consumer/home
applications.  Consequently, our attention is drawn to this segment
which will dominate the electronics industry into the next century.<P>



<B>RELATED BCC STUDIES</B><P>

BCC has followed the electronics industry closely due to its
importance both in terms of its size and its rapidly-changing
technologies, particularly as they impact on plastics usage.  For
example, a series of EMI/RFI shielding studies has been done
periodically for the last twenty years, the most recent published
earlier this year.  In addition, there are several recently-
published studies, cited below, which analyze the technologies,
materials and markets for electronics products.<P>


<UL>GB-066U  EMI/RFI Shielding, 9/93<BR>

GB-128R  Thick Film/Thin-Film Impact on Microelectronics, 7/93<BR>

G-138    Video Communications into the 21st Century, 10/92<BR>

P-064U   Plastics in Business Machines, 10/92<BR>

GB-160   Magnetic/Opto-Magnetic Storage: Media
         & Materials, 9/92<BR>

GB-156   Advanced Electronic Packaging Systems
         Technology Through 2000, 8/92<BR>

P-099R   Plastics in ESD Applications, 1/92<P></UL>


