<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-152:NEW DIRECTIONS IN STYRENIC-BASED PLASTICS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-152:NEW DIRECTIONS IN STYRENIC-BASED PLASTICS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Melvin Schlechter</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The objective of this study is to provide an analysis of styrene
polymers in terms of current and forecasted markets.  New
developments in styrene polymers have expanded usage in existing
and new applications.  The competitive scenario between styrene and
other polymers will be described, in addition to competition among
styrene polymers themselves.  In some cases, styrenics have
replaced non-plastic materials.<P>

Important suppliers of styrene polymers, their product lines, and
other important factors that impact the market will be discussed.<P>


<b>REASONS FOR DOING STUDY</B><P>

Styrene polymers have evolved as more than commodity polystyrene. 
Even with ABS reaching "commodity status" with volumes over one
billion pounds and prices in the $.80/lb. range, other styrene
polymers have become successful and important commercial products. 
Styrene polymers have found use in almost every plastic application
and are available as rigid thermoplastic films, sheet, foams, and
elastomers.  Furthermore, styrene polymers form an important part
of alloys/blends and thermoplastic elastomers (TPEs).<P>

Styrene polymers comprise about 12% of total U.S. resin sales; 15%
of thermoplastic sales; and have equivalent volumes with
poly-propylene -- the third ranking resin behind polyethylene and
PVC.<P>

Styrene polymer growth rates should keep pace with both
polyethylenes and PVC although aggregate styrene polymer prices are
higher than polyethylene, PVC, and polypropylene.<P>


<b>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

The term "styrene polymers" is somewhat subjective.  For the
purposes of this report, it will include the following:<P>

<UL>-  polystyrene (injection molded, extruded, thermoformed,
   film/sheet, and foam/expanded)<P>
-  ABS (acrylonitrile-butadiene-styrene)<P>
-  SAN (styrene-acrylonitrile)<P>
-  SMA (styrene-maleic anhydride)<P>
-  SBC (styrene butadiene block copolymers -- also called
   thermoplastic styrenes)<P>
-  HIPS (high-impact polystyrene)<P>
-  PPO/HIPS (polyphenylene oxide/high-impact polystyrene
   alloy/blend)<P>
-  PC/ABS (polycarbonate/ABS alloy/blend)<P>
-  Other ABS alloys/blends (PVC, PBT, polyurethanes, etc.)<P>
-  Other styrenic alloys/blends.<P></UL>

Styrene-butadiene rubbers will be excluded from this study.<P>

The following styrenic applications will be covered in this report:<P>

<UL>-  adhesives<BR>
-  appliances<BR>
-  automotive<BR> 
-  building/construction<BR>
-  business machines<BR> 
-      consumer & other
electronics<BR>
-  food packaging<BR> 
-  furniture/furnishings<BR>
-  housewares<BR>
-  lawn/garden equipment & tools<BR>
-  medical<BR> 
 -      other packaging<BR>
-  polymer modifiers<BR> 
-      sport/leisure<BR>
-  telecommunications<BR>
 -  toys/novelties</UL><P>


<b>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

A comprehensive review was undertaken of: literature relating to
styrene polymers, their applications and technology, and
significant new developments; supplier trade literature; texts and
monographs, etc.<P>

Following the collection and analysis of this information,
extensive interviews were conducted with many producers, suppliers,
and compounders of styrene polymers.<P>


<b>ACRONYMS</B><P>

The following acronyms will be used throughout the report:<P>

<UL>ASA  -    acrylic-styrene-acrylonitrile<BR>
ABS  -    acrylonitrile-butadiene-styrene<BR>
EPS  -    expandable PS<BR>
HIPS -    high-impact polystyrene<BR>
OPS  -    oriented polystyrene<BR>
PPO  -    polyphenylene oxide<BR>
PS   -    polystyrene<BR>
SAN  -    styrene-acrylonitrile<BR>
SBCs -    styrene-butadiene block copolymers<BR>
SMA  -    styrene-maleic anhydride<BR>
SPS  -    syndiotactic polystyrene</UL><P>

Trade names will appear in upper case letters, volumes are in
millions/MM of pounds/lbs., and dollar values in 1994 dollars. 
Growth rates are annually compounded.  Alloys and/or blends will be
noted as "alloys/blends," and Dow Chemical will be written as
either "Dow" or "Dow Plastics."<P> 

