<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-154: PLASTICS DISPOSABLES MARKETS:
UPDATE
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-154: PLASTICS DISPOSABLES MARKETS:
UPDATE
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Howard Kibbel
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The U.S. market for plastics disposables is growing steadily as the
population increases, the need to reduce the costs of healthcare
persists, and Americans continue to seek convenience and protection 
for their products.<P> 

We demonstrate in this study that disposable products, chiefly
composed of plastics, can contribute to our society's need for
quality healthcare at an affordable price, while concurrently
supporting efforts to improve the environment.  Other markets also
benefit from the trend toward disposables and away from reusable
products as being consistent with the desire to better handle the
disposal of waste.  The study reveals that the use of plastics will
accomplish that objective.<P> 

<b>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P> 

This study targets those plastic products viewed as "disposable,"
in the sense that the products are single use or at least complete
their function in a relatively short time.  Arbitrarily, we have
selected a period of one year as the maximum useful use in our
definition of disposable.<P>

The dominant plastic materials used in these applications are the
thermoplastics, particularly the commodity plastics of
polyethylene, polypropylene, polystyrene, and PVC.  The study,
however, identifies and quantifies all thermoplastics employed in
packaging and non-packaging, including engineering resins. 
Plastics consumption is analyzed as intramaterial and intermaterial
competition (i.e., versus such non-plastics as glass, paper, and
metal in terms of cost and performance).<P>   

The study follows the resins consumed in disposables from the resin
suppliers and distributors, through the grades of resin used,
competing materials, and identifies the major manufacturers and
suppliers.  These data are presented in a framework of current
trends in materials, markets, and technologies within the structure
of the several industries which consume plastics disposables.<P>  

In addition to a description of resins used in typical products,
our analyses include specific product offerings, particularly where
material selected, product design, or manner of use represents an
innovation versus traditional consumption.<P>  

Since these products are consumed in a highly regulated
environment, an important aspect of the study is a discussion of
the regulatory agencies and specific regulations which determine
the types of resins which may be used, the role of safety and
health issues, and the potential liabilities associated not only
with resins but also with product design in terms of performance in
use.<P>

A significant amount of time was spent on the medical and
pharmaceutical sector of many reasons. That sector is different
from general packaging markets due to the extensive amount of
regulation involving medical packaging and medical disposable
devices. In addition, there is more activity in terms of innovative
product designs and material enhancement (e.g., adaptability to
sterilization techniques). Among the materials consumed in medical
disposables, plastics are the leaders. Finally, the
medical/pharmaceutical market represents a major outlet for
plastics disposables, both in terms of dollars and pounds.<P>

The reader should note that not all medical (or other) disposables
are accounted for in the demand tables. There are niche markets for
which no data are available, for example, plastic stirrers. While
there may be several such markets, we believe that their
contribution to total plastics demand in disposables is negligible.
Likewise, there may be some small markets excluded where non-
plastics materials are consumed. Again, however, we believe such
markets would not alter the total demand reported by material
(where applicable) or the relevant growth rates.<P>  

The demand data shown represent current (1994) levels through the
next ten years.  Data are keyed to the years 1993, 1994, and 1999
with average annual growth rates calculated for the 5-year 1994-
1999 time period.<P>

<b>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

In addition to telephone interviews with resin suppliers,
fabricators, and end users, we have gathered data and insight from
trade associations and government agencies.  These contacts have
been supplemented with information obtained from the technical and
marketing trade publications and relevant data from previous BCC
studies.<P>

All BCC estimates of future demand are based on our interpretation
of the information received from an extensive list of industry
specialists.  Thus, we believe this study represents an accurate
view of the current and future demand for disposables.<P>

<b>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

The U.S. market for plastics disposables is now a 19 billion pound
business, which accounts for 30% of total plastics demand. 
Plastics consumption in the U.S. healthcare industry for disposable
products alone grew at 9.7% annually from 1987 to 1992, compared to
a 2.2% growth rate for plastics overall during that period. 
Medical/pharmaceutical disposables now account for about 2% of
total U.S. plastics consumption.  This combination of widespread
use and fast growth confirms the importance of such products for
the future of the plastics industry.<P>

This study is intended for use by companies along the chain of
distribution of disposable products -- resin suppliers,
distributors, and fabricators, plus companies which participate in
the packaging and non-packaging industries with nonplastics
products.  Our comprehensive analyses identify those resins which
will have the greatest future success in healthcare products and
the reasons for their use versus competing plastics and non-
plastics.<P>


<b>RELATED BCC REPORTS</B><P>

This study is the latest in a series of business opportunity
reports published by BCC covering plastics and competitive
materials used as packaging and in disposable products.  Listed
below are some of the more recent studies which may be of value in
supplementing the reader's interest.<P>


<UL>P-152--New Directions in Styrenic-Based Plastics,         8/94<P>

P-216--State of Plastics Recycling,                       6/94<P>

P-137--Barrier & Selective Barrier Plastic-Based
          Materials & Structures for Packaging,              2/94<P>

P-213--Ubiquitous Markets for Blister & Skin Packaging 
          & Their Competitors,                               3/93<P>

P-212--Plastics in Medical & Pharmaceutical Disposables,  1/93<P>

GB-159--Infusion Products, Devices and Materials          7/92<P>

C-045N--Medical Diagnostic Kits and Products,              7/92<P>

P-133--PVC & the Environment,                             4/92<P>

P-130--The Flexible Pouch Business,                       1/92<P></UL>

