<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-155: PLASTICS IN AUTOMOTIVE EXTERIORS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-155: PLASTICS IN AUTOMOTIVE EXTERIORS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Melvin Schlechter
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The objective of this study is to provide an analysis of the automotive 
exterior plastics market in terms of current and forecasted values.<P> 


<b>REASONS FOR DOING THE STUDY</B><P>

The automotive exterior plastics market is fiercely competitive, with plastics 
vying with aluminum and steel.  Intraplastic competition is also a major 
factor in this market, especially with "plastic intensive" autos.  
Thermoplastics are also competing with thermosets for body panels, fenders and 
other major exterior parts.<P> 


<b>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This report will cover automotive exterior plastic parts segmented by major 
types such as commodity thermoplastics, engineering resins, thermosets, 
polymer alloys/blends, TPEs, etc. Applications will be broken down into the 
following categories: body panels, bumper systems, fenders, transparent auto 
exteriors and housings and other exterior parts.  Over 20 more detailed 
applications will be covered, including roofs, doors, bumper beams and covers, 
radiator grilles, side trim, hoods, wheel covers, etc.<P> 

Other critical topics covered will include processing, marketing, research and 
development activities, new production introductions, recycling, major product 
lines of suppliers, etc.<P> 

Report also includes statistics and data on major resins used in automotive 
exterior.<P> 


<b>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

A comprehensive review was undertaken of trade and technical literature 
relating to auto exterior plastics, specific applications, technologies, new 
developments, etc.  Included in this review were supplier trade literature, 
texts and monographs.<P> 

Following collection and analysis of this information, extensive interviews 
were conducted with polymer and elastomer producers and suppliers. 

All dollar values are in 1994 dollars, "millions" are often abbreviated as 
"MM", growth rates are annually compounded and trade-named products appear in 
upper case letters.<P>

<CENTER><HR WIDTH=50% SIZE=4>
<H3>TABLE OF CONTENTS</H3></CENTER>
<PRE>
INTRODUCTION . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .  xii
     STUDY GOALS AND OBJECTIVES. . . . . . . . . . . . . . .  xii
