<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-157: THE CHANGING PLASTICS DISTRIBUTING/
COMPOUNDING BUSINESS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-157: THE CHANGING PLASTICS DISTRIBUTING/
COMPOUNDING BUSINESS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>Howard Kibbel
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<B>STUDY OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This study reviews the various methods by which plastics are
transported to the plastic processors.  The dominant companies in
this distribution of plastics are the compounders, of which there
are independents, toll-type, proprietary and custom, the resin
companies, and the plastics processors themselves.  These companies
add value to the resin through application of additives and
reinforcing agents.<P>  

The other major category includes the distributors, which generally
do not add value to the resin but rather repackage large quantities
(e.g. truck-load) into smaller quantities for the processors.  By
1994, more than $1 billion worth of resins passed through
distributors.  The study also includes the activities of other
types of companies which may or may not actually handle the resins
but rather manage the contract paperwork between buyers and
sellers.  These companies are alternatively identified as jobbers,
brokers or resellers.  These same companies may also be
compounders, distributors or recyclers.<P>


<b>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>

This study follows the path of plastics from original producer
through the end user, which may be a custom or proprietary
processor or an OEM.  In addition, the equipment and additives used
by the compounders are highlighted since they play a vital role in
compounder activity.<P>  

The study includes key trends in technology, services, material
handling and the economics related to compounding.  A major section
is the identification and profiles of the major participants in the
compounding/distribution industry.  Finally, data track the
estimated movement of resin via the different types of companies
from resin producer to end user.<P>

The demand data are presented for 1993, 1994 and 1999, with a five-
year growth rate calculated for 1994-1999.  These data are
generally in pounds and dollars so that comparisons can be made
with the rest of the plastics industry.<P>


<b>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

The primary data gathered for this study involved telephone contact
with the major compounders, distributors and other types of
resellers, machinery companies, and recyclers.  This primary
research was reinforced with information gathered from the main
trade association for the plastics distributors, trade journals and
past BCC studies.<P>


<b>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY</B><P>

One of the key trends in the plastics industry is that an
increasing amount of resins are being modified to "tailor" them to
specific applications.  Resin companies are limiting their sales to
major customers, leaving the small- and medium-sized processors to
deal with compounders and distributors, particularly for specialty
resins and alloys/blends.  By the year 2000, it is estimated that
30% of plastics processors will be serviced by distributors.  In
addition, the growth of the plastics recycling industry will impact
directly on the relationship between resin producers and their
customers, create new demand for compounding equipment
manufacturers, and boost interest in compounding technology.<P>  

It is apparent that the compounding/distribution industry is
becoming a major force in the resin-to-processor distribution
channel.  Thus, our review of this industry's progress should be of
interest to resin producers, machinery suppliers and additive
suppliers.<P> 


<b>RELATED BCC STUDIES</B><P>

BCC has followed the plastics compounding industry for many years,
specializing in resin technologies that have influenced
compounding.  Listed below are some of the more recent studies done
on that industry as well as those which track trends in recycling
and disposability -- which are of interest to the recyclers.<P>

<UL>P-154--Plastics Disposables Update,                         11/94<P>

P-216--State of Plastics Recycling,                         7/94<P>

P-124--New Olefin Resins Via New Polymerization &
        Compounding,                                         9/91<P>

P-070R--The Value Added in Plastics Compounding,             2/90<P>

P-208--Upgraded Commodities Compete with Engineering
        Resins                                              5/89<P></UL>


