<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>P-210  THE CHANGING COMPETITIVE PALLET MARKET

</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-210  THE CHANGING COMPETITIVE PALLET MARKET</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>PHILIP S AUCHINCLOSS
</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

Business Communications Company first studied the pallet business in the early
1970s.  Here in 1992 we return to this marketplace, and we chronicle the trends over
the past and over the coming years in terms of the materials and the markets for this
product.<P>


<B>STUDY GOAL AND OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The pallet has been a fundamental part of the materials handling business since the
1930s.  In the early days the wooden pallet, nailed or bolted together, was the
industry standard, and competition for shares of this growing business was waged
among the various softwood and hardwood unit fabricators.  After World War II the
metal pallet, made of roll formed and welded steel, was developed in response to
the need for units with greater load-bearing strength and toughness.  Yet the metal
pallet was expensive to produce, and it also added extra transportation costs to
shipments due to its extreme weight.<P>

The pallet business had a new entrant in the late 1960s - namely the structural foam
molded plastic pallet.  These units were promoted on the basis of their light weight,
unified construction, durability, and resistance to moisture and other environmental
conditions.  Their relatively high price (relative to the wood pallet standard) was
justified on the grounds that they would extend the life-cycle of a pallet to 20 or more
trips.  And in the current era when concern for the environment is paramount in
materials decision-making, the plastic pallet is well-positioned since it can so easily
be recycled.<P>

This concern over the role of pallets in materials handling as the environmental
impact becomes a critical decision variable has recently let to increased interest in a
fourth pallet option -  namely, the paperboard pallet which is extremely light weight
and easy to dispose of.  Corrugated or honeycomb construction is used to provide
adequate strength along with light weight.<P>

How will the pallet business fare in the 1990s and which materials are likely to gain
or lose market share as cost, performance, and environmental requirements evolve
over the coming years?  Are there new materials or new combinations of materials
on the horizon?  How will the pallet industry structure change in the 1990s?  These
are some of the issues that we address in this comprehensive analysis of the inter-
material competition and evolving industry dynamics in the pallet segment of the
materials handling industry.<P>

The objectives of this study include the determination and re-examination of:<P>

<UL>

<LI> the overall size of the wood, metal, plastic and paperboard pallet<P>
<LI> industries in units and dollars<P>

<LI> the overall profitability of the pallet industry and its component parts<P>

<LI> the industry structure<P>

<LI>the future growth potential of each of the four segments and why<P>

<LI> the changes manufacturers may have to make to compete successfully  in the next decade<P>

<LI> the importance of environmental issues on the pallet industry<P>

<LI> changing leasing opportunities<P>

<LI> the import/export trends to determine future competitive threats or
            opportunities.<P></UL>

<B>REASONS FOR DOING THIS STUDY</B><P>

The reason for examining the pallet business is to assess an industry which enjoyed
a successful growth record as established by the wooden pallet industry since the
1930's. This group of small business entrepreneurs has successfully grown at a
rapid pace that has exceeded the economy's growth.  The questions of concern are:<P>

<UL>"Can the industry maintain the established pace?"<BR>

            "What will the future bring?"<BR>

            "For which material?"<BR>

            "For which application?"<BR>

            "What are the important market niches, if any?"<P></UL>


<B>CONTRIBUTION OF THE STUDY AND FOR WHOM</B><P>

This study is intended to serve as an aid to pallet producers in their continual
assessment of evolving material preferences and growth prospects by sub-market.  it
is also intended as a guide to future purchasing decisions on the part of pallet end-
users in that we attempt to provide a consensus of the emerging economics (e.g.;
buy vs. lease) and environmental advantages of the various pallet types by materials
and construction.<P>

This study provides insights into the wood, metal, plastic, and paperboard pallet
industry on such issues as future growth, competitive economics, major producers in
key segments, and new technology.<P>

The study is intended for pallet manufacturers interested in determining how their
company fits into the industry, calculating their market share, and learning what may
happen to the industry during the next decade.  Manufacturers will also be interested
in customer perceptions of their products and how they compare with alternate pallet
forms.<P>

Suppliers to the pallet industry will find this report helpful in determining the
potential market size for their products, whether it be machinery or raw materials.
Also, data are presented on a state-by-state basis which is helpful in allocating sales
effort and locating customers.<P>

Pallet users will find the report useful in determining what kinds of pallets to acquire
or lease.  Users can use this report as a reference point for pallet applications that
may fit their particular needs.<P>


<B>SCOPE AND FORMAT</B><P>


This report describes the pallet industry which consists of unit-load platforms
capable of handling loads of up to 4,000 pounds in transit.  These pallets are
intended to be lifted by fork lift trucks.  The four main material types - wood, plastic,
metal and paperboard - are covered in this report.  The report includes domestic
data on the United States only.<P>

The report begins with an overview of the pallet industry showing units, dollars and
prices.  It then moves on to industry structure which identifies shipments by pallet
type, geographic location of the industry, key manufacturers and industry
economics.
Future industry growth is followed by chapters on technology, markets, inter-pallet
competition and international trade.  The purpose is to describe key factors affecting
the future of the pallet industry.<P>


<B>METHODOLOGY</B><P>

The research methodology used is a combination of telephone interviews with key
industry personnel and experts and a careful search of published data from the U. S.
Government and other sources.  The number of people contacted are shown in the
table below.<P>

<CENTER>TABLE A - TELEPHONE INTERVIEWS</CENTER> 
<UL>Description - Number interviewed<P> 
Pallet users - 41<BR> 
Wood pallet manufacturers - 31<BR> 
Plastic pallet manufacturers - 20<BR> 
Industry experts - 14<BR> 
Paperboard pallet producers - 7<BR> 
Metal pallet producers - 4<BR>
TOTAL interviewed - 117<P>
Telephone interviewing was conducted in 1991 and 1992.<P></UL>


<B>INFORMATION SOURCES</B><P>

Information sources included data obtained from industry experts, producers of
pallets, and their customers.  In addition, information was obtained from government
and trade association data where available.  Sources are footnoted throughout the
report.<P>

