<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>
P-211  PREMIUM POLYMERICS IN BIOMEDICAL APPLICATIONS
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="bccLogoSmall.gif" ALT="LOGO">
<CENTER><H2>P-211  PREMIUM POLYMERICS IN BIOMEDICAL APPLICATIONS
</H2>

<HR><P>

<I>YATIN THAKORE</I><BR>
PROJECT ANALYST
<P>

<H3><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H3>
</CENTER>

Polymers, or plastics to most of us, have enormously changed the modern health-care
system. Consider this:<P>

<DD><LI>Today, nearly one out of ten Americans use plastic contact lenses to correct
  vision.<P>

<DD><LI>Everyday, roughly 45,000 Americans with kidney failures get hooked up to
  artificial kidneys, wherein  polymeric membranes  remove life-threatening
  toxins from blood.<P>


<DD><LI>Some 7,000 angiography procedures are performed in the U.S. each day, to
  determine patients' cardiovascular health. A thin plastic tube, known as a
  catheter, is snaked in a patient's blood vessel, and radio-opaque dye is
  injected. Computer enhanced X-ray pictures allow the physician to examine
  blood flow.<P>

<DD><LI>When blood flow is obstructed, catheters equipped with tiny inflatable
  balloons are usually used to dislodge the plaque deposits obstructing the
  arteries.  Such modern medical plumbing often prevents expensive and more invasive
  surgery.<P>


<DD><LI>When major surgery is called for, surgeons perform bypass surgeries, often
  using synthetic plastic blood vessels to bypass damaged large arteries. When
  bypassing damaged coronary arteries, more often than not, it is a membrane
  oxygenator, with a polymeric membrane, that takes over the function of lungs
  during these open-heart procedures.<P>

It is hard to believe that these medical devices and procedures that we take for
granted today, were not commonplace 30 years ago. Materials, and particularly
synthetic polymers, more than anything else, have been instrumental in improving the
quality of our health-care.<P>



<B>OBJECTIVES</B><P>

This study examines a very important segment of the health-care market. It analyzes
technology, current status and future trends of high value-added polymeric raw
materials, and their end products, used in biomedical devices. Polymers have
revolutionized health-care in the past 25 years, and are continuing to improve the
detection and treatment of diseases.<P>

The principal objective of this study is to provide detailed analysis of the various
market segments of high value-added polymeric raw materials. Raw material could be
either virgin polymer, compounded polymer, or polymer processed into value-added
formats, such as membranes, depending upon the starting material for the end user.<P>

Additionally, this study is intended to provide its readers with an overall
understanding of the end use markets for the value-added raw materials. We have
tried to bring out the complex interplay between innovation, market requirements,
regulations and technology.<P>



<B>TARGETED AUDIENCE</B><P>

This study covers detailed analysis of high value-added raw materials, their end use
markets and technologies. It is intended to assist executives of companies involved
with the manufacture or distribution of medical devices, specialty medical polymers
or formatted raw materials, to understand trends, technologies and  the marketplace.
It would also be helpful to prospective entrants in this business, analysts, venture
capitalists, investors and industry watchers.<P>



<B>WHAT IS HIGH VALUE-ADDED?</B><P>

This study is about "High Value-Added Polymeric Raw Materials." How do we define
high value-added?<P>

We mentioned that not only polymer resins but also formatted raw materials such as
membranes will be covered in this report. We'll define very high value-added
polymeric raw materials as those which cost more than $5/lb in the resin form and
more than $50/lb  in a formatted form. Rationale behind this definition is discussed
in detail in the OVERVIEW chapter.<P>


<B>SCOPE OF THIS STUDY</B><P>

This study focuses on High value-added polymeric raw materials in the
biomedical area. For convenience, we'll refer to these as "premium polymerics" in
the remainder of this report. Premium polymerics could be in one of the following
forms:<P>

<DD>1. Resin/powder/liquid/solution/paste of polymer/prepolymer/monomer, often compounded with other additives<BR>
<DD>2. Membranes: flat sheet or hollow fibers<BR>
<DD>3. Beads<BR>
<DD>4. Sheet/rod<P>

To qualify as a premium polymeric, the basic form (#1) should sell, for at least $5 per
pound, whereas the formatted forms (#2 to #4) should sell for at least $50 per pound,
at a wholesale level.<P>

This study analyzes various market segments of premium polymerics. It estimates the
present usage and forecasts future growth. It also describes end use markets, relevant
technologies and regulatory procedures.<P>

The emphasis is on the domestic U.S. market, which is analyzed in detail. However,
there is an international section which does discuss overall world market and trends.<P>



<B>WHICH END USES ARE COVERED?</B><P>

"Biomedical" is a very broad term and often assumes different interpretations. It is
therefore important to clarify the biomedical end use markets targeted in the study.<P>

The scope of this study is outlined in TABLE 1. The shaded left column shows the
applications covered in this study. All applications are for human use only. Veterinary
uses are excluded.<P>

Moreover, this study is limited to end products wherein the polymer will be required
to interact with tissues or body fluids. Therefore, applications such as packaging,
syringes, garments, furniture and instrument casings will not be considered. These
are medical applications, but not biomedical ones, as defined here. Most of these use
commodity type plastics.<P>

Next, we only consider products used as implants or for therapy or treatment.
Therefore passive barrier devices such as condoms, face-shields and gloves are not
included. Products such as diapers are also excluded. Contact lenses, however are
included in our application since they do treat a medical problem of poor vision.<P>

Finally, in the remaining applications, the criteria of high value-added is applied. This
eliminates applications such as blood bags and most medical tubings made up of
commodity type plastics. Catheter use, is however included. Catheter manufacturers
often use premium polymerics as their starting raw material to impart special
properties such as enhanced bio-compatibility or lubricity.<P>


 <CENTER><B>                           TABLE 1</CENTER></B><BR>

<CENTER><B>SCOPE OF THIS STUDY</CENTER></B><P>

